[Golden Bear]] for Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n|[[Teddy Award]] for Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|Baltimore International Black Film Festival\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n|Audience Award for Best International Short Film\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|The Camargo Foundation\n|''Save the Rex''\n|Travel Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Africa Movie Academy Award]]\n|''On Monday of Last Week''\n|Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Pratt Institute]]\n|''On Monday of Last Week''\n|Mellon Research Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[International Short Film Festival Oberhausen]]\n|Oberhausen Film Seminar\n|Featured Artist\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Goethe-Institut]] Vila Sul Salvador-Bahia\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Artist-in-Residence\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Cobo Center]] Marquee Video Art Series\n|''Intermittent Delight''\n|[[John S. and James L. Knight Foundation]]\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Wattis Institute for Contemporary Arts]]\n|''Akosua Adoma Owusu: Welcome to the Jungle''\n|The Westridge Foundation\n|Won\n|\n|}\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" ;\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Ajube Kete''\n| writer, director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n|2006\n|''Tea 4 Two''\n|director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Intermittent Delight''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n|2008\n|'' Revealing Roots''\n|actress, director, producer\n|-\n| 2008\n|''Boyant: A Michael Jordan in a Speedo is Far Beyond the Horizon''\n| actress, producer\n|-\n| 2009\n|''Me Broni Ba''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2010-11\n|''Drexciya''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2012\n|''Split Ends, I Feel Wonderful''\n| director, producer\n|-\n| 2013\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n| writer, director, producer\n|-\n| 2015\n|''Bus Nut''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2016\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2018\n|''On Monday of Last Week''\n| writer, director, producer\n|-\n| 2018\n|''Mahogany Too''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2019\n|''Pelourinho: They Don\u2019t Really Care About Us''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2019\n|''White Afro''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n|in production\n|''Black Sunshine'' (feature film)\n|writer, director, producer\n|-\n|}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*Owusu, Akosua Adoma, and Adwoa Adu-Gyamfi. ''Me broni ba''. New York, NY: [http://store.cinemaguild.com/nontheatrical/product/2358.html Cinema Guild] (2009).\n*Len\u00e9 Hole, Kristin. ''Film Feminisms: A Global Introduction''[https://books.google.com/books?id=QCBtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT251&lpg=PT251&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+ajube+kete&source=bl&ots=CmIGbxV1hi&sig=1Xu5fDlyidV9DEGNea_QiwmgA-Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiWp4qJ2LPfAhXpdN8KHZzBA0Q4ChDoATAMegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20ajube%20kete&f=false] (2018).\n*Kelly, Gabrielle. ''Celluloid Ceiling: Women Film Directors Breaking Through'' (2018) \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=0U07DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&lpg=PT29&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+triple+consciousness&source=bl&ots=hFyyC3hfGH&sig=1aX2-gvVrGK4SJLO-VJe0vDXPAU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiioPahlMDfAhXkQd8KHRkPBP04KBDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20triple%20consciousness&f=false]\"\n*Johnson, Elizabeth. ''Female Narratives in Nollywood Melodramas'' (2016) \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=x4vpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+%22triple+consciousness%22&source=bl&ots=kPgX7rGQqM&sig=-jf8thF22VdkHG0EysB4w6QzpNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj63fv1x_LeAhXKslkKHbGdDrc4KBDoATAIegQIARAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20%22triple%20consciousness%22&f=false]\", p.&nbsp;113.\n*Ellerson, Beti. ''Gaze Regimes: Film And Feminisms In Africa'' (2015) [https://books.google.com/books?id=3DZjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50&lpg=PT50&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+%22triple+consciousness%22&source=bl&ots=aytupH0_7B&sig=wy3JoGmo6R_CTYn29Tz3OMNcKLU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj63fv1x_LeAhXKslkKHbGdDrc4KBDoATACegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20%22triple%20consciousness%22&f=false]\"\n*Agyeman, Erica. \"[http://iraaa.museum.hamptonu.edu/store/Details.cfm?ProdID=166&category=7 Akosua Adoma Owusu: Exploring 'Threeness]\", ''The International Review of African American Art'' 24.3 (2013), 11-13.\n*Kendall, Nzingha, \"[http://muse.jhu.edu/article/525956 Commentary: Haunting in Akosua Adoma Owusu's Short Experimental Films]\" (2013). ''Black Camera''\n*Mask, Mia, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=dX-kvyCFVF0C&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=%2522erie%2522+%252B+%2522akosua+adoma+owusu%2522&source=bl&ots=QegbYJKSwt&sig=wyr3PkHKmmeVe93_u19GpIhJ-h4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiEhKKj2PneAhVSnlkKHaVFDIoQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ%23v=onepage&q=%2522erie%2522%2520%252#v=onepage&q=%2522erie%2522%2520%252&f=false Contemporary Black American Cinema: Race, Gender and Sexuality at the Movies]\" (2012).\n*Dovey, Lindiwe. ''African Feminist Engagements with Film'' (2012) \"[http://www.agi.ac.za/sites/default/files/image_tool/images/429/feminist_africa_journals/archive/16/fa16_full_pub.pdf]\", p. 18-23.\n*Nelmes, Jill. ''Introduction to Film Studies'' (2012) \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=AnGrAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT620&lpg=PT620&dq=%22erie%22+%2B+%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22&source=bl&ots=Ru8VWIEuNU&sig=CcxTEgi6i6U4UHLF09PE4_pZkK0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjGrIju2PneAhVp0FkKHakABu04ChDoATABegQIBBAB#v=onepage&q=%22erie%22%20%2B%20%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22&f=false]\"\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://obibinipictures.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3113362/?ref_=tt_ov_dr/ Akosua Adoma Owusu] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*[https://mubi.com/cast/akosua-adoma-owusu/ Akosua Adoma Owusu] on [[MUBI]]\n*[[Ghanaian Filmmakers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owusu, Akosua Adoma}}\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Akosua Adoma Owusu''' (born January 1, 1984) is a Ghanaian-American filmmaker, producer and cinematographer whose films and installation work have screened worldwide in prestigious film festivals, museums, galleries, universities and microcinemas since 2005. Her films often address the collision of identities. Interpreting the notion of \"[[double consciousness]],\" coined by sociologist and civil rights activist [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] to define the experience of black Americans negotiating selfhood in the face of discrimination and cultural dislocation, Owusu aims to create a third cinematic space or consciousness. In her works, feminism, queerness, and African identities interact in African, white American, and black American cultural environments.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Akosua Adoma Owusu talks about triple consciousness|url = https://www.artforum.com/interviews/akosua-adoma-owusu-talks-about-triple-consciousness-79725|website = ArtForum|access-date = 2019-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nickelodeon.org/an-interview-with-akosua-adoma-owusu-2/|title = Akosua Adoma Owusu on Triple Consciousness|website=nickelodeon.org|access-date = 2018-02-02|first = Alison|last = Kozberg}}</ref>\n\nShe is a Visiting Assistant Professor of Non-Fiction and Expanded Cinema at the [[Pratt Institute]] in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Pratt Institute|url =https://www.pratt.edu/faculty_and_staff/bio/?id=MkJSZ1F0T2RlNlhKY1ExVlkrMGRkUT09|website = Pratt Institute|access-date = 2018-11-18|first = Pratt|last = Institute}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Akosua Adoma Owusu\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = <!-- use the image's pagename; do not include the \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and do not use brackets-->\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name = <!-- Akosua Adoma Owusu -->\n| birth_date = January 1, 1984<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. -->\n| birth_place = [[Alexandria, Virginia]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality = Ghanaian, American\n| residence = Ghana, New York\n| education = [[University of Virginia]] and [[California Institute of the Arts]]\n| alma_mater = \n| known_for = [[Kwaku Ananse (film)]] (2013), Me Broni Ba (2009) and [[Drexciya (2010 film)|Drexciya (film)]] (2011)\n| notable_works = Reluctantly Queer (2016), On Monday of Last Week (2018)\n| style = Film Artist, Producer\n| movement = Feminism\n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| awards = John Simon Guggenheim Foundation, 2015 Creative Capital Foundation, 2015 MacDowell Colony Fellow, 2013 [[Africa Movie Academy Award]], 2013\n| elected = \n| patrons = \n| memorials = \n| website = http://akosuaadoma.com/home.html<!-- {{https://vimeo.com/user5596421}} -->\n| module = \n}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nBorn to Ghanaian parents on January 1, 1984,<ref>{{Cite web|title = On The Verge: Producer - Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = http://thestylehq.com/on-the-verge-akosua-adoma/|website = The Style HQ|access-date = 2016-04-11}}</ref> Owusu was raised in the immigrant community in Alexandria, [[Virginia]]. She is the youngest of three siblings to Grace and Albert A. Owusu, Sr. Owusu holds master's degrees in Film & Video and Fine Art from [[California Institute of the Arts]] and received her BA in Media Studies and Studio Art with distinction from the University of Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|title = University of Virginia Arts Magazine - Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = https://magazine.arts.virginia.edu/stories/hoos-for-art-adoma|website = University of Virginia|access-date = 2015-12-09}}</ref> She began her career as a post-production assistant on [[Chris Rock]]\u2019s [[HBO]] documentary \u201cGood Hair\u201d (2009). Soon thereafter she transitioned to making her own short, experimental films.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fowler In Focus: The Art of Hair in Africa|url = https://www.fowler.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Art-of-Hair-Press-Release-_Final_rev-4-17-15.pdf|website = Fowler Museum UCLA|access-date = 2015-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nShortly after graduating from CalArts in 2008, Owusu was a featured artist at the 56th Robert Flaherty Film Seminar programmed by renowned critic and film curator Dennis Lim.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dennis Lim|url = http://dennis-lim.com|website = Dennis Lim|access-date = 2016-02-18}}</ref> Named by ''[[Indiewire]]'' as one of the six [[Experimental film|Avant-Garde]] Female Filmmakers Who Redefined Cinema,<ref>{{Cite web|title = 6 Avant-Garde Female Filmmakers Who Redefined Cinema|url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/6-avant-garde-female-filmmakers-who-redefined-cinema-20151007|website = Indiewire|access-date = 2016-02-18|first = Aubrey|last = Page}}</ref> and one of [[The Huffington Post]]\u2018s Black Artists: 30 Contemporary Art Makers Under 40 You Should Know,<ref>{{Cite web|title = 30 Black Artists Under 40 You Should Know|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/26/black-artists-under-40-contemporary-painters-sculptors-performance-race-representation-art_n_2725639.html|website = The Huffington Post|access-date = 2016-02-18}}</ref> Akosua Adoma Owusu was a 2013 [[MacDowell Colony]] Fellow and a 2015 [[Guggenheim Fellow]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2015 Guggenheim Fellows|url = http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|access-date = 2015-10-13}}</ref> On February 26th 2020, Owusu received the [[Lincoln Center]] Award for Emerging Artists bestowed by [[Film at Lincoln Center]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lincoln Center Awards For Emerging Artists|url = https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Flash-BE-MORE-CHILL-Producer-Jennifer-Ashley-Tepper-and-More-Receive-2020-Emerging-Artist-Awards-at-Lincoln-Center-20200227|website = Broadway World|access-date = 2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n''Indiewire'' describes Owusu's shape-shifting film style:\n\n<blockquote> Trafficking in the \u201ccomplex contradictions\u201d of blackness, displacement and memory, Owusu seamlessly transitions between experimental cinema, fine art and African tradition in order to create avant-garde films that question the nature of identity.</blockquote>\n\nHer \u201cwarring consciousness\u201d as she describes it, becomes the point of departure for her film ''Me broni ba'' (my white baby). Using hair as a medium of culture, she examines African and African-American identities and ideologies in an effort to resolve their differences.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Akosua Adoma Owusu\u2019s Triple Consciousness|url = http://africanwomenincinema.blogspot.com/2010/11/akosua-adoma-owusus-triple-consciousness.html|website = African Women in Cinema|access-date = 2010-11-23}}</ref> [[Ed Halter]], one of the founders of Light Industry in Brooklyn, listed ''Me Broni Ba'' as one of 2010's top ten films in [[Artforum]] magazine. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/201008/ed-halter-26416|title=Akosua Adoma Owusu / Top Ten|website=artforum.com|access-date=2010-12-18|first = Ed|last = Halter}}</ref>\n\nShe has produced award-winning films including ''Reluctantly Queer'' and ''[[Kwaku Ananse (film)|Kwaku Ananse]]''. In 2013, ''Kwaku Ananse'' received a Golden Bear nomination at the Berlinale and won the 2013 [[Africa Movie Academy Award]] for the West African nation of [[Ghana]] in the Best Short Film category. ''Kwaku Ananse'' also participated in the [[Acad\u00e9mie des Arts et Techniques du Cin\u00e9ma]] - C\u00e9sar Golden Nights Panorama of Best Short Films, a program<ref>[http://www.academie-cinema.org/the-golden-nights/golden-nights/archives/panorama/edition,2013.html Kwaku Ananse - French Cesar Academy]</ref> that selects notable short films awarded that year. \n\nHer film ''Reluctantly Queer'' (2016) produced in collaboration with Dr. Kwame Edwin Otu,<ref>[https://woodson.as.virginia.edu/people/profile/eko3q University of Virginia - Carter G. Woodson Institute]</ref> an Assistant Professor of African American and African Studies at the [[University of Virginia]] was nominated for the Golden Bear and Teddy Award at the 2016 Berlin International Film Festival.<ref>[https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/2016/02_programm_2016/02_Filmdatenblatt_2016_201605738.php#tab=filmStills Berlinale, Berlin International Film Festival]</ref> The film eventually aired as part of the American Documentary [[POV (TV series)]] ''Post-Colonial Queer''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Post-Colonial Queer|url = https://www.pbs.org/pov/watch/postcolonialqueer/|website = American Documentary|access-date = 2020-01-21}}</ref> on [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS).\n\nIn 2018, Owusu produced \"On Monday of Last Week\",<ref>{{Cite web|title = Another Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie Story Is Being Adapted Into a Film |url = http://www.essence.com/2016/06/13/akosua-adoma-owusu-chimamanda-ngozi-adichie-short-story|website = Essence.com|access-date = 2016-10-18|language = en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web |url=https://trueafrica.co/article/meet-the-ghanaian-filmmaker-adapting-a-chimamanda-ngozi-adichie-novel-to-film/| title=Meet the Ghanaian filmmaker who\u2019s adapting Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie |website = True Africa.co|access-date = 2016-06-22|first = Priscilla|last = Debar}}</ref> a film adaptation of a short story in celebrated author [[Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie|Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's]] collection, \"The Thing Around Your Neck.\" The film, which starred American actress [[Karyn Parsons]] best known for her role as [[Hilary Banks]] on the [[NBC]] [[sitcom]] [[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]], secured a nomination at the 2017 African Movie Academy Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|title = On Monday of Last Week Interview: With Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = http://www.elle.co.za/akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = elle.co.za|access-date = 2017-07-17|first = Dimeji|last = Alara}}</ref> The film went on to screen at the Fowler Museum,<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Triple Consciousness of \u2018On Monday Last Week\u2019|url = https://femmagazine.com/the-triple-consciousness-of-on-monday-last-week-2018/|website = FEM Magazine|access-date = 2018-05-17|first = Jemina|last = Garcia}}</ref> ICA London <ref>{{Cite web|title = Daughters of Africa Screen Narratives: Archive Revelations VII|url = https://archive.ica.art/whats-on/daughters-africa-screen-narratives-archive-revelations-vii|website = ICA London|access-date = 2018-06-13|first = June|last = Givanni}}</ref> and 25th New York African Film Festival co-presented by Film at Lincoln Center.<ref>[https://www.filmlinc.org/films/selbe-one-among-many/ Film Society of Lincoln Center]</ref>\n\nIn an interview with South Africa's ''[[Elle (magazine)]]'', in 2015, Owusu said \"I began filming in Ghana as a way to find a place in my Ghanaian heritage.  I often refer to myself as a Ghanaian-American, but I do consider myself to be an American filmmaker of Ghanaian descent. When I am in America, I feel very Ghanaian and when I\u2019m in Ghana, I feel more American. I started traveling to Ghana with my friends from America to help me with the trauma of dealing with blackness both in Africa and in the African diaspora. My love for Africa was informed by romantic ideas about the continent as a home awaiting my arrival. Filming in Ghana, forms part of this journey.\" <ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = http://www.elle.co.za/meet-akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = Elle Magazine South Africa|access-date = 2015-09-12|first = Ntombenhle|last = Shezi|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170527223655/http://www.elle.co.za/meet-akosua-adoma-owusu/|archive-date = 2017-05-27|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Owusu exhibited work in ''Cusp: Works on Film & Video by [[Kevin Jerome Everson]] & Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the Luggage Store Gallery. Called the \u201cintimate and the ideal realization of the vision of a valuable genius\",<ref>{{Cite web|title = Whip My Hair|url = http://www.sfweekly.com/sanfrancisco/whip-my-hair/Content?oid=2180113|website = SF Weekly|access-date = 2016-02-18|first = Hiya|last = Swanhuyser}}</ref> this show included ''Revealing Roots'', a silent re-enactment of one of the most dramatic scenes from the television version of Alex Haley's ''Roots'' combining found footage and scenes that star Owusu along with other African actors.\n\nHer films are produced under her production company Obibini Pictures LLC.\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\n\n*2020: ''Akosua Adoma Owusu: Welcome to the Jungle'' at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] Documentary Fortnight <ref>{{Cite web|title = MoMA Documentary Fortnight |url = https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/6387|website = Museum of Modern Art|access-date = 2020-02-08|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Akosua Adoma Owusu: Welcome to the Jungle'' at [[Contemporary Arts Center (New Orleans)]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = Contemporary Arts Center New Orleans|url = https://cacno.org/welcometothejungle|website = Contemporary Arts Center New Orleans|access-date = 2020-02-03}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Akosua Adoma Owusu: Welcome to the Jungle'' at [[Wattis Institute for Contemporary Arts]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = Wattis Institute for Contemporary Arts|url = https://wattis.org/view?id=687|website = CCA Wattis Institute|access-date = 2019-04-10}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Between Three Worlds: Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at [[REDCAT]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = REDCAT|url = https://www.redcat.org/event/between-three-worlds-films-akosua-adoma-owusu|website = REDCAT(Roy and Edna Disney/CalArts Theater)|access-date = 2018-12-28}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Triple Consciousness: Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Yerba Buena Center for the Arts]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Yerba Buena Center for the Arts|url = http://www.sfcinematheque.org/screenings/triple-consciousness-films-by-akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = SF Cinematheque|access-date = 2019-04-11}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Sala de Video: Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[S\u00e3o Paulo Museum of Art]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Video room: Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = https://masp.org.br/en/exhibitions/video-room-akosua-adoma-owusu|website = Museu de Arte de S\u00e3o Paulo|access-date = 2019-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Afro-Atlantic Histories|url = https://www.e-flux.com/announcements/204006/histrias-afro-atlnticas/|website = Museu de Arte de S\u00e3o Paulo|access-date = 2018-09-12}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Triple Consciousness: Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Institute for Contemporary Art, Richmond]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Institute for Contemporary Art|url = https://icavcu.org/films/short-film-showcase-akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = Institute for Contemporary Art(ICA)|access-date = 2019-03-14}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Screening: Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Screening: Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = https://mcachicago.org/Calendar/2019/01/Screening-Akosua-Adoma-Owusu|website = MCA Chicago|access-date = 2018-12-27}}</ref>\n*2018: ''Triple Consciousness'' at BOZAR, [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = Triple Consciousness: Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/147402-triple-consciousness|website = BOZAR Cinema|access-date = 2018-05-11}}</ref> \n*2018: ''African Twilight'' at the [[Bowers Museum]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = African Twilight |url = https://www.bowers.org/index.php/component/yendifevents/event/1735-kwaku-ananse-screening-and-live-performance-by-baba-the-storyteller|website = African Twilight|access-date = 2018-09-15}}</ref> \n*2018: ''Fragments of a Dream'' at the [[McNay Art Museum]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fragments of a Dream |url = https://www.mcnayart.org/exhibitions/upcoming/fragments-of-a-dream|website = McNay Art Museum|access-date = 2018-06-15}}</ref> \n*2018: ''Screening and Conversation with Director Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Fowler Museum at UCLA]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = On Monday of Last Week|url = https://www.fowler.ucla.edu/events/screening-conversation-monday-last-week-akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = Fowler Museum|access-date = 2018-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Akosua Adoma Owusu - John Simon Memorial Foundation|url = https://www.gf.org/news/events/akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|access-date = 2018-04-17}}</ref> \n*2017: ''Akosua Adoma Owusu and Bus Nut'' at the [[Atlanta Contemporary Art Center]];<ref>{{Cite web|title = Atlanta Contemporary Art Center|url = https://atlantacontemporary.org/exhibitions/akosua-adoma-owusu|website = Atlanta Contemporary|access-date = 2017-06-05}}</ref> \n*2016: ''Making Africa: Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at [[Centre de Cultura Contempor\u00e0nia de Barcelona]] <ref>{{Cite web|title =  New Voices of African Cinema - Akosua Adoma Owusu |url = http://www.cccb.org/en/participants/file/akosua-adoma-owusu/223091|website = Centre de Cultura Contempor\u00e0nia de Barcelona|access-date = 2016-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title =  Making Africa - Akosua Adoma Owusu |url = http://www.cccb.org/en/activities/file/new-voices-of-african-cinema-akosua-adoma-owusu/223059|website = Centre de Cultura Contempor\u00e0nia de Barcelona - Akosua Adoma Owusu|access-date = 2016-04-21}}</ref>  \n*2016: ''Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at [[Tabakalera]] <ref>{{Cite web|title =  Tabakalera |url = https://www.tabakalera.eu/en/akosua-adoma-owusu|website = Tabakalera|access-date = 2016-04-06}}</ref> \n*2016: ''Encuentro con Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Castilla y Le\u00f3n]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Encuentro con Akosua Adoma Owusu |url = http://www.laguiago.com/evento/encuentro-akosua-adoma-owusu-musac/|website = MUSAC|access-date = 2016-09-15}}</ref> \n*2016: ''L'\u00e9v\u00e8nement Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Centre Georges Pompidou]]<ref>{{Cite web|title =  L'\u00e9v\u00e8nement Akosua Adoma Owusu |url = https://www.centrepompidou.fr/cpv/resource/c45yK9a/rx5XKMR|website = Centre Pompidou|access-date = 2016-09-03}}</ref> \n*2016: ''Triple Consciousness'' at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]] <ref>{{Cite web|title =  Triple Consciousness: Films of Akosua Adoma Owusu |url = https://www.cinemahtx.org/3889-2/|website = Houston Cinema Arts Society|access-date = 2016-11-25}}</ref>\n*2016: ''Dreamlands: Immersive Cinema and Art, 1905\u20132016'' at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dreamlands: Afrofuturism - Whitney Museum |url = https://whitney.org/Events/Afrofuturism|website = Whitney Museum of American Art|access-date = 2016-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Dreamlands: Pain Revisited - Whitney Museum|url = https://whitney.org/Events/PainRevisited|website = Whitney Museum of American Art|access-date = 2016-12-12}}</ref> \n*2015: ''Modern Mondays: An Evening with Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = An Evening With Akosua Adoma Owusu - MoMA |url = https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/1621|website = Museum of Modern Art|access-date = 2015-12-27}}</ref> \n*2015: ''Existential Crisis'' at the [[Rochester Art Center]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = Rochester Art Center|url = http://rochesterartcenter.org/exhibition/akosua-adoma-owusu/|access-date = 2015-12-11}}</ref>\n*2015: ''America Is Hard to See'' at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = America is Hard To See|url = https://whitney.org/Exhibitions/AmericaIsHardToSee|website = Whitney Museum of American Art|access-date = 2015-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 24700 News from CalArts|url = http://blog.calarts.edu/2015/04/20/calartians-named-2015-guggenheim-fellows/|website = California Institute of the Arts|access-date = 2015-07-09}}</ref>\n*2015: ''The Art of Hair in Africa'' at the [[Fowler Museum at UCLA]] <ref>{{Cite web|title = Fowler in Focus: The Art of Hair in Africa|url = https://www.fowler.ucla.edu/exhibitions/fowler-focus-art-hair-africa/|website = Fowler Museum at UCLA|access-date = 2015-11-10}}</ref>\n*2015: ''Two Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at Art and Practice <ref>{{Cite web|title = Off-Site Program: In Conversation: Njideka Akunyili Crosby and Akosua Adoma Owusu|url = https://hammer.ucla.edu/programs-events/2015/09/off-site-program-in-conversation-njideka-akunyili-crosby-and-akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = Hammer Museum|access-date = 2015-09-27}}</ref> in association with the [[Hammer Museum]]\n*2015: ''Do/Tell'' at the [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Do/Tell |url = https://icaphila.org/exhibitions/do-tell-erin-bernard-heather-hart-rachelle-mozman-and-akosua-adoma-owusu/|website = ICA Philadelphia|access-date = 2015-09-29|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2014: ''Prospect.3: Notes for Now'' New Orleans Triennial<ref>{{Cite web|title = Prospect.3 |url = https://www.artforum.com/inprint/issue=201501&id=49428|website = artforum.com|access-date = 2015-01-13|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2013: ''Films by Akosua Adoma Owusu'' at the [[Moderna Museet]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = CinemAfrica  - Moderna Museet|url = https://www.modernamuseet.se/stockholm/sv/aktiviteter/cinemafrica-filmfestival/|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2012: ''Fore'' at the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fore - Smithsonian Libraries|url = https://siris-libraries.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1546O9V395595.39270&profile=liball&source=~!silibraries&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!1025889~!1&ri=2&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=akosua+adoma+owusu&index=GW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=2|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2012: ''The Bearden Project'' at the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Beardenmania |url = http://gailgregg.com/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/Beardenmania.pdf|website = ARTnews|access-date = 2012-06-01|language = en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = The Bearden Project |url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/bearden-project/oclc/841590034|website = WorldCat|access-date = 2012-12-20|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2011: ''VideoStudio: Changing Same'' at the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = VideoStudio: Changing Same |url = https://www.studiomuseum.org/exhibition/videostudio/changing-same|access-date = 2010-11-12|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2011: ''Quadruple Consciousness'' at the [[Vox Populi (art gallery)]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Quadruple Consciousness |url = http://voxpopuligallery.org/exhibitions/quadruple-consciousness/|website = voxpopuligallery.org|access-date = 2011-01-06|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2009: ''30 Seconds Off an Inch'' at the [[Studio Museum in Harlem]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = A Beating Heart of Social Import |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/11/arts/design/11inch.html|website = NY Times|access-date = 2009-12-10|language = en-US}}</ref>\n*2009: ''Me Broni Ba'' at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] Documentary Fortnight <ref>{{Cite web|title = MoMA Documentary Fortnight |url = http://press.moma.org/wp-content/press-archives/PRESS_RELEASE_ARCHIVE/DocMonth_Release.pdf|website = Museum of Modern Art|access-date = 2009-02-01|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Permanent collections ==\n\nHer work is included in the permanent collections of the Whitney Museum of American Art,<ref>[http://collection.whitney.org/artist/14667/AkosuaAdomaOwusu Whitney Museum Collections]</ref> the [[Centre Georges Pompidou]], and the [[Fowler Museum]].\n\n== Rex Cinema ==\n\nIn 2013, Akosua Adoma Owusu launched a global crowdfunding initiative to \u2018Save the Rex\u2019. The Rex Cinema <ref>{{Cite web|title = Filmmaker hoping to rejuvenate Ghana's dilapidated old cinemas|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AuEwUkOmsno&feature=c4-overview&list=UU86dbj-lbDks_hZ5gRKL49Q|website = AFP news agency|access-date = 2013-10-27|language = en-US}}</ref> is one of Ghana's oldest cinema houses. During a time of political insecurity in Ghana in the 60s, 70s and 80s, there was a decline in the Arts. All of the cinema houses closed down in the wake of military coups and curfews. Owusu sought to save Rex Cinema for the purpose of preserving cinema houses.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Nana Darkoa Sekyiamah |title=Akosua Adoma Owusu: From \u2018Kwaku Ananse\u2019 to \u2018Bus Nut\u2019 |url=https://thisisafrica.me/lifestyle/akosua-adoma-owusu-kwaku-ananse-bus-nut/ |publisher=This Is Africa |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |date=April 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Dr. Kwame Edwin Otu |title= Akosua Adoma Owusu Saving Rex Cinema |url=http://www.design233.com/oldhtml/works/akosua_adoma_owusu_rex_cinema.html|publisher=Design233 |accessdate=2018-12-13 |date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Owusu developed a screenplay based on her global campaign to Save the Rex Cinema in Ghana at the Camargo Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Camargo Foundation |url = http://camargofoundation.org/programs/partnership-programs/jerome-foundation/art-matters/2016/akosua-adoma-owusu/ |website = The Camargo Foundation - Save the Rex|access-date = 2016-10-09|first = Akosua Adoma|last = Owusu}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Save the Rex |url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5734222/?ref_=nm_knf_i4|website = IMDb|access-date = 2018-10-10|first = Akosua Adoma|last = Owusu}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''[[The Guardian]]'' announced that Akosua Adoma Owusu is working on a part-real life, part-fictionalized feature film about her campaign to restore Accra's historic Rex cinema.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Accra at 60: concrete heads and colonial questions in Ghana's capital |url = https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2017/mar/06/accra-60-independence-birthday-parade-arts-colonisation-ghana|website = The Guardian|access-date = 2017-03-09|first = Alice|last = McCool}}</ref>\n\n== International recognition ==\n\nIn 2015, Two films directed and produced by Akosua Adoma Owusu were critics' picks <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artforum.com/picks/id=56161|title=Akosua Adoma Owusu / Critics' Picks|website=artforum.com|access-date=2016-02-18|first = Kate|last = Sutton}}</ref> in [[Artforum]] magazine.\n\nIn 2016, Owusu's film ''Reluctantly Queer'' was one of critics\u2019 best films of 2016 in [[Sight & Sound]], a monthly film magazine published by the [[British Film Institute]] (BFI)<ref>{{Cite web|title = The best films of 2016. |url = http://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2016|website = Sight & Sound Magazine|access-date = 2016-12-20|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Owusu was named by Britain's Royal African Society as their Human of the Week <ref>{{Cite web|title = What\u2019s Trending #014: Human of the Week|url = http://whatsonafrica.org/whats-trending-014/|website = Whatsonafrica.org|access-date = 2016-08-07|language = en-US}}</ref> and by South Africa's ''[[Elle (magazine)]]'' as one of 50 incredible women.\n\nIn 2017, she was named by ''[[Dazed]]'' magazine as one of ten experimental filmmakers tackling the world's big topics.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ten experimental filmmakers tackling the world\u2019s big topics|url = http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/34976/1/filmmakers-experimenting-with-big-subjects|website = Dazed.com|access-date = 2017-03-09|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Owusu was commissioned by the [[Cobo Center]] to produce a video installation along Jefferson and Washington avenues in downtown Detroit, Michigan during Black History Month.\n\nIn 2018, she was awarded an artist-in-residence by the [[Goethe-Institut]] Vila Sul in Salvador-Bahia along with celebrated British installation artist and filmmaker [[Isaac Julien]].\n\nIn 2019, Owusu's film ''White Afro'' (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|title = White Afro|url = https://www.locarnofestival.ch/en/pardo/program/archive/2019/film?fid=1111691&eid=72&|website = Locarno Film Festival|access-date = 2019-08-30|language = en-US}}</ref> received the Premio Medien Patent Verwaltung AG prize in Pardi di domani (Leopards of Tomorrow) section of the [[Locarno Festival]] in Switzerland. The winning film will be subtitled in three central European languages. This subtitling can be inserted on film, video or DVD format.\n\nIn 2019, Owusu's film ''Pelourinho: They Don't Really Care About Us'' was one of critics\u2019 best films of 2019 in [[Sight & Sound]] magazine published by the [[British Film Institute]] (BFI)<ref>{{Cite web|title = The best films of 2019. |url = https://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/sight-sound-magazine/polls-surveys/annual-round-ups/best-films-2019-all-votes#BeccaVoelcker|website = Sight & Sound Magazine|access-date = 2019-12-20|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Award\n!Work\n!Category\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2005\n|Virginia Film Festival\n|''Ajube Kete'' \n| Ken Jacobs Award for Best Experimental Short Film\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|Berlin International Film Festival\n|''Me Broni Ba/My White Baby''\n|Berlinale Talent Campus\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|[[California Institute of the Arts]]\n|''Good Hair''\n|[[Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences]] Grant \n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|Detroit Docs\n|''Intermittent Delight''\n|Most Progressive Filmmaker Award\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|Mexico International Film Festival\n|''Me Broni Ba/My White Baby''\n|Silver Palm Award\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Athens International Film and Video Festival]]\n|''Me Broni Ba/My White Baby''\n|Best Documentary Short\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Chicago Underground Film Festival]]\n|''Me Broni Ba/My White Baby''\n|Best Documentary Short\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Robert J. Flaherty]] Film Seminar\n|Work\n|Featured Artist\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|Real Life Documentary Festival\n|''Me Broni Ba/My White Baby''\n|Special Jury Mention, Best Short Film\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|Black Maria Film Festival\n|''Drexciya''\n|Jury's Citation Prize\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|African Film Festival, Tarifa\n|''Drexciya''\n|Special Jury Mention\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Expresi\u00f3n en Corto International Film Festival]]\n|''Drexciya''\n|Best Experimental Short\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Focus Features]] Africa First\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n|Production Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Creative Capital]] Foundation\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Film/Video Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|Art Matters Foundation\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n|Post-Production Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|Ann Arbor Film Festival\n|''Split Ends, I Feel Wonderful''\n|Most Promising Filmmaker Prize\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n|[[Golden Bear]] Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Africa Movie Academy Award]]\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n|Best Short Film\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Acad\u00e9mie des Arts et Techniques du Cin\u00e9ma]]\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n|Best Short Film of the Year\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Arte]] International Prize\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Development Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|[[MacDowell Colony]] Fellowship\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Screenwriting Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Production Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|Association Cin\u00e9mas et Cultures d'Afrique\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n|Special Jury Mention\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|[[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]]\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|[[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Tribeca Film Institute]]\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Tribeca All Access Development Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n|[[Golden Bear]] for Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n|[[Teddy Award]] for Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|Baltimore International Black Film Festival\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n|Audience Award for Best International Short Film\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|The Camargo Foundation\n|''Save the Rex''\n|Travel Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Africa Movie Academy Award]]\n|''On Monday of Last Week''\n|Best Short Film\n|Nominated\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Pratt Institute]]\n|''On Monday of Last Week''\n|Mellon Research Grant\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[International Short Film Festival Oberhausen]]\n|Oberhausen Film Seminar\n|Featured Artist\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Goethe-Institut]] Vila Sul Salvador-Bahia\n|''Black Sunshine''\n|Artist-in-Residence\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Cobo Center]] Marquee Video Art Series\n|''Intermittent Delight''\n|[[John S. and James L. Knight Foundation]]\n|Won\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Wattis Institute for Contemporary Arts]]\n|''Akosua Adoma Owusu: Welcome to the Jungle''\n|The Westridge Foundation\n|Won\n|\n|}\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" ;\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Ajube Kete''\n| writer, director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n|2006\n|''Tea 4 Two''\n|director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Intermittent Delight''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n|2008\n|'' Revealing Roots''\n|actress, director, producer\n|-\n| 2008\n|''Boyant: A Michael Jordan in a Speedo is Far Beyond the Horizon''\n| actress, producer\n|-\n| 2009\n|''Me Broni Ba''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2010-11\n|''Drexciya''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2012\n|''Split Ends, I Feel Wonderful''\n| director, producer\n|-\n| 2013\n|''Kwaku Ananse''\n| writer, director, producer\n|-\n| 2015\n|''Bus Nut''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2016\n|''Reluctantly Queer''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2018\n|''On Monday of Last Week''\n| writer, director, producer\n|-\n| 2018\n|''Mahogany Too''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2019\n|''Pelourinho: They Don\u2019t Really Care About Us''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n| 2019\n|''White Afro''\n| director, producer, cinematographer\n|-\n|in production\n|''Black Sunshine'' (feature film)\n|writer, director, producer\n|-\n|}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*Owusu, Akosua Adoma, and Adwoa Adu-Gyamfi. ''Me broni ba''. New York, NY: [http://store.cinemaguild.com/nontheatrical/product/2358.html Cinema Guild] (2009).\n*Len\u00e9 Hole, Kristin. ''Film Feminisms: A Global Introduction''[https://books.google.com/books?id=QCBtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT251&lpg=PT251&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+ajube+kete&source=bl&ots=CmIGbxV1hi&sig=1Xu5fDlyidV9DEGNea_QiwmgA-Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiWp4qJ2LPfAhXpdN8KHZzBA0Q4ChDoATAMegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20ajube%20kete&f=false] (2018).\n*Kelly, Gabrielle. ''Celluloid Ceiling: Women Film Directors Breaking Through'' (2018) \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=0U07DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&lpg=PT29&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+triple+consciousness&source=bl&ots=hFyyC3hfGH&sig=1aX2-gvVrGK4SJLO-VJe0vDXPAU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiioPahlMDfAhXkQd8KHRkPBP04KBDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20triple%20consciousness&f=false]\"\n*Johnson, Elizabeth. ''Female Narratives in Nollywood Melodramas'' (2016) \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=x4vpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+%22triple+consciousness%22&source=bl&ots=kPgX7rGQqM&sig=-jf8thF22VdkHG0EysB4w6QzpNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj63fv1x_LeAhXKslkKHbGdDrc4KBDoATAIegQIARAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20%22triple%20consciousness%22&f=false]\", p.&nbsp;113.\n*Ellerson, Beti. ''Gaze Regimes: Film And Feminisms In Africa'' (2015) [https://books.google.com/books?id=3DZjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT50&lpg=PT50&dq=%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22+%22triple+consciousness%22&source=bl&ots=aytupH0_7B&sig=wy3JoGmo6R_CTYn29Tz3OMNcKLU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj63fv1x_LeAhXKslkKHbGdDrc4KBDoATACegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22%20%22triple%20consciousness%22&f=false]\"\n*Agyeman, Erica. \"[http://iraaa.museum.hamptonu.edu/store/Details.cfm?ProdID=166&category=7 Akosua Adoma Owusu: Exploring 'Threeness]\", ''The International Review of African American Art'' 24.3 (2013), 11-13.\n*Kendall, Nzingha, \"[http://muse.jhu.edu/article/525956 Commentary: Haunting in Akosua Adoma Owusu's Short Experimental Films]\" (2013). ''Black Camera''\n*Mask, Mia, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=dX-kvyCFVF0C&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=%2522erie%2522+%252B+%2522akosua+adoma+owusu%2522&source=bl&ots=QegbYJKSwt&sig=wyr3PkHKmmeVe93_u19GpIhJ-h4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiEhKKj2PneAhVSnlkKHaVFDIoQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ%23v=onepage&q=%2522erie%2522%2520%252#v=onepage&q=%2522erie%2522%2520%252&f=false Contemporary Black American Cinema: Race, Gender and Sexuality at the Movies]\" (2012).\n*Dovey, Lindiwe. ''African Feminist Engagements with Film'' (2012) \"[http://www.agi.ac.za/sites/default/files/image_tool/images/429/feminist_africa_journals/archive/16/fa16_full_pub.pdf]\", p. 18-23.\n*Nelmes, Jill. ''Introduction to Film Studies'' (2012) \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=AnGrAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT620&lpg=PT620&dq=%22erie%22+%2B+%22akosua+adoma+owusu%22&source=bl&ots=Ru8VWIEuNU&sig=CcxTEgi6i6U4UHLF09PE4_pZkK0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjGrIju2PneAhVp0FkKHakABu04ChDoATABegQIBBAB#v=onepage&q=%22erie%22%20%2B%20%22akosua%20adoma%20owusu%22&f=false]\"\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://obibinipictures.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3113362/?ref_=tt_ov_dr/ Akosua Adoma Owusu] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*[https://mubi.com/cast/akosua-adoma-owusu/ Akosua Adoma Owusu] on [[MUBI]]\n*[[Ghanaian Filmmakers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owusu, Akosua Adoma}}\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "name_user": "Bebox219", "label": "safe", "comment": "creative capital, Seattle references added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akosua_Adoma_Owusu"}
{"title_page": "Ruby Princess", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|British-American cruise ship}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Ruby Princess (ship, 2008) IMO 9378462; in Split, 2011-10-17 (2).jpg\n|Ship caption= ''Ruby Princess'' leaving [[Split, Croatia|Split]] on October 17, 2011\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name= ''Ruby Princess''\n|Ship owner=[[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n|Ship operator=[[Princess Cruises]]\n|Ship registry= {{flagicon|Bermuda}} [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]\n|Ship ordered= 2007\n|Ship builder= [[Fincantieri]] ([[Monfalcone]]-[[Trieste]], [[Italy]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shipparade.com/az/Ruby_Princess/Ruby_Princess.htm|title=Ruby Princess Cruise Ship Photos|work=ShipParade|accessdate=30 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227121624/http://www.shipparade.com/az/Ruby_Princess/Ruby_Princess.htm|archive-date=27 December 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondships.com/files/RU_ship_facts.PDF|title=Ruby Princess Ship Facts|last=Wagner|first=Richard H.|work=BeyondShips|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship original cost= [[US $]]400,000,000\n|Ship yard number= 6150<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/world/highvalueships/cruiseoperators.htm|title=Large Cruise Ships by Operator|last=Colton|first=Tim|work=ShipbuildingHistory.com|accessdate=13 February 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nV3ppTBz?url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/world/highvalueships/cruiseoperators.htm|archivedate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=June 2007\n|Ship launched=February 1, 2008\n|Ship completed= October 2008\n|Ship christened=November 6, 2008 <small>by [[Trista Sutter]] and [[Ryan Sutter]]</small><ref name=\"princess\">{{cite news|url=http://www.princess.com/news/article.jsp?newsArticleId=na976|title=Ruby Princess Delivered by Shipyard Today; Sets Sail for Florida |date=23 October 2008 |publisher=[[Princess Cruises]]|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=October 23, 2008\n|Ship maiden voyage=November 8, 2008\n|Ship in service=November 2008\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|9378462}}<ref name=\"coast guard\">{{csr|register=PSIX|id=982126|shipname=Ruby Princess}}</ref>\n*[[Call sign#Ships and boats|Call Sign]]: ZCDY2<ref name=\"coast guard\"/>\n*{{MMSI Number|310567000}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Ruby-Princess-9378462.html |title= Ruby Princess (IMO: 9378462) |accessdate=2010-01-29 |work=vesseltracker.com}}</ref>\n|Ship fate= \n|Ship status=Quarantined\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=[[Grand-class cruise ship#Crown class|''Crown''-class]] [[cruise ship]]\n|Ship tonnage={{GT|113,561}}\n|Ship length={{convert|951|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|118|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height= \n|Ship draught= {{convert|8|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks= 19 decks\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship power= 4 x V12 [[Wartsila]] Common Rail [[Diesel generator|Diesel Generator]]s, 2 x inline 8 Wartsila Common Rail Diesel Generators.\n|Ship propulsion= Twin propellers\n|Ship speed={{convert|23|kn}}\n|Ship capacity= 3,080 passengers\n|Ship crew= 1,100\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Ruby Princess''''' is a [[Grand-class cruise ship#Crown class|''Crown''-class]] [[cruise ship]] owned and operated by [[Princess Cruises]]. She was built in 2008 by [[Fincantieri]] in [[Trieste]], Italy. She is a [[sister ship]] to {{ship||Crown Princess|2005|2}} and {{ship||Emerald Princess}}. ''Ruby Princess'' was turned over to [[Carnival Corporation]] and [[Princess Cruises]] in late October 2008.<ref name=\"cruisehive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cruisehive.com/cruiseships/princess/ruby/|title=Ruby Princess|work=Cruise Hive|accessdate=30 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403215556/http://www.cruisehive.com/cruiseships/princess/ruby/|archivedate=3 April 2010}}</ref> She was formally named at [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], on November 6, 2008 by [[Trista Sutter|Trista]] and [[Ryan Sutter]].<ref name=\"princess\"/>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Ruby Princess in Ketchikan.jpg|thumb|''Ruby Princess'' docked in [[Ketchikan, Alaska]] during a 7-day Alaska cruise in August 2019]]\n''Ruby Princess'' continued the modified {{sclass-|Grand|cruise ship|0}} design with the Night Club moved just aft of the funnel, rather than suspended over the stern like the original designs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlesoftheseas.nl/pageID_7144901.html|title=Grand Class|last=Klein|first=Robert|work=Castles of the Seas|accessdate=13 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nV1sboCc?url=http://www.castlesoftheseas.nl/pageID_7144901.html |archivedate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy gross tonnage she was the largest ship in the Princess fleet until the arrival of the new {{ship||Royal Princess|2013|2}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.princess.com/news/article.jsp?newsArticleId=na966|title=Princess Cruises Debuts New \"Ultimate Ship Tour\" with Launch of Ruby Princess |date=9 February 2008|publisher=[[Princess Cruises]]|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Areas of operation==\n''Ruby Princess'' was based in [[Los Angeles]] for cruises to the [[Mexican Riviera]], [[Hawaii]] and California coastal cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boards.cruisecritic.com/showthread.php?t=1781864&page=3 |title=Europe 2014 - Page 3 - Cruise Critic Message Board Forums |publisher=Boards.cruisecritic.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-13}}</ref>\n\nStarting in late 2019, ''Ruby Princess'' is based in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-10-08/fremantle-to-keep-carnival-australia-cruise-ships/9028348|title=Fremantle to keep cruise ships after port access stoush|first=David|last=Weber|date=8 October 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n==2020: spread of COVID-19==\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Ruby Princess|Biosecurity in Australia}}\nThe ship discharged 2,700 passengers in Sydney, [[New South Wales]], on 19 March 2020. The state health minister, [[Brad Hazzard]] announced on 20 March 2020 that 13 of the people on the ship had been tested for the [[SARS-CoV-2]] coronavirus, and 3 of the tests were positive. New South Wales health authorities asked all passengers to go into self-isolation.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-thousands-who-left-cruise-ship-in-sydney-told-to-self-isolate-after-three-people-test-positive?CMP=Share_AndroidApp_WhatsApp|title= Coronavirus: thousands who left cruise ship in Sydney told to self-isolate after three people test positive|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date= 20 March 2020|accessdate= 20 March 2020}}</ref> It was announced on 24 March that one passenger had died and 133 on the ship had tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-24/coronavirus-cases-in-nsw-increase-and-pass-800/12080260|title= Coronavirus infections in NSW pass 800, Australia's eighth death confirmed|newspaper= ABC News|date= 24 March 2020|accessdate= 24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Ruby Princess'' visit to [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]], [[Hawke's Bay]] in [[New Zealand]] on 15 March 2020 may have resulted in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand | spreading COVID-19]] there.<ref>{{cite press release| date= 2020-03-26\n| title= Three New Cases Of COVID-19 In HB - One Linked To Cruise Ship Ruby Princess | url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/AK2003/S00523/three-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-hb-one-linked-to-cruise-ship-ruby-princess.htm | publisher= Hawke's Bay District Health Board | access-date= 28 March 2020| via= [[Scoop (website) | Scoop]] | quote= The third case was not linked to overseas travel but did have a connection to the Cruise Ship - The Ruby Princess. <br> Dr Eyre said anyone who had COVID-19 symptoms and came into close contact for 15 minutes or longer with passengers from The Ruby Princess, which docked 15 March, Napier Port, and is now symptomatic should call their GP.}}</ref> As of 3 April 2020, the [[Disease cluster|cluster]] was confirmed to be linked from the ship and responsible for hundreds of Australian cases.<ref>[https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/coronavirus-new-hawke-s-bay-cluster-linked-to-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-responsible-for-hundreds-of-australian-cases.html New cluster linked to Ruby Princess]</ref>\n\nAs of 30 March, at least 440 passengers (211 in New South Wales, 71 in South Australia, 70 in Queensland, 43 in Western Australia, 22 in the Australian Capital Territory, 18 in Victoria, three in Tasmania and two in the Northern Territory) had tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"guardian2020-03-31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/31/more-than-400-coronavirus-cases-australia-total-ruby-princess-cruise-ship |title=More than 400 coronavirus cases \u2013 10% of Australia\u2019s total \u2013 are from Ruby Princess cruise ship |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> As of 31 March 2020, five of them had died, one in the Australian Capital Territory, two in Tasmania, one in New South Wales and one in Queenland.<ref name=\"seven2020-03-31\">{{cite news|url=https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/coronavirus-death-in-act-was-a-passenger-on-the-under-fire-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-c-901621 |title=Coronavirus death in ACT was a passenger on the under-fire Ruby Princess cruise ship|newspaper=[[Seven Network]] |date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> As of 2 April, the number of cases in New South Wales had risen to 337 passengers and 3 crew members, so total passenger cases in Australia had risen to at least 576 cases.<ref name=\"nswh-2-4-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20200402_00.aspx|title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) statistics|publisher=NSW Health|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> This does not include passengers who left Australia without being tested.\n\nAs of 1 April, the ship was located off [[Port Botany]]. The [[International Transport Workers' Federation]] had called on the Australian government to allow the crew members to be disembarked so that they could be flown to their countries of residence. They formed part of 15,000 crew members in 18 cruise ships sitting off the Australian coast during the Pandemic. Six from ''Ruby Princess'' had been medically evacuated.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/01/coronavirus-calls-to-repatriate-15000-crew-members-from-cruise-ships-off-australias-coast?CMP=Share_AndroidApp_WhatsApp |title=Coronavirus: calls to repatriate 15,000 crew members from cruise ships off Australia's coast |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> [[Aspen Medical]] was contracted to carry out medical assessments on the ship and visited it on 2 April.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-03\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/two-cruise-ships-agree-to-leave-australian-waters-as-police-raise-hopes-of-resolving-standoff |title=Two cruise ships agree to leave Australian waters as police raise hopes of resolving standoff |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAnother three passengers from the ship were reported dead in New South Wales<ref name=\"abc-5-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/nsw-health-reports-four-more-coronavirus-deaths/12122966 |title=NSW coronavirus death toll rises, with three people dying after travelling on the Ruby Princess|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> and a fourth in Queensland on 5 April.<ref name=rpcrim/> A man was reported to have died in Western Australian on 6 April.<ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-06/wa-fourth-coronavirus-death-at-royal-perth-hospital/12124280 |title=WA coronavirus deaths rise to four as man from Ruby Princess dies of COVID-19 at Royal Perth Hospital|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> An additional death was announced in Tasmania on 7 April,<ref name=\"abc-7-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-07/coronavirus-tasmania-third-death/12127782 |title=Tasmanian man in his 80s becomes state's third coronavirus fatality|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> bringing total deaths to 13.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-05\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster |title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\"/><ref name=\"abc-7-4-20\"/> There had been 662 confirmed cases of the virus,<ref name=\"Guardian-4-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/04/nsw-health-minister-defends-experts-who-handled-ruby-princess-coronavirus-outbreak |title=NSW health minister defends experts who handled Ruby Princess coronavirus outbreak|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Ben Smee |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> including 342 in New South Wales. 11 cases of secondary transmission from people infected on the ship had been reported, which had not led to any deaths.<ref name=\"abc-5-4-20\"/> \n\nAs of 8 April, the ship's crew of about 1,000 remained on-board, with 200 exhibiting flu-like symptoms; 18 had tested positive for COVID-19. The vessel remained in Australia but was expected to move to [[Bermuda]] seven days later. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/nsw-police-seize-black-box-in-ruby-princess-coronavirus-probe/12135832 |title=NSW Police seize Ruby Princess's 'black box' in overnight raid for coronavirus investigation |date=9 April 2020 |publisher=ABC|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==== Criminal investigation ====\n\nOn 5 April 2020, [[New South Wales Police]] launched a [[criminal investigation]] into whether the operator of the ship, Carnival Australia, broke the ''[[Biosecurity Act 2015]]'' (Cwth) and [[New South Wales]] state laws, by deliberately concealing COVID-19 cases.<ref name=rpcrim>{{cite web | last=Nguyen | first=Kevin | last2=Thomas | first2=Sarah | title=Ruby Princess coronavirus deaths to be subject of criminal investigation by NSW Police homicide squad | website=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date=5 April 2020 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/nsw-police-investigate-ruby-princess-cruise-coronavirus-deaths/12123212 | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>  A report by [[The Guardian]] discussed the investigation and included this comment: \"Since the ship's 2,700 passengers were allowed to freely disembark in Sydney on 19 March, federal and state authorities have been pinballing blame.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster|title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster |date=5 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=At least 11 passengers from ship have now died, more than 30% of Australia\u2019s total Covid-19 deaths}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 2020, it was reported that the New Zealand Prime Minister, [[Jacinda Ardern]], has requested [[Crown Law Office (New Zealand)|Crown Law]] to check whether the country's laws had been broken.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gower |first1=Patrick |authorlink1=Patrick Gower |title=Coronavirus: Jacinda Ardern seeks legal advice on Ruby Princess cruise ship |url= https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/coronavirus-jacinda-ardern-seeks-legal-advice-on-ruby-princess-cruise-ship.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[Newshub]] |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of the evening of 8 April, 30 investigators had been assigned to Strike Force Bast which was looking into the Ruby Princess case: as to \"the communications, actions, and other circumstances that led to the docking and disembarking of the vessel\" without a quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.police.nsw.gov.au/news/news_article?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGZWJpenByZC5wb2xpY2UubnN3Lmdvdi5hdSUyRm1lZGlhJTJGODQxMTMuaHRtbCZhbGw9MQ%3D%3D |title=Strike Force Bast underway to investigate actions surrounding Ruby Princess |date=8 April 2020 |publisher=NSW Police|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> The ship's \"black box\" recorder (similar to a [[Flight recorder]]) had been seized.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/nsw-police-seize-black-box-in-ruby-princess-coronavirus-probe/12135832 |title=NSW Police seize Ruby Princess's 'black box' in overnight raid for coronavirus investigation |date=9 April 2020 |publisher=ABC|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline|Ruby Princess (ship, 2008)|''Ruby Princess'' (ship, 2008)}}\n* {{official|http://www.princess.com/learn/ships/ru/index.html }}\n\n{{List of ships built by Fincantieri}}\n{{Grand class}}\n{{Princess Ships}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of Princess Cruises]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Monfalcone]]\n[[Category:2008 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Fincantieri]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|British-American cruise ship}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Ruby Princess (ship, 2008) IMO 9378462; in Split, 2011-10-17 (2).jpg\n|Ship caption= ''Ruby Princess'' leaving [[Split, Croatia|Split]] on October 17, 2011\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name= ''Ruby Princess''\n|Ship owner=[[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n|Ship operator=[[Princess Cruises]]\n|Ship registry= {{flagicon|Bermuda}} [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]\n|Ship ordered= 2007\n|Ship builder= [[Fincantieri]] ([[Monfalcone]]-[[Trieste]], [[Italy]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shipparade.com/az/Ruby_Princess/Ruby_Princess.htm|title=Ruby Princess Cruise Ship Photos|work=ShipParade|accessdate=30 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227121624/http://www.shipparade.com/az/Ruby_Princess/Ruby_Princess.htm|archive-date=27 December 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondships.com/files/RU_ship_facts.PDF|title=Ruby Princess Ship Facts|last=Wagner|first=Richard H.|work=BeyondShips|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship original cost= [[US $]]400,000,000\n|Ship yard number= 6150<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/world/highvalueships/cruiseoperators.htm|title=Large Cruise Ships by Operator|last=Colton|first=Tim|work=ShipbuildingHistory.com|accessdate=13 February 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nV3ppTBz?url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/world/highvalueships/cruiseoperators.htm|archivedate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=June 2007\n|Ship launched=February 1, 2008\n|Ship completed= October 2008\n|Ship christened=November 6, 2008 <small>by [[Trista Sutter]] and [[Ryan Sutter]]</small><ref name=\"princess\">{{cite news|url=http://www.princess.com/news/article.jsp?newsArticleId=na976|title=Ruby Princess Delivered by Shipyard Today; Sets Sail for Florida |date=23 October 2008 |publisher=[[Princess Cruises]]|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=October 23, 2008\n|Ship maiden voyage=November 8, 2008\n|Ship in service=November 2008\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|9378462}}<ref name=\"coast guard\">{{csr|register=PSIX|id=982126|shipname=Ruby Princess}}</ref>\n*[[Call sign#Ships and boats|Call Sign]]: ZCDY2<ref name=\"coast guard\"/>\n*{{MMSI Number|310567000}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Ruby-Princess-9378462.html |title= Ruby Princess (IMO: 9378462) |accessdate=2010-01-29 |work=vesseltracker.com}}</ref>\n|Ship fate= \n|Ship status=Quarantined\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=[[Grand-class cruise ship#Crown class|''Crown''-class]] [[cruise ship]]\n|Ship tonnage={{GT|113,561}}\n|Ship length={{convert|951|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|118|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height= \n|Ship draught= {{convert|8|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks= 19 decks\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship power= 4 x V12 [[Wartsila]] Common Rail [[Diesel generator|Diesel Generator]]s, 2 x inline 8 Wartsila Common Rail Diesel Generators.\n|Ship propulsion= Twin propellers\n|Ship speed={{convert|23|kn}}\n|Ship capacity= 3,080 passengers\n|Ship crew= 1,100\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Ruby Princess''''' is a [[Grand-class cruise ship#Crown class|''Crown''-class]] [[cruise ship]] owned and operated by [[Princess Cruises]]. She was built in 2008 by [[Fincantieri]] in [[Trieste]], Italy. She is a [[sister ship]] to {{ship||Crown Princess|2005|2}} and {{ship||Emerald Princess}}. ''Ruby Princess'' was turned over to [[Carnival Corporation]] and [[Princess Cruises]] in late October 2008.<ref name=\"cruisehive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cruisehive.com/cruiseships/princess/ruby/|title=Ruby Princess|work=Cruise Hive|accessdate=30 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403215556/http://www.cruisehive.com/cruiseships/princess/ruby/|archivedate=3 April 2010}}</ref> She was formally named at [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], on November 6, 2008 by [[Trista Sutter|Trista]] and [[Ryan Sutter]].<ref name=\"princess\"/>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Ruby Princess in Ketchikan.jpg|thumb|''Ruby Princess'' docked in [[Ketchikan, Alaska]] during a 7-day Alaska cruise in August 2019]]\n''Ruby Princess'' continued the modified {{sclass-|Grand|cruise ship|0}} design with the Night Club moved just aft of the funnel, rather than suspended over the stern like the original designs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlesoftheseas.nl/pageID_7144901.html|title=Grand Class|last=Klein|first=Robert|work=Castles of the Seas|accessdate=13 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nV1sboCc?url=http://www.castlesoftheseas.nl/pageID_7144901.html |archivedate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy gross tonnage she was the largest ship in the Princess fleet until the arrival of the new {{ship||Royal Princess|2013|2}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.princess.com/news/article.jsp?newsArticleId=na966|title=Princess Cruises Debuts New \"Ultimate Ship Tour\" with Launch of Ruby Princess |date=9 February 2008|publisher=[[Princess Cruises]]|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Areas of operation==\n''Ruby Princess'' was based in [[Los Angeles]] for cruises to the [[Mexican Riviera]], [[Hawaii]] and California coastal cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boards.cruisecritic.com/showthread.php?t=1781864&page=3 |title=Europe 2014 - Page 3 - Cruise Critic Message Board Forums |publisher=Boards.cruisecritic.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-13}}</ref>\n\nStarting in late 2019, ''Ruby Princess'' is based in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-10-08/fremantle-to-keep-carnival-australia-cruise-ships/9028348|title=Fremantle to keep cruise ships after port access stoush|first=David|last=Weber|date=8 October 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n==2020: spread of COVID-19==\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Ruby Princess|Biosecurity in Australia}}\nThe ship discharged 2,700 passengers in Sydney, [[New South Wales]], on 19 March 2020. The state health minister, [[Brad Hazzard]] announced on 20 March 2020 that 13 of the people on the ship had been tested for the [[SARS-CoV-2]] coronavirus, and 3 of the tests were positive. New South Wales health authorities asked all passengers to go into self-isolation.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-thousands-who-left-cruise-ship-in-sydney-told-to-self-isolate-after-three-people-test-positive?CMP=Share_AndroidApp_WhatsApp|title= Coronavirus: thousands who left cruise ship in Sydney told to self-isolate after three people test positive|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date= 20 March 2020|accessdate= 20 March 2020}}</ref> It was announced on 24 March that one passenger had died and 133 on the ship had tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-24/coronavirus-cases-in-nsw-increase-and-pass-800/12080260|title= Coronavirus infections in NSW pass 800, Australia's eighth death confirmed|newspaper= ABC News|date= 24 March 2020|accessdate= 24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Ruby Princess'' visit to [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]], [[Hawke's Bay]] in [[New Zealand]] on 15 March 2020 may have resulted in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand | spreading COVID-19]] there.<ref>{{cite press release| date= 2020-03-26\n| title= Three New Cases Of COVID-19 In HB - One Linked To Cruise Ship Ruby Princess | url= https://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/AK2003/S00523/three-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-hb-one-linked-to-cruise-ship-ruby-princess.htm | publisher= Hawke's Bay District Health Board | access-date= 28 March 2020| via= [[Scoop (website) | Scoop]] | quote= The third case was not linked to overseas travel but did have a connection to the Cruise Ship - The Ruby Princess. <br> Dr Eyre said anyone who had COVID-19 symptoms and came into close contact for 15 minutes or longer with passengers from The Ruby Princess, which docked 15 March, Napier Port, and is now symptomatic should call their GP.}}</ref> As of 3 April 2020, the [[Disease cluster|cluster]] was confirmed to be linked from the ship and responsible for hundreds of Australian cases.<ref>[https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/coronavirus-new-hawke-s-bay-cluster-linked-to-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-responsible-for-hundreds-of-australian-cases.html New cluster linked to Ruby Princess]</ref>\n\nAs of 30 March, at least 440 passengers (211 in New South Wales, 71 in South Australia, 70 in Queensland, 43 in Western Australia, 22 in the Australian Capital Territory, 18 in Victoria, three in Tasmania and two in the Northern Territory) had tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"guardian2020-03-31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/31/more-than-400-coronavirus-cases-australia-total-ruby-princess-cruise-ship |title=More than 400 coronavirus cases \u2013 10% of Australia\u2019s total \u2013 are from Ruby Princess cruise ship |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> As of 31 March 2020, five of them had died, one in the Australian Capital Territory, two in Tasmania, one in New South Wales and one in Queenland.<ref name=\"seven2020-03-31\">{{cite news|url=https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/coronavirus-death-in-act-was-a-passenger-on-the-under-fire-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-c-901621 |title=Coronavirus death in ACT was a passenger on the under-fire Ruby Princess cruise ship|newspaper=[[Seven Network]] |date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> As of 2 April, the number of cases in New South Wales had risen to 337 passengers and 3 crew members, so total passenger cases in Australia had risen to at least 576 cases.<ref name=\"nswh-2-4-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/20200402_00.aspx|title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) statistics|publisher=NSW Health|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> This does not include passengers who left Australia without being tested.\n\nAs of 1 April, the ship was located off [[Port Botany]]. The [[International Transport Workers' Federation]] had called on the Australian government to allow the crew members to be disembarked so that they could be flown to their countries of residence. They formed part of 15,000 crew members in 18 cruise ships sitting off the Australian coast during the Pandemic. Six from ''Ruby Princess'' had been medically evacuated.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/01/coronavirus-calls-to-repatriate-15000-crew-members-from-cruise-ships-off-australias-coast?CMP=Share_AndroidApp_WhatsApp |title=Coronavirus: calls to repatriate 15,000 crew members from cruise ships off Australia's coast |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> [[Aspen Medical]] was contracted to carry out medical assessments on the ship and visited it on 2 April.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-03\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/two-cruise-ships-agree-to-leave-australian-waters-as-police-raise-hopes-of-resolving-standoff |title=Two cruise ships agree to leave Australian waters as police raise hopes of resolving standoff |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAnother three passengers from the ship were reported dead in New South Wales<ref name=\"abc-5-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/nsw-health-reports-four-more-coronavirus-deaths/12122966 |title=NSW coronavirus death toll rises, with three people dying after travelling on the Ruby Princess|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> and a fourth in Queensland on 5 April.<ref name=rpcrim/> A man was reported to have died in Western Australian on 6 April.<ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-06/wa-fourth-coronavirus-death-at-royal-perth-hospital/12124280 |title=WA coronavirus deaths rise to four as man from Ruby Princess dies of COVID-19 at Royal Perth Hospital|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> An additional death was announced in Tasmania on 7 April,<ref name=\"abc-7-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-07/coronavirus-tasmania-third-death/12127782 |title=Tasmanian man in his 80s becomes state's third coronavirus fatality|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> bringing total deaths to 13.<ref name=\"guardian2020-04-05\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster |title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"abc-6-4-20\"/><ref name=\"abc-7-4-20\"/> There had been 662 confirmed cases of the virus,<ref name=\"Guardian-4-4-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/04/nsw-health-minister-defends-experts-who-handled-ruby-princess-coronavirus-outbreak |title=NSW health minister defends experts who handled Ruby Princess coronavirus outbreak|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|author=Ben Smee |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> including 342 in New South Wales. 11 cases of secondary transmission from people infected on the ship had been reported, which had not led to any deaths.<ref name=\"abc-5-4-20\"/> \n\nAs of 8 April, the ship's crew of about 1,000 remained on-board, with 200 exhibiting flu-like symptoms; 18 had tested positive for COVID-19. The vessel remained in Australia but was expected to move to [[Bermuda]] seven days later. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/nsw-police-seize-black-box-in-ruby-princess-coronavirus-probe/12135832 |title=NSW Police seize Ruby Princess's 'black box' in overnight raid for coronavirus investigation |date=9 April 2020 |publisher=ABC|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==== Criminal investigation ====\n\nOn 5 April 2020, [[New South Wales Police]] launched a [[criminal investigation]] into whether the operator of the ship, Carnival Australia, broke the ''[[Biosecurity Act 2015]]'' (Cwth) and [[New South Wales]] state laws, by deliberately concealing COVID-19 cases.<ref name=rpcrim>{{cite web | last=Nguyen | first=Kevin | last2=Thomas | first2=Sarah | title=Ruby Princess coronavirus deaths to be subject of criminal investigation by NSW Police homicide squad | website=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date=5 April 2020 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-05/nsw-police-investigate-ruby-princess-cruise-coronavirus-deaths/12123212 | access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>  A report by [[The Guardian]] discussed the investigation and included this comment: \"Since the ship's 2,700 passengers were allowed to freely disembark in Sydney on 19 March, federal and state authorities have been pinballing blame.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/criminal-investigation-launched-ruby-princess-cruise-ship-coronavirus-disaster|title=Criminal investigation launched into Ruby Princess cruise ship coronavirus disaster |date=5 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=At least 11 passengers from ship have now died, more than 30% of Australia\u2019s total Covid-19 deaths}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 2020, it was reported that the New Zealand Prime Minister, [[Jacinda Ardern]], has requested [[Crown Law Office (New Zealand)|Crown Law]] to check whether the country's laws had been broken.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gower |first1=Patrick |authorlink1=Patrick Gower |title=Coronavirus: Jacinda Ardern seeks legal advice on Ruby Princess cruise ship |url= https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2020/04/coronavirus-jacinda-ardern-seeks-legal-advice-on-ruby-princess-cruise-ship.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[Newshub]] |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of the evening of 8 April, 30 investigators had been assigned to Strike Force Bast which was looking into the Ruby Princess case: as to \"the communications, actions, and other circumstances that led to the docking and disembarking of the vessel\" without a quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.police.nsw.gov.au/news/news_article?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGZWJpenByZC5wb2xpY2UubnN3Lmdvdi5hdSUyRm1lZGlhJTJGODQxMTMuaHRtbCZhbGw9MQ%3D%3D |title=Strike Force Bast underway to investigate actions surrounding Ruby Princess |date=8 April 2020 |publisher=NSW Police|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> The ship's \"black box\" recorder (similar to a [[Flight recorder]] had been seized.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/nsw-police-seize-black-box-in-ruby-princess-coronavirus-probe/12135832 |title=NSW Police seize Ruby Princess's 'black box' in overnight raid for coronavirus investigation |date=9 April 2020 |publisher=ABC|access-date=9 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline|Ruby Princess (ship, 2008)|''Ruby Princess'' (ship, 2008)}}\n* {{official|http://www.princess.com/learn/ships/ru/index.html }}\n\n{{List of ships built by Fincantieri}}\n{{Grand class}}\n{{Princess Ships}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of Princess Cruises]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Monfalcone]]\n[[Category:2008 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Fincantieri]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Peter K Burian", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriminal investigation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_Princess"}
{"title_page": "June and Jennifer Gibbons", "text_new": "{{short description|Barbadian Welsh identical twins, writer and crime duo}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name = June Gibbons \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|4|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Aden, Yemen]]\n| parents = Gloria and Aubrey Gibbons \n| occupation = Fiction author\n}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name = Jennifer Gibbons\n| birth_date = 11 April 1963\n| birth_place = Aden, Yemen\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1993|3|9|1963|4|11|df=y}}\n| home_town = Haverfordwest, Wales, UK\n| parents = Gloria and Aubrey Gibbons\n| occupation = Fiction author\n}}\n'''June Gibbons''' (born 11 April 1963)<ref name=\"Morgan\" /> and '''Jennifer Gibbons''' (11 April 1963 \u2013 9 March 1993) were [[identical twin]]s who grew up in [[Wales]]. They became known as '''\"The Silent Twins\"''' since they only communicated with each other. They began writing works of fiction but later turned to crime. Both women were admitted to [[Broadmoor Hospital]] where they were held for eleven years.\n\n== Childhood ==\nJune and Jennifer were the daughters of Caribbean immigrants Gloria and Aubrey Gibbons. The Gibbons\u2019 moved from [[Barbados]] to the [[United Kingdom]] in the early 1960s, as part of the [[Windrush generation]].<ref name=\"Evans\">{{Cite news |last=Evans |first=Jason |url=https://www.questia.com/article/1G1-566778385/locked-up-mysterious-twins-wouldn-t-speak-to-anyone |title=Locked Up Mysterious Twins Wouldn't Speak to Anyone |date=23 December 2018 |work=Wales On Sunday |access-date=24 April 2019 |via=Questia |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Gloria was a housewife and Aubrey worked as a technician for the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Harpin |first=Anna |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=c5hNDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA65 |title=Performance and Participation: Practices, Audiences, Politics |last2=Nicholson |first2=Helen |date=7 October 2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9781137393180 |access-date=30 January 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref> The twins were born on 11 April 1963 at a military hospital in [[Aden]], [[Yemen]], where their father had been deployed. The family soon relocated\u2014first to England, and in 1974, to [[Haverfordwest]], Wales.<ref name=\"Evans\" /> The twin sisters were inseparable and their language, a sped-up [[Bajan Creole]], made it difficult for people to understand them.\n\nAs the only [[black British|black]] children in the community, they were ostracized at school.<ref name=\"Morgan\" /> This proved to be traumatic for the twins, eventually causing their school administrators to dismiss them early each day so that they might avoid bullying. Their language became even more [[idiosyncratic]] at this time. Soon it was unintelligible to others. Their language, or [[idioglossia]], qualified as an example of [[cryptophasia]], exemplified by the twins' simultaneous actions, which often mirrored each other. The twins became increasingly reserved and eventually spoke to no one except each other and their younger sister Rose.<ref name=\"wallace\">{{Cite book |last=Wallace |first=Marjorie |title=The Silent Twins |publisher=Prentice-Hall |year=1986 |isbn=978-5551732501}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe girls continued to attend school, although they refused to read or write. In 1974, a medic administering vaccinations at the school noted their impassive behavior and notified a child psychologist.<ref name=\"Evans\" /> The twins began seeing a succession of therapists who tried unsuccessfully to get them to communicate with others. They were sent to separate [[boarding school]]s in an attempt to break their isolation, but the pair became [[Catatonia|catatonic]] and entirely withdrawn when parted.<ref name=\"wallace\" />{{Page needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Creative expression==\nWhen they were reunited, the two spent several years isolating themselves in their bedroom, engaged in elaborate plays with dolls. They created many plays and stories in a sort of soap opera style, reading some of them aloud on tape as gifts for their sister, Rose. Inspired by a pair of gift diaries on Christmas 1979, they began their writing careers. They sent away for a [[mail order]] course in creative writing, and each kept an extensive diary and wrote a number of stories, poems and novels.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> Set primarily in the United States and particularly in [[Malibu, California]], the stories involve young men and women who exhibit strange and often criminal behaviour.<ref name=\"wallace\" />{{Page needed|date=April 2019}} \n\nJune wrote a novel titled ''Pepsi-Cola Addict'', in which the high-school hero is seduced by a teacher, then sent away to a [[reformatory]] where a homosexual guard makes a play for him.<ref>{{Cite news |last=de Angelis |first=April |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jun/28/fiction.classicalmusicandopera |title=April de Angelis on troubled twins Jennifer and June Gibbons |date=28 June 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=19 July 2013 |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] |location=London |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |author-link=April De Angelis}}</ref> The two girls pooled together their [[unemployment benefits]] in order to get the novel published by a [[self-publishing press|vanity press]].<ref name=\"people\">{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/archive/a-british-journalist-unravels-the-tale-of-the-twins-who-wouldnt-talk-vol-26-no-17/ |title=A British Journalist Unravels the Tale of the Twins Who Wouldn't Talk |last=Shapiro |first=Harriet |date=27 October 1986 |website=People |language=en |access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref> Their other attempts to publish novels and stories were unsuccessful. In Jennifer's ''The Pugilist'', a physician is so eager to save his child's life that he kills the family dog to obtain its heart for a transplant.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> The dog's spirit lives on in the child and ultimately has its revenge against the father. Jennifer also wrote ''Discomania'', the story of a young woman who discovers that the atmosphere of a local disco incites patrons to insane violence.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> She followed up with ''The Taxi-Driver's Son'', a radio play called ''Postman and Postwoman'', and several short stories. June Gibbons is considered to be an outsider writer.\n\n==Hospitalisation==\nIn their later teenage years, the twins began experimenting with drugs and alcohol.<ref name=\"Evans\" /> In 1981, the girls committed a number of crimes including [[vandalism]], petty [[theft]] and [[arson]], which led to their being admitted to [[Broadmoor Hospital]], a high-security mental health hospital. The twins were sentenced to indefinite detention under the [[Mental Health Act 1983]].<ref name=\"Evans\" /> They remained at Broadmoor for eleven years.<ref name=\"Misstear\">{{Cite news |last=Misstear |first=Rachael |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-271206167/powerful-play-about-silent-twins-will-get-you-talking |title=Powerful Play about Silent Twins Will Get You Talking |date=31 October 2011 |work=Western Mail |access-date=24 April 2019 |location=Cardiff, Wales |via=Questia |url-access=subscription}}</ref> June later blamed this lengthy sentence on their selective muteness: \"Juvenile delinquents get two years in prison... We got twelve years of hell because we didn't speak... We lost hope, really. I wrote a letter to the Queen, asking her to get us out. But we were trapped.\"<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> Placed on high doses of [[antipsychotic]] medications, they found themselves unable to concentrate; Jennifer apparently developed [[tardive dyskinesia]] (a neurological disorder resulting in involuntary, repetitive movements). Their medications were apparently adjusted sufficiently to allow them to continue the copious diaries they had begun in 1980, and they were able to join the hospital choir, but they lost most of their interest in creative writing.<ref name=\"wallace\" />{{Page needed|date=April 2019}} \n\nThe case achieved notoriety due to newspaper coverage by journalist [[Marjorie Wallace (SANE)|Marjorie Wallace]] of ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/05/08/405191622/the-silent-twins |title=The Silent Twins |date=8 May 2015 |website=NPR |language=en |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorker\">{{Cite news |last=Als |first=Hilton |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2000/12/04/we-two-made-one |title=The Identical Twin Sisters Who Retreated Into Their Own World |date=4 December 2000 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref> Wallace later wrote a book about the two called ''The Silent Twins''.<ref name=\"Evans\" />\n\n==Jennifer's death==\nAccording to Wallace, the girls had a longstanding agreement that if one died, the other must begin to speak and live a normal life. During their stay in the hospital, they began to believe that it was ''necessary'' for one of them to die, and after much discussion, Jennifer agreed to make the sacrifice of her life.<ref name=\"wallace2003\">{{Cite news |last=Wallace |first=Marjorie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2003/jul/13/health.lifeandhealth |title=Marjorie Wallace: The tragedy of the Bijani sisters |date=2003-07-13 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-09 |location=London |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In March 1993, the twins were transferred from Broadmoor to the more open Caswell Clinic in [[Bridgend]], Wales. On arrival Jennifer could not be roused. She was taken to the hospital where she died soon after of acute [[myocarditis]], a sudden [[inflammation]] of the heart.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kellam |first=Alexander M.P. |date=October 1993 |year=1993 |title=The silent twins |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/E99608E3CB1BA89D12C25BC1D97CCEDB/S0955603600085329a.pdf |journal=Psychiatric Bulletin |volume=17 |issue=10 |pages=622\u2013623}}</ref><ref name=\"Morgan\">{{Cite news |last=Morgan |first=Kathleen |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts-ents/stage-visual-arts/tragic-tale-of-twins-and-their-secret-world-1.1045865 |title=Tragic tale of twins and their secret world |date=2 August 2010 |work=Herald Scotland |access-date=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517024140/http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts-ents/stage-visual-arts/tragic-tale-of-twins-and-their-secret-world-1.1045865 |archive-date=17 May 2015}}</ref> There was no evidence of drugs or poison in her system, and her death remains a mystery.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bennetto |first=Jason |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/inquiry-into-death-of-silent-twin-1497079.html |title=Inquiry into death of 'silent twin' |date=1993-03-12 |work=The Independent |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref> At the inquest, June revealed that Jennifer had been acting strangely for about a day before their release; her speech had been slurring, and she had said that she was dying. On the trip to Caswell, she had slept in June's lap with her eyes open.<ref name=\"Wallace293\" /> On a visit a few days later, Wallace recounted that June \"was in a strange mood\". She said, \"I'm free at last, liberated, and at last Jennifer has given up her life for me\".<ref name=\"Morgan\" />\n\nAfter Jennifer's death, June gave interviews with ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> By 2008, she was living quietly and independently, near her parents in West Wales.<ref name=\"Wallace293\">{{Cite book |last=Wallace |first=Marjorie |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/60262552 |title=The Silent Twins |publisher=Vintage |year=2008 |isbn=0-09-958641-X |location=London |pages=293 |oclc=60262552}}</ref> She was no longer monitored by psychiatric services, has been accepted by her community, and sought to put the past behind her.<ref name=\"Morgan\" /> A 2016 interview with her sister Greta revealed that the family had been deeply troubled by the girls' incarceration. She blamed Broadmoor for ruining their lives and for neglecting Jennifer's health. She had wanted to file a lawsuit against Broadmoor, but Aubrey and Gloria refused, saying it would not bring Jennifer back.<ref name=\"dailymail2016\">{{Cite news |last=Joseph |first=Claudia |url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3526486/Sister-Silent-Twins-close-one-DIE-live.html |title='Silent Twins' so close that one had to DIE so the other could live |date=2016-04-13 |work=Daily Mail |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\n\nThe pair were the subject of the 1986 television drama ''[[The Silent Twins (film)|The Silent Twins]]'', broadcast on BBC Two as part of its ''[[Screen Two]]'' series,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/cdb0079565784ec8a6430e8a9a2936fc |title=Screen Two: The Silent Twins |date=19 January 1986 |website=BBC Genome |publisher=BBC |access-date=17 September 2017}}</ref> and an ''Inside Story'' documentary ''Silent Twin \u2013 Without My Shadow'', which aired on BBC One in September 1994.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/eda57dfce87846fca3eb3ee195fea354 |title=Inside Story Silent Twin \u2013 Without My Shadow |date=22 September 1994 |website=BBC Genome |publisher=BBC |access-date=17 September 2017}}</ref> A play based on Wallace's book, titled ''[[Speechless (play)|Speechless]]'', debuted in London in 2011.<ref name=\"Misstear\" />\n\nThe twins' story also inspired the 1998 [[Manic Street Preachers]] song \"[[Tsunami (Manic Street Preachers song)|Tsunami]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mackay |first=Emily |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/dec/10/manic-street-preachers-10-of-the-best |title=Manic Street Preachers: 10 of the best |date=10 December 2014 |work=The Guardian |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Ursula and Sabina Eriksson]]\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Other sources===\n* [[Oliver Sacks]], [https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/19/books/bound-together-in-fantasy-and-crime.html?pagewanted=all \"Bound Together in Fantasy and Crime\"] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' review of ''The Silent Twins'', 19 October 1986.\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE0D81730F931A25750C0A965958260 Jennifer Gibbons, 29, 'Silent Twin' of a Study] Announcement of Jennifer's death in the ''New York Times'', 12 March 1993.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibbons, June And Jennifer}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh novelists]]\n[[Category:People acquitted by reason of insanity]]\n[[Category:People detained at Broadmoor Hospital]]\n[[Category:People from Haverfordwest]]\n[[Category:Barbadian emigrants to Wales]]\n[[Category:Black Welsh people]]\n[[Category:Identical twins]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Wales]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:History of mental health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Outsider literature]]\n[[Category:20th-century Barbadian writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Barbadian Welsh identical twins, writer and crime duo}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name = June Gibbons \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|4|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Aden, Yemen]]\n| parents = Gloria and Aubrey Gibbons \n| occupation = Fiction author\n}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name = Jennifer Gibbons\n| birth_date = 11 April 1963\n| birth_place = Aden, Yemen\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1993|3|9|1963|4|11|df=y}}\n| home_town = Haverfordwest, Wales, UK\n| parents = Gloria and Aubrey Gibbons\n| occupation = Fiction author\n}}\n'''June Gibbons''' (born 11 April 1963)<ref name=\"Morgan\" /> and '''Jennifer Gibbons''' (11 April 1963 \u2013 9 March 1993) were [[identical twin]]s who grew up in [[Wales]]. They became known as '''\"The Silent Twins\"''' since they only communicated with each other. They began writing works of fiction but later turned to crime. Both women were admitted to [[Broadmoor Hospital]] where they were held for eleven years.\n\n== Childhood ==\nJune and Jennifer were the daughters of Caribbean immigrants Gloria and Aubrey Gibbons. The Gibbons\u2019 moved from [[Barbados]] to the [[United Kingdom]] in the early 1960s, as part of the [[Windrush generation]].<ref name=\"Evans\">{{Cite news |last=Evans |first=Jason |url=https://www.questia.com/article/1G1-566778385/locked-up-mysterious-twins-wouldn-t-speak-to-anyone |title=Locked Up Mysterious Twins Wouldn't Speak to Anyone |date=23 December 2018 |work=Wales On Sunday |access-date=24 April 2019 |via=Questia |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Gloria was a housewife and Aubrey worked as a technician for the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Harpin |first=Anna |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=c5hNDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA65 |title=Performance and Participation: Practices, Audiences, Politics |last2=Nicholson |first2=Helen |date=7 October 2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9781137393180 |access-date=30 January 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref> The twins were born on 11 April 1963 at a military hospital in [[Aden]], [[Yemen]], where their father had been deployed. The family soon relocated\u2014first to England, and in 1974, to [[Haverfordwest]], Wales.<ref name=\"Evans\" /> The twin sisters were inseparable and their language, a sped-up [[Bajan Creole]], made it difficult for people to understand them.\n\nAs the only [[black British|black]] children in the community, they were ostracized at school.<ref name=\"Morgan\" /> This proved to be traumatic for the twins, eventually causing their school administrators to dismiss them early each day so that they might avoid bullying. Their language became even more [[idiosyncratic]] at this time. Soon it was unintelligible to others. Their language, or [[idioglossia]], qualified as an example of [[cryptophasia]], exemplified by the twins' simultaneous actions, which often mirrored each other. The twins became increasingly reserved and eventually spoke to no one except each other and their younger sister Rose.<ref name=\"wallace\">{{Cite book |last=Wallace |first=Marjorie |title=The Silent Twins |publisher=Prentice-Hall |year=1986 |isbn=978-5551732501}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe girls continued to attend school, although they refused to read or write. In 1974, a medic administering vaccinations at the school noted their impassive behavior and notified a child psychologist.<ref name=\"Evans\" /> The twins began seeing a succession of therapists who tried unsuccessfully to get them to communicate with others. They were sent to separate [[boarding school]]s in an attempt to break their isolation, but the pair became [[Catatonia|catatonic]] and entirely withdrawn when parted.<ref name=\"wallace\" />{{Page needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Creative expression==\nWhen they were reunited, the two spent several years isolating themselves in their bedroom, engaged in elaborate plays with dolls. They created many plays and stories in a sort of soap opera style, reading some of them aloud on tape as gifts for their sister, Rose. Inspired by a pair of gift diaries on Christmas 1979, they began their writing careers. They sent away for a [[mail order]] course in creative writing, and each kept an extensive diary and wrote a number of stories, poems and novels.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> Set primarily in the United States and particularly in [[Malibu, California]], the stories involve young men and women who exhibit strange and often criminal behaviour.<ref name=\"wallace\" />{{Page needed|date=April 2019}} \n\nJune wrote a novel titled ''Pepsi-Cola Addict'', in which the high-school hero is seduced by a teacher, then sent away to a [[reformatory]] where a homosexual guard makes a play for him.<ref>{{Cite news |last=de Angelis |first=April |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jun/28/fiction.classicalmusicandopera |title=April de Angelis on troubled twins Jennifer and June Gibbons |date=28 June 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=19 July 2013 |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|GMG]] |location=London |issn=0261-3077 |oclc=60623878 |author-link=April De Angelis}}</ref> The two girls pooled together their [[unemployment benefits]] in order to get the novel published by a [[self-publishing press|vanity press]].<ref name=\"people\">{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/archive/a-british-journalist-unravels-the-tale-of-the-twins-who-wouldnt-talk-vol-26-no-17/ |title=A British Journalist Unravels the Tale of the Twins Who Wouldn't Talk |last=Shapiro |first=Harriet |date=27 October 1986 |website=People |language=en |access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref> Their other attempts to publish novels and stories were unsuccessful. In Jennifer's ''The Pugilist'', a physician is so eager to save his child's life that he kills the family dog to obtain its heart for a transplant.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> The dog's spirit lives on in the child and ultimately has its revenge against the father. Jennifer also wrote ''Discomania'', the story of a young woman who discovers that the atmosphere of a local disco incites patrons to insane violence.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> She followed up with ''The Taxi-Driver's Son'', a radio play called ''Postman and Postwoman'', and several short stories. June Gibbons is considered to be an outsider writer.\n\n==Hospitalisation==\nIn their later teenage years, the twins began experimenting with drugs and alcohol.<ref name=\"Evans\" /> In 1981, the girls committed a number of crimes including [[vandalism]], petty [[theft]] and [[arson]], which led to their being admitted to [[Broadmoor Hospital]], a high-security mental health hospital. The twins were sentenced to indefinite detention under the [[Mental Health Act 1983]].<ref name=\"Evans\" /> They remained at Broadmoor for eleven years.<ref name=\"Misstear\">{{Cite news |last=Misstear |first=Rachael |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-271206167/powerful-play-about-silent-twins-will-get-you-talking |title=Powerful Play about Silent Twins Will Get You Talking |date=31 October 2011 |work=Western Mail |access-date=24 April 2019 |location=Cardiff, Wales |via=Questia |url-access=subscription}}</ref> June later blamed this lengthy sentence on their selective muteness: \"Juvenile delinquents get two years in prison... We got twelve years of hell because we didn't speak... We lost hope, really. I wrote a letter to the Queen, asking her to get us out. But we were trapped.\"<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> Placed on high doses of [[antipsychotic]] medications, they found themselves unable to concentrate; Jennifer apparently developed [[tardive dyskinesia]] (a neurological disorder resulting in involuntary, repetitive movements). Their medications were apparently adjusted sufficiently to allow them to continue the copious diaries they had begun in 1980, and they were able to join the hospital choir, but they lost most of their interest in creative writing.<ref name=\"wallace\" />{{Page needed|date=April 2019}} \n\nThe case achieved notoriety due to newspaper coverage by journalist [[Marjorie Wallace (SANE)|Marjorie Wallace]] of ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/05/08/405191622/the-silent-twins |title=The Silent Twins |date=8 May 2015 |website=NPR |language=en |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorker\">{{Cite news |last=Als |first=Hilton |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2000/12/04/we-two-made-one |title=The Identical Twin Sisters Who Retreated Into Their Own World |date=4 December 2000 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref> Wallace later wrote a book about the two called ''The Silent Twins''.<ref name=\"Evans\" />\n\n==Jennifer's death==\nAccording to Wallace, the girls had a longstanding agreement that if one died, the other must begin to speak and live a normal life. During their stay in the hospital, they began to believe that it was ''necessary'' for one of them to die, and after much discussion, Jennifer agreed to make the sacrifice of her life.<ref name=\"wallace2003\">{{Cite news |last=Wallace |first=Marjorie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2003/jul/13/health.lifeandhealth |title=Marjorie Wallace: The tragedy of the the Bijani sisters |date=2003-07-13 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-09 |location=London |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In March 1993, the twins were transferred from Broadmoor to the more open Caswell Clinic in [[Bridgend]], Wales. On arrival Jennifer could not be roused. She was taken to the hospital where she died soon after of acute [[myocarditis]], a sudden [[inflammation]] of the heart.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kellam |first=Alexander M.P. |date=October 1993 |year=1993 |title=The silent twins |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/E99608E3CB1BA89D12C25BC1D97CCEDB/S0955603600085329a.pdf |journal=Psychiatric Bulletin |volume=17 |issue=10 |pages=622\u2013623}}</ref><ref name=\"Morgan\">{{Cite news |last=Morgan |first=Kathleen |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts-ents/stage-visual-arts/tragic-tale-of-twins-and-their-secret-world-1.1045865 |title=Tragic tale of twins and their secret world |date=2 August 2010 |work=Herald Scotland |access-date=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517024140/http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts-ents/stage-visual-arts/tragic-tale-of-twins-and-their-secret-world-1.1045865 |archive-date=17 May 2015}}</ref> There was no evidence of drugs or poison in her system, and her death remains a mystery.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bennetto |first=Jason |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/inquiry-into-death-of-silent-twin-1497079.html |title=Inquiry into death of 'silent twin' |date=1993-03-12 |work=The Independent |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref> At the inquest, June revealed that Jennifer had been acting strangely for about a day before their release; her speech had been slurring, and she had said that she was dying. On the trip to Caswell, she had slept in June's lap with her eyes open.<ref name=\"Wallace293\" /> On a visit a few days later, Wallace recounted that June \"was in a strange mood\". She said, \"I'm free at last, liberated, and at last Jennifer has given up her life for me\".<ref name=\"Morgan\" />\n\nAfter Jennifer's death, June gave interviews with ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> By 2008, she was living quietly and independently, near her parents in West Wales.<ref name=\"Wallace293\">{{Cite book |last=Wallace |first=Marjorie |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/60262552 |title=The Silent Twins |publisher=Vintage |year=2008 |isbn=0-09-958641-X |location=London |pages=293 |oclc=60262552}}</ref> She was no longer monitored by psychiatric services, has been accepted by her community, and sought to put the past behind her.<ref name=\"Morgan\" /> A 2016 interview with her sister Greta revealed that the family had been deeply troubled by the girls' incarceration. She blamed Broadmoor for ruining their lives and for neglecting Jennifer's health. She had wanted to file a lawsuit against Broadmoor, but Aubrey and Gloria refused, saying it would not bring Jennifer back.<ref name=\"dailymail2016\">{{Cite news |last=Joseph |first=Claudia |url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3526486/Sister-Silent-Twins-close-one-DIE-live.html |title='Silent Twins' so close that one had to DIE so the other could live |date=2016-04-13 |work=Daily Mail |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\n\nThe pair were the subject of the 1986 television drama ''[[The Silent Twins (film)|The Silent Twins]]'', broadcast on BBC Two as part of its ''[[Screen Two]]'' series,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/cdb0079565784ec8a6430e8a9a2936fc |title=Screen Two: The Silent Twins |date=19 January 1986 |website=BBC Genome |publisher=BBC |access-date=17 September 2017}}</ref> and an ''Inside Story'' documentary ''Silent Twin \u2013 Without My Shadow'', which aired on BBC One in September 1994.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/eda57dfce87846fca3eb3ee195fea354 |title=Inside Story Silent Twin \u2013 Without My Shadow |date=22 September 1994 |website=BBC Genome |publisher=BBC |access-date=17 September 2017}}</ref> A play based on Wallace's book, titled ''[[Speechless (play)|Speechless]]'', debuted in London in 2011.<ref name=\"Misstear\" />\n\nThe twins' story also inspired the 1998 [[Manic Street Preachers]] song \"[[Tsunami (Manic Street Preachers song)|Tsunami]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mackay |first=Emily |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/dec/10/manic-street-preachers-10-of-the-best |title=Manic Street Preachers: 10 of the best |date=10 December 2014 |work=The Guardian |access-date=3 February 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Ursula and Sabina Eriksson]]\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Other sources===\n* [[Oliver Sacks]], [https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/19/books/bound-together-in-fantasy-and-crime.html?pagewanted=all \"Bound Together in Fantasy and Crime\"] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' review of ''The Silent Twins'', 19 October 1986.\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE0D81730F931A25750C0A965958260 Jennifer Gibbons, 29, 'Silent Twin' of a Study] Announcement of Jennifer's death in the ''New York Times'', 12 March 1993.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibbons, June And Jennifer}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh novelists]]\n[[Category:People acquitted by reason of insanity]]\n[[Category:People detained at Broadmoor Hospital]]\n[[Category:People from Haverfordwest]]\n