{"title_page": "Lakhta Center", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}{{Infobox building\n| name = Lakhta Center\n| native_name = \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| former_names = Gazprom Tower, [[Okhta Center]]\n| alternate_names = \n| status = {{Color|green|Completed}}\n| image = Saint Petersburg Lakhta center 06.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = July 2018\n| location = [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|59|59|13.7|N|30|10|37.3|E|region:RU|display=inline,title}}\n| address = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = Russia\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = 2012\n| completion_date = 2019\n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT\n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Gazprom Neft]]\n| cost = US$1.77 billion<ref>[https://realty.rbc.ru/news/5bed46bd9a794728d6707196]</ref>\n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 87\n| awards = \n| parking = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| highest_region = \n| highest_reflabel = \n| highest_prev = \n| highest_start = \n| highest_end = \n| highest_next = \n| map_type = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| altitude = \n| building_type = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| current_tenants = \n| renovation_date = \n| height = {{convert|462|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| architectural = \n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| observatory = \n| other_dimensions = \n| elevator_count = 40<ref>[https://habr.com/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371087/ Elevators in a skyscraper]</ref>\n| architecture_firm = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT<ref>[https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/europes-tallest-skyscraper-lakhta-centre Europe's tallest skyscraper is nearing completion in St. Petersburg]</ref>\n| main_contractor = [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]\n| designations = \n| url = \n}}\nThe '''Lakhta Center''' ({{Lang-rus|\u041b\u0430\u0301\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0442\u0440|r=Lakhta tsentr}}) is an 87-story [[skyscraper]] built in the outskirts of [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]. Standing {{convert|462|m|ft}} tall, the Lakhta Center is the [[List of tallest buildings in Russia|tallest building in Russia]], the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest building in Europe]], and the [[List of tallest buildings|16th-tallest building in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title=Lakhta Center - The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/ru/about/project/ |title=Lakhta Center Website, \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/uploaded/file_list/ROSAVIA706(19.07.2011).pdf |title=Federal Air Transport Agency Authorization |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title= Lakhta Center|accessdate= 22 January 2014|work= The Skyscraper Center|publisher= [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]}}</ref> The Lakhta Center is also the second-tallest structure in Russia and Europe, behind [[Ostankino Tower]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|title=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat, '100 Future tallest buildings in the world'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723110141/http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|archivedate=2012-07-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of Lakhta Center started on 30 October 2012; it was topped out on 29 January 2018.<ref name=\"installation\" >[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1295 The installation of the spire of the Lakhta Center], Press release of 29 January 2018.</ref> The Lakhta Center surpassed Vostok Tower of the [[Federation Tower|Federation Towers]] in Moscow as the tallest building in Russia and Europe on 5 October 2017. The center is designed for large-scale [[mixed-use development]], consisting of public facilities and offices.  The building was designed by [[RMJM]]. The project was then continued by GORPROJECT (2011-2017) based on the RMJM Concept (2011) under the main contractor, [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]. The Lakhta Center is intended to become the new headquarters of Russian energy company [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn December 24, 2018, Lakhta Center was certified according to the criteria of ecological efficiency at [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum<ref>[https://www.usgbc.org/projects/lakhta-centertower Lakhta Center-Tower]</ref> \u2013 it is one of the five most eco-friendly skyscrapers in the world.<ref>[https://realty.ria.ru/20191220/1562593482.html The Chronicles of the stone of greens, as buildings become energy efficient]</ref> The concrete pouring of the bottom slab of Lakhta Center's foundation was registered by [[Guinness World Records]] as the largest continuous concrete pour; 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were used, which is approximately 3,000 cubic meters more than in the previous record registered at [[Wilshire Grand Tower]].<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-continuous-concrete-pour/ Largest Continuous Concrete Pour]</ref> The tower's [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] is also the world\u2019s largest cold-bent facade by area.\n\nThe opening date of the complex will be determined after the completion of finishing and landscaping. The improvement of the embankments is planned to be completed at the end of 2020.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2019/08/08/Vozle_Lahti-centra_pojav Near the \"Lakhta center\" will be a public space with \" glass wings\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\n\nOn, 26 January 2012, it became known that [[Gazprom]] was planning to build a new harbor for yachts near Lakhta Center and Krestovsky Island. A new company for managing these sea assets was to be created.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/01/26/157/#comments \u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \"\u041b\u0435\u043d\u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\" \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u044f\u0445\u0442]</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2012, it was announced that a new metro station was to be constructed near Lakhta Center. This metro station's building was included in the City development plan of [[Leningrad]] in 1980 but only with the construction of the Lakhta Center did it again enter the agenda. The plan of the metro station's construction was to be finalized by the end of 2012.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/03/16/074/ \u0412\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0418\u0411\u0414\u0414 16.03.2012 13:26]</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2012 the permit for construction of the first stage of Lakhta Center, which included a skyscraper and stylobate, was obtained.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/08/20/114/ \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e]</ref>\nOn 31 August 2012, a public hearing on the topic of the layout and surveying of the site of the Lakhta Center was held in the administration of the Primorsky district of Saint Petersburg. Objects planned for placing in the area of construction, scheme of communications and transportation infrastructure were presented to the public.<ref>[http://izvestia.ru/news/534256 \u041d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433]</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nApproximately 3000 people will be employed in the construction, mostly from professions relating to design and construction. After construction, a few thousand workers of different occupations were expected to be employed in the complex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2235582|title=\"\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\"|date=2013-07-17|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n\nGeodesic, ecologic and soil investigations and design documentation for the project were prepared by GORPROJECT (Russia), NIIOSP (Russia), Petrochim-technologiya LLC (Russia) and Trest GRII JSC (Russia). In planning and executing works at the underground cycle, piling and producing construction materials such companies as [[Arabtec]] (UAE), [[Bauer Group]] (Germany), Geostroy CJSC (Russia), Inforsproekt CJSC (Russia) and Renaissance Construction (Turkey) take part. Verification calculations, working documentation development, optimisation of processes and technical supervision are performed by [[Arup Group Limited]] (Great Britain), [[Samsung C&T]] (Korea) and [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction]] (Great Britain). Project management is being done by [[AECOM]] (USA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/|title=Key Contractors|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n[http://www.exclusivadesign.com Exclusiva Design] (Italy) is key contractor for the interior design of public spaces.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/exclusiva/ Exclusiva Design]</ref><ref>[http://www.exclusivadesign.com/lakhta-center-exclusiva-wins-the-bid-to-design-the-public-spaces/?lang=en/ Lakhta Center: Exclusiva Design wins the Bid to Design the Public Spaces]</ref> German company Josef Gartner is in charge for the glazing of the skyscraper.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2015/09/16/Nemeckaja_Gartner_otkroet/ \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f Gartner \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref> Glazed facades of Entrance Arch as well as parts of Multi-functional building are done by [[Waagner-Biro]].\n\nOn 30 October 2012 the zero cycle works started. Zero cycle consists of the pit excavation, installation of the disk system, piling under the tower, multifunctional building and stylobate and construction of the foundation itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/current/|title= Lakhta Center. Project status|accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref>\n\n22 April 2014 the main potential general contractor for the construction of Lakhta Center was selected. It was Turkish Renaissance Construction company.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/news/?id=237 Potential general constructor selected]</ref> 22 May 2014 the contract for the construction of the foundation of one of the buildings in Lakhta Center was finally signed.\n\n<div>Lakhta Center Construction Time Schedule:</div>\n\n* March 2013 \u2013 zero cycle works are in process. Piles are being installed. According to the schedule of construction a [[diaphragm wall]] is to be completed by the end of April while piling works will continue until 15 August 2013.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=390991 \u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041e\u0414\u0426 \"\u041e\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0410.\u0411\u043e\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0412 \u201e\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\u201c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0439\"]</ref>\n* July 2013 \u2013 mounting of the 264 piles under the box-type foundation has been finished. Excavation of the foundation pit is in progress.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413160601/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php |date=13 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* September 2013 \u2013 total area of the site is announced to be increased from 330 to 400 thousand square meters due to a 700 parking space expansion to the planned parking spaces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |title=\u0421\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0418\u0422\u0415\u041b\u042c\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u041d\u0423\u041b\u0415\u0412\u041e\u0413\u041e \u0426\u0418\u041a\u041b\u0410 \"\u041b\u0410\u0425\u0422\u0410 \u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\" \u041e\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041b\u0418 \u0412 $100 \u041c\u041b\u041d |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128003246/http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |archive-date=28 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* October 2013 \u2013 construction of box-type foundation has been started. According to the plan this part of the work is to be finished in 2014.<ref>[http://advis.ru/php/view_news.php?id=763315EE-9CD4-6040-80D4-FA160CE9C441 \u0420\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043d\u0443\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0435 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\".]</ref>\n\n* December 2013 \u2013 mounting of the concrete disks to the [[diaphragm wall]] has started. Disks are to provide the diaphragm wall with more resistance to outside ground pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |title=\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431 \u0443 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430. |access-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317210545/http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* April 2014 \u2013 construction of foundation pit for the skyscraper is over.<ref>[http://karpovka.net/2014/04/02/137579/ \u0413\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref>\n* June 2014 \u2013 piling is completed. 264 piles were mounted for the tower of Lakhta Center, 848 piles were mounted for the mixed-use building and entrance arch and 968 piles were mounted for the stylobate (undergroung parking). All in all 2080 piles were dug in.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=892 All 2080 Piles in Lakhta Center Foundation]</ref>\n* September 2014 \u2013 excavation of the foundation pit for the mixed-use building has been finished. Foundation concreting has started.\n* February and March 2015 \u2013 the pouring of the bottom slab of the skyscraper's box shaped foundation over. 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were cast in the foundation.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2015/03/02/169/ Alexey Miller: First floors of the skyscraper in Lakhta will appear this year]</ref>\n* June 2015 \u2013 construction of the underground floors has finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 pouring of the 2m thick upper box foundation slab has been completed, which means that all works below zero elevation are finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 the construction of the first floors of the tower core is underway.<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=1087 Pouring of the Upper Slab of the Lakhta Center Tower Foundation]</ref>\n* January 2016 \u2013 construction of the succeeding ten floors of the tower; works on stylobate complex.\n* April 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 22-26. Installation of the metal farm in the 18-22nd floors of the tower.\n* May 2016 \u2013 glazing of the facade of the Tower has started.\n* September 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 46-50.<ref>[https://www.liebherr.com/en/deu/latest-news/news-press-releases/detail/liebherr-tower-cranes-in-action-erecting-the-highest-building-in-europe.html?news.type=press/ Liebherr tower cranes in action erecting the highest building in Europe]</ref>\n* December 2016 \u2013 installation of facade at floors 16-18; construction of the tower core at floors 57-61 \n* February 2017 \u2013 Lahkta Center's tower reaches height of 260 metres; floors 61-64 are under construction.\n* April 2017 -  height exceeds 300 meters, making Lakhta Center a [[supertall]] building (international classification), work is being done on the 67 floor.\n* May 2017 - the skyscraper reached the height 327,6 meters, working on the 78th floor.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2017/05/13/034/ Lakhta Center outgrew the tower]</ref>\n* August 2017 - Installation of the spire starts at 83 floors.\n* 5 October 2017 - Lakhta center became the tallest building in Europe when it reached a height of 374 meters.<ref>[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1280 European altitude record broken]</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/06/russian-skyscraper-becomes-europe-s-tallest-building# Russian skyscraper \u2018becomes Europe\u2019s tallest building]</ref>\n* 29 January 2018 - the height of Lakhta center project reached a height of 462 meters, the assembly of structures of the spire is completed. The glazing of the tower continues at floor 70.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Y-0SYU5sJU Lakhta Center reached the design height]</ref>\n* On 27 June 2018, the initial commissioning of the building was carried out. Technical documentation, building plan and technical passport were prepared.<ref>[https://www.archdaily.com/898132/europes-tallest-skyscraper-approaches-completion-in-st-petersburg Europe's Tallest Skyscraper Approaches Completion in St Petersburg]</ref>\n* On 16 October 2018, Lakhta Center MFC JSC received authorization for commissioning of the facility. The relevant document was officially published by the State Construction Supervision and Inspection Service of Saint Petersburg, Russia. There is about a year to go until the opening of Lakhta Center Multifunctional Complex, its dominant being the tallest skyscraper of Europe.<ref>[https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1321 Lakhta Center Officially Commissioned]</ref>\n\nNext to the already commissioned Lakhta Center, construction continues. To the four objects of the complex (tower, multi-purpose building, arch, stylobate) will be added one more. According to official documents, it takes place under the name \"Complex of buildings and structures\", or simply KZS.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/03/28/111/ \"Complex of buildings and structures\"]</ref>\n\nThe complex of buildings and structures is a single building consisting of two buildings connected by a courtyard. The authors of the project suggest that it will not only strengthen the office function of the Lakhta Center, but also complete the formation of the architectural ensemble, balancing the skyscraper in the horizontal.<ref>[https://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/345989-kzs-lahta \"Complex of buildings and structures\". It will be built at the \"Lakhta center\" in 2021]</ref> The total area of the Lakhta center is 400 000 m\u00b2. With the addition of the KZS, the total area of the complex is 570 000 m\u00b2.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=924846&sec=1679 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 Renaissance Construction]</ref>\n\n== Multi-functional building ==\nMulti-functional building (MFZ) - an object divided into two buildings - North and South, which are United by a common Foundation, stylobate and roof. The building resembles a boomerang. It has a variable number of storeys with a height difference from 7 to 17 floors, with the peak height being a little more than 80 meters. The building is approximately 300 meters long.  Feature - negative angle of the end facades due to the removal of the console on 25 m. Facades - glass, with a total area of more than 60 thousand m2.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371535/ Horizontal versus vertical. Or for? Why Lakhta Center \"recumbent\" dominant]</ref>\n\nConstructive scheme of the building - frame. More than 24 thousand tons of metal structures were used for the construction of this facility.\n\nThe main load-bearing elements are 4 reinforced concrete cores which perceive horizontal and vertical loadings, transferring them to the base executed in the form of the plate grillage leaning against piles. Between the Southern and Northern buildings of the MFZ along the entire height of the atrium, with a roof of translucent polymer membranes ETFE. In the space of the atrium, transitional bridges are spanned, which serve as observation points. Atrium is a pedestrian area from which you can get to any of the objects of the building.\n\nThe MFZ will house a number of public spaces - for example, a planetarium in the shape of a ball or a seven-storey hall-transformer, which can take different configurations: from the classical parquet to the amphitheater.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Facilities ===\nLakhta Center will contain offices, a [[co-working]] center, a sports center, a children's science center, and a conference center. The project includes 1,500 square meters of indoor exhibition space. Part of the open area will be used to demonstrate art, installations and sculptures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/ru/press/gallery/presentation/?id=445|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> There will be a free public observation deck at the top of the skyscraper at a height of 357m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/objects/viewpoint/|title=Observation deck {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/08/19/122/|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0443 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=2014-08-19|accessdate=2018-07-30|language=ru}}</ref> Planetarium - a 19-meter sparkling ball on the surface of which are 1223 curved triangular stainless steel sheets, polished to a shine. A very accurate projection of the starry sky is formed by a star machine (Japanese projector - Ohira Tech Megastar-IIA ). Larger objects, artificial aircraft, visual effects and much more are created by a projection system with a resolution of 8K at the meridian, which uses 10 Sony GTZ280 laser projectors. Five projectors illuminate the lower tier of the dome, four the top, and one forms an image at the [[zenith]]. Thus, a total resolution of 48 483 533 pixels is achieved.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/447764/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441! \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430]</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\n* The main entrance of Lakhta Center is designed to be an [[arch]]. The height of the arch is almost 24m while its length is 98m.\n* There will be 34 elevators in the tower, but not all of them will travel to the top floor. The mixed-use building will contain 62 elevators. Besides these elevators there will be special firefighter lifts constructed to be used in case of emergency. The total capacity of all elevators is up to 1,280 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nvspb.ru/stories/neboskreby-menyayut-soznanie-sociuma-52309|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0451\u0431\u044b \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0443\u043c\u0430\" {{!}} \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|website=www.nvspb.ru|language=ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* Lakhta Center's foundation is going to be concreted continuously in round-the-clock mode. Constructors plan to pour 24,000 cubic metres in 48 hours. The volume of concrete to be poured under the mixed-use building near the tower is 48,000 cubic metres. This volume is large enough to be included in the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=447425 Construction director of Lakhta Center Elena Morozova: \"We will become record-holders due to the volume of concrete poured\"]</ref>\n* Around 400,000 cubic meters of concrete will be used for Lakhta Center's construction. During the first stage of foundation concreting 8,500 cubic meters of concrete will be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dp.ru/a/2014/12/08/Beton_dlja_Lahta_Centra/|title=\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"|website=www.dp.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* The area of glazing of the Tower totals 72,500 square meters as the area of the glazing for the complex in the whole makes up 130,000 square meters.<ref>[http://www.megapolis-online.ru/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. 462 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f]</ref>\n* Lakhta Center is designed to a high safety standard, which allows it to stand on one core even if all ten supportive columns collapse. The core structure is up to the highest fire rating. The building is designed to be able to withstand a four-hour fire without any structural damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.popmech.ru/technologies/48791-kak-stroitsya-lakhta-tsentr-v-sankt-peterburge/#full|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u00ab\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435|work=Popmech.ru|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n* On December 31, 2018 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlwYShApM9U Green Christmas lights] were lit on the skyscraper, thus turning the building into the highest Christmas tree in Europe<ref>[https://forpost-sz.ru/a/2018-12-31/lakhta-centr-prevratili-v-samuyu-vysokuyu-yolku-evropy The tallest Christmas tree in Europe]</ref>\n* On June 28, 2019, an automatic weather station was installed at the highest point of the spire (462 meters), which monitors temperature, humidity, wind direction and speed.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/06/28/053/ From Lakhta Center will now monitor the weather. On the spire of the St. Petersburg skyscraper appeared weather station]</ref>\n* 2019 - the Lakhta center complex became the leader in the number of nominations for the Award of Excellence and Urban Habitat.<ref>[https://tallinnovation.com/program/projects-featured/ Award of Excellence Winners]</ref> It was a finalist in five categories: Best high-rise building of 400 meters and higher; Construction award; Award in the field of construction engineering; award in the field of geotechnical engineering; award for facade engineering.\n\n=== Innovations ===\nIn order to provide more effective fire-fighting, a HI-FOG water mist suppression system will be used. When the temperature exceeds 57&nbsp;\u00b0C, sprinklers creating a water mist will start working automatically. Along with the sprinklers, there will be drenchers which could be switched on manually or by the means of remote control in order to create a water curtain in an emergency.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e \u041e\u0431 \u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193513/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Lakhta Center is also set to be the first skyscraper in St. Petersburg where an ice formation control system will be used. Heating of the glass at high floors will prevent ice accumulation and help maintain good visibility. The spire of the Tower will be made from metal gauze to prevent a layer of ice forming in winter.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e. \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440: \u043b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043c] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193302/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> The consumption of material and energy resources will be decreased due to conversion of kinetic energy of the Center's workers and visitors' steps to electric energy.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.regnum.ru/news/realestate/1784199.html \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\" \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435: \u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0448\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\"]</ref>\nDuring migration periods of birds special illumination will be used to light the tower.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2015/05/06_a_6668381.shtml Lakhta Center Skyscraper Continues to Surprise with its Technologies]</ref>\n\n=== Environmental technologies ===\nWhile designing Lakhta Center several \"green\" and energy-saving technologies were planned for further application. They are\n\n* Double facade. Usage of double glazing will help to increase the level of thermal insulation, which allowed the designers to reduce costs for heating and conditioning.\n* Usage of the excess heat generated by working technical equipment for the heating of premises.\n* Usage of equipment with reduced noise level along with noise suppressors, sound-proof curtain walls and [[floating floor]]s.\n* Usage of economical infrared radiators.\n* Usage of contactless sensors or [[motion detectors]] for economizing electric energy and water.\n* Mounting of the systems supporting the optimal level of temperature and humidity inside the building.\n* Smart waste disposal system which improves hygiene and reduces CO2 emissions. Also wastes are sorted, which is one of the essential principles of green construction. Waste disposal is required by 20 times less frequent than in a conventional system.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html Lakhta Center: 462 meters above the sea level] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208073228/http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html |date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>\n* Constructing of the ice storages which will accumulate up to 1000 tons of ice at night for air conditioning during the daytime. It will help to reduce the differences in the usage of electricity during the night and day periods. It also allows reducing expenditures on electric power on the account of the differences in tariffs for day and night usage of electricity. As the cooling of the building is to be made using accumulative ice generators it will be possible to save on electricity expenditures up to 13 thousand rubles a day.\n* In support to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] and FLAP's (Fatal Light Awareness Program) \"Bird - Friendly Building Program\", Lakhta Center's illumination will be designed so to make the building bird-safe especially in the periods of migration of birds (autumn, winter). The system of the illumination intensity and color change is under development at the moment.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami Lakhta Center is eager to make friends with birds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428052153/http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami |date=28 April 2017 }}</ref>\n* Due to the peculiarities of the highly humid and windy climate in the North Western region of Russia the possibility of icing up of buildings is relatively high. In order to prevent complete icing up of the spire of the Lakhta Center's tower engineers changed glassing to the metal gauze.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=544242&sec=1671 \u0421\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e 13 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0440\u0443\u0431. \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n* In order to provide Lakhta Center and adjoining areas with electricity without making any extra burden on existing infrastructure a new standalone power substation \"Nevskaya guba\" will be constructed.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://asninfo.ru/news/v-lahte-postroyat-podstanciyu-nevskaya-guba \"Nevskaya guba\" power substation will be built in Lakhta]</ref>\n\nAll in all, while constructing Lakhta Center approximately 100 [[innovation]]s are to be used. It lets increase the indexes of energy saving by 40% compared to the buildings where standard technologies are in use.\n\nIn experts' opinion, period of recoupment of using green and energy-saving technologies in Lakhta Center may be at about 20 years though Lakhta Center's Projection department's specialists think that this figure is a bit overestimated.\n\n===Transportation development===\nLakhta Center's construction raises a problem of transportation development because of the expected growth of the traffic flow in the region. Two traffic circles are to be built near Lakhta Center. These will become part of the \u041c32\u0410 highway in the future.<ref>[http://www.spbdnevnik.ru/news/2014-07-10/dva-razvorotnykh-koltsa-poyavyatsya-v-primorskom-rayone/]</ref>\nA light rail service from [[Finland Railway Station]] and a new tram line from Primorskaya underground station will be built to serve Lakhta Center. Plans are ongoing to build a new underground station with the working title of \"Lakhta\".<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/transport/ Transport Infrastructure Development]</ref> Bicycle lanes near Lakhta Center with 90 parking places for bicycles are also planned.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/07/15/138/ \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044b \u041c-32 \u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043a\u0443]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f |access-date=18 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413143303/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\nAs the [[Historic Centre of Saint Petersburg and Related Groups of Monuments|historical center of St. Petersburg]] has become a [[World Heritage Site]] since 1990; The [[World Heritage Committee]] opposed the construction of the 400-metre tower of [[Okhta Center]] as it would affect the cityscape of historic Saint Petersburg.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/612 UNESCO welcomes backing by President of Russian Federation for the preservation of St Petersburg]</ref> In December 2006 [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre Director Francesco Bandarin reminded Russia about its obligations to preserve it and expressed concern over the project.<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2006/12/05/117081 UNESCO is worried] by Elena Ragozina, [[Vedomosti]] #229 (1756), 5 December 2006 (in Russian).</ref> In 2007, the [[World Monuments Fund]] placed the historic skyline of St. Petersburg on its 2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites due to the potential construction of the building, and in 2009 reported that the tower \"would damage the image of Russia.\"<ref name=BBCUNESCO>{{Cite news |title=Russian tower plans cause alarm |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8272401.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}</ref> During the 36 session of the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO held in Saint Petersburg in 2012 it was stated that a large area of Saint-Petersburg falls within preservation and buffer zones provided for UNESCO World Heritage Sites. That is why it is good for the city that the Okhta Center, which had been planned by Gazprom in front of Smolny Cathedral was moved to Lakhta.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/sessions/36COM 36th session of the Committee of the World Heritage Committee]</ref> Eleonora Mitrofanova, Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to UNESCO noticed that the approved construction project for Lakhta Center is located far from the buffer zone and the historical center, so in theory Gazprom is not even obliged to ask UNESCO. However, the government authorities will definitely have consultations for the project with UNESCO. Now we are working to clarify the boundaries of the World Heritage zone and the boundaries of the buffer zone.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=326845&sec=1671 \u0412\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0420\u0424 \u0432 \u042e\u041d\u0415\u0421\u041a\u041e]</ref>\n\nThe project being moved to Lakhta didn't stop the discussions. On 11 April 2012, ex-governor of St. Petersburg and now Federation Council chairwoman Valentina Matvienko said to journalists that the \"Lakhta center could become a new symbol of the city and attract the businessmen from all over the world to St. Petersburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/sorokina/876139-echo/ |title=\"In the light circle\", the interview with Ms.Matvienko at \"Echo Moskvy\" |publisher=Echo.msk.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Russia in 2011 the Chairman of the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] Professor Sang-Dae Kim was treated to a presentation of a project of Lakhta Center. Professor Kim commented on the \"modern shape\" of the proposed Lakhta Center, which according to him had \"nothing in common with ordinary boxes\".<ref>[http://www.ctbuh.org/Events/ToursVisits/ProfKimVisitstoSEAsiaRussia/ProfKimvisitRussia/tabid/2778/language/en-US/Default.aspx CTBUH Meeting: Russia]</ref> He also stated that something new ought to be created, which can be shown to new generations in 200\u2013300 years as for them what is created nowadays will be the same history as the architecture of the 18-19th centuries for us today. Professor also noticed that the project reminds him of an oriental concept [[Yin Yang]]: on the one hand, the historic part of the city with horizontal buildings and water, and on the other hand, a vertical which will add additional charm to the city. Lakhta Center combines an interesting form and modern technologies, so up to Mr. Kim, with the lapse of time the Center can become a new symbol of Saint Petersburg.<ref>[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2011/09/07_a_3759709.shtml Without skyscrapers Russia is the Kremlin and the Red Army]</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2012, St. Petersburg governor Georgiy Poltavchenko emphasized in his annual report for House of Assembly the necessity of building a new \"city\" in St. Petersburg. According to Mr Poltavchenko, there are three appropriate districts for that: Lakhta center, Pulkovo and [[aggradation|aggradated]] territories near Waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/05/15/056/ |title=Poltavchenko: Petersburg needs a new business center and town-planning dictation |publisher=Fontanka.ru |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Construction gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Site's view prior to construction.jpg|Site's view prior to construction, July 2012.\nFile:Aerial view of the construction site of Lakhta Center in Saint Petersburg, November 2014.jpg|Panoramic view of the construction site, November 2014.\nFile:Piling process.jpg|Piling process\nFile:Construction of the foundation under the Tower.jpg|Construction of the foundation under the Tower\nFile:Foundations of the Tower and mixed-use building are ready.jpg|Foundations of the tower and mixed-use building are ready\nFile:Lakhta Center.jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2015\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Feb, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0438\u044e\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Jul, 2016\nFile:Lakhta_Center_Oktober_2016.jpg|The state of the construction as of October, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Skyscraper at the end of 2016. Height is 245 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c 2017).jpg|Skyscraper in April 2017. Height is 310 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u0439 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2017. Height is 323 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in September 2017. Height is 365 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440, \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.jpg|Lakhta Center in January 2018. Installation of the spire, height of about 450 meters\nFile:Lakhta Center orig.jpg|Skyscraper at the end of February 2018. Installation of the spire is complete, glazing of the tower and spire continues.\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u044f\u043a).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2018.\nFile:Das Lachta Zentr- \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 2H1A5980WI.jpg| June 2018\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2018).jpg|Lakhta Center in November 2018\nFile:2-\u044f \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044c \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Construction of the 2nd stage (November 2018)\nFile:Lakhta Center at night in april 2019.jpg|April 2019\nFile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Skyscraper lighting\nFile:Lakhta Center, spire.jpg|The spire of the skyscraper (General view).\nFile:\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445 \u0448\u043f\u0438\u043b\u044f \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|The top of the spire. Floodlight projectors are integrated in it\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Russia]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n* [[List of twisted buildings]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/ Official site of Lakhta Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070401024640/http://www.ohta-center.ru/ Official Site of the Okhta Center project]\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/future/view/ Visual Analysis projecting the appearance of the tower at the Lakhta site, from various points in St. Petersburg]\n* [https://ru-ru.facebook.com/lakhtacenter.ru/ Official social media page]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Russia]]\n[[Category:Gazprom]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Twisted buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}{{Infobox building\n| name = Lakhta Center\n| native_name = \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| former_names = Gazprom Tower, [[Okhta Center]]\n| alternate_names = \n| status = {{Color|green|Completed}}\n| image = Saint Petersburg Lakhta center 06.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = July 2018\n| location = [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|59|59|13.7|N|30|10|37.3|E|region:RU|display=inline,title}}\n| address = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = Russia\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = 2012\n| completion_date = 2019\n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT\n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Gazprom Neft]]\n| cost = US$1.77 billion<ref>[https://realty.rbc.ru/news/5bed46bd9a794728d6707196]</ref>\n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 87\n| awards = \n| parking = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| highest_region = \n| highest_reflabel = \n| highest_prev = \n| highest_start = \n| highest_end = \n| highest_next = \n| map_type = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| altitude = \n| building_type = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| current_tenants = \n| renovation_date = \n| height = {{convert|462|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| architectural = \n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| observatory = \n| other_dimensions = \n| elevator_count = 40<ref>[https://habr.com/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371087/ Elevators in a skyscraper]</ref>\n| architecture_firm = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT<ref>[https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/europes-tallest-skyscraper-lakhta-centre Europe's tallest skyscraper is nearing completion in St. Petersburg]</ref>\n| main_contractor = [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]\n| designations = \n| url = \n}}\nThe '''Lakhta Center''' ({{Lang-rus|\u041b\u0430\u0301\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0442\u0440|r=Lakhta tsentr}}) is an 87-story [[skyscraper]] built in the outskirts of [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]. Standing {{convert|462|m|ft}} tall, the Lakhta Center is the [[List of tallest buildings in Russia|tallest building in Russia]], the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest building in Europe]], and the [[List of tallest buildings|16th-tallest building in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title=Lakhta Center - The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/ru/about/project/ |title=Lakhta Center Website, \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/uploaded/file_list/ROSAVIA706(19.07.2011).pdf |title=Federal Air Transport Agency Authorization |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title= Lakhta Center|accessdate= 22 January 2014|work= The Skyscraper Center|publisher= [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]}}</ref> The Lakhta Center is also the second-tallest structure in Russia and Europe, behind [[Ostankino Tower]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|title=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat, '100 Future tallest buildings in the world'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723110141/http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|archivedate=2012-07-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of Lakhta Center started on 30 October 2012; it was topped out on 29 January 2018.<ref name=\"installation\" >[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1295 The installation of the spire of the Lakhta Center], Press release of 29 January 2018.</ref> The Lakhta Center surpassed Vostok Tower of the [[Federation Tower|Federation Towers]] in Moscow as the tallest building in Russia and Europe on 5 October 2017. The center is designed for large-scale [[mixed-use development]], consisting of public facilities and offices.  The building was designed by [[RMJM]]. The project was then continued by GORPROJECT (2011-2017) based on the RMJM Concept (2011) under the main contractor, [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]. The Lakhta Center is intended to become the new headquarters of Russian energy company [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn December 24, 2018, Lakhta Center was certified according to the criteria of ecological efficiency at [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum<ref>[https://www.usgbc.org/projects/lakhta-centertower Lakhta Center-Tower]</ref> \u2013 it is one of the five most eco-friendly skyscrapers in the world.<ref>[https://realty.ria.ru/20191220/1562593482.html The Chronicles of the stone of greens, as buildings become energy efficient]</ref> The concrete pouring of the bottom slab of Lakhta Center's foundation was registered by [[Guinness World Records]] as the largest continuous concrete pour; 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were used, which is approximately 3,000 cubic meters more than in the previous record registered at [[Wilshire Grand Tower]].<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-continuous-concrete-pour/ Largest Continuous Concrete Pour]</ref> The tower's [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] is also the world\u2019s largest cold-bent facade by area.\n\nThe opening date of the complex will be determined after the completion of finishing and landscaping. The improvement of the embankments is planned to be completed at the end of 2020.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2019/08/08/Vozle_Lahti-centra_pojav Near the \"Lakhta center\" will be a public space with \" glass wings\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\n\nOn, 26 January 2012, it became known that [[Gazprom]] was planning to build a new harbor for yachts near Lakhta Center and Krestovsky Island. A new company for managing these sea assets was to be created.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/01/26/157/#comments \u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \"\u041b\u0435\u043d\u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\" \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u044f\u0445\u0442]</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2012, it was announced that a new metro station was to be constructed near Lakhta Center. This metro station's building was included in the City development plan of [[Leningrad]] in 1980 but only with the construction of the Lakhta Center did it again enter the agenda. The plan of the metro station's construction was to be finalized by the end of 2012.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/03/16/074/ \u0412\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0418\u0411\u0414\u0414 16.03.2012 13:26]</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2012 the permit for construction of the first stage of Lakhta Center, which included a skyscraper and stylobate, was obtained.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/08/20/114/ \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e]</ref>\nOn 31 August 2012, a public hearing on the topic of the layout and surveying of the site of the Lakhta Center was held in the administration of the Primorsky district of Saint Petersburg. Objects planned for placing in the area of construction, scheme of communications and transportation infrastructure were presented to the public.<ref>[http://izvestia.ru/news/534256 \u041d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433]</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nApproximately 3000 people will be employed in the construction, mostly from professions relating to design and construction. After construction, a few thousand workers of different occupations were expected to be employed in the complex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2235582|title=\"\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\"|date=2013-07-17|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n\nGeodesic, ecologic and soil investigations and design documentation for the project were prepared by GORPROJECT (Russia), NIIOSP (Russia), Petrochim-technologiya LLC (Russia) and Trest GRII JSC (Russia). In planning and executing works at the underground cycle, piling and producing construction materials such companies as [[Arabtec]] (UAE), [[Bauer Group]] (Germany), Geostroy CJSC (Russia), Inforsproekt CJSC (Russia) and Renaissance Construction (Turkey) take part. Verification calculations, working documentation development, optimisation of processes and technical supervision are performed by [[Arup Group Limited]] (Great Britain), [[Samsung C&T]] (Korea) and [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction]] (Great Britain). Project management is being done by [[AECOM]] (USA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/|title=Key Contractors|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n[http://www.exclusivadesign.com Exclusiva Design] (Italy) is key contractor for the interior design of public spaces.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/exclusiva/ Exclusiva Design]</ref><ref>[http://www.exclusivadesign.com/lakhta-center-exclusiva-wins-the-bid-to-design-the-public-spaces/?lang=en/ Lakhta Center: Exclusiva Design wins the Bid to Design the Public Spaces]</ref> German company Josef Gartner is in charge for the glazing of the skyscraper.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2015/09/16/Nemeckaja_Gartner_otkroet/ \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f Gartner \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref> Glazed facades of Entrance Arch as well as parts of Multi-functional building are done by [[Waagner-Biro]].\n\nOn 30 October 2012 the zero cycle works started. Zero cycle consists of the pit excavation, installation of the disk system, piling under the tower, multifunctional building and stylobate and construction of the foundation itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/current/|title= Lakhta Center. Project status|accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref>\n\n22 April 2014 the main potential general contractor for the construction of Lakhta Center was selected. It was Turkish Renaissance Construction company.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/news/?id=237 Potential general constructor selected]</ref> 22 May 2014 the contract for the construction of the foundation of one of the buildings in Lakhta Center was finally signed.\n\n<div>Lakhta Center Construction Time Schedule:</div>\n\n* March 2013 \u2013 zero cycle works are in process. Piles are being installed. According to the schedule of construction a [[diaphragm wall]] is to be completed by the end of April while piling works will continue until 15 August 2013.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=390991 \u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041e\u0414\u0426 \"\u041e\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0410.\u0411\u043e\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0412 \u201e\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\u201c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0439\"]</ref>\n* July 2013 \u2013 mounting of the 264 piles under the box-type foundation has been finished. Excavation of the foundation pit is in progress.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413160601/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php |date=13 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* September 2013 \u2013 total area of the site is announced to be increased from 330 to 400 thousand square meters due to a 700 parking space expansion to the planned parking spaces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |title=\u0421\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0418\u0422\u0415\u041b\u042c\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u041d\u0423\u041b\u0415\u0412\u041e\u0413\u041e \u0426\u0418\u041a\u041b\u0410 \"\u041b\u0410\u0425\u0422\u0410 \u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\" \u041e\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041b\u0418 \u0412 $100 \u041c\u041b\u041d |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128003246/http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |archive-date=28 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* October 2013 \u2013 construction of box-type foundation has been started. According to the plan this part of the work is to be finished in 2014.<ref>[http://advis.ru/php/view_news.php?id=763315EE-9CD4-6040-80D4-FA160CE9C441 \u0420\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043d\u0443\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0435 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\".]</ref>\n\n* December 2013 \u2013 mounting of the concrete disks to the [[diaphragm wall]] has started. Disks are to provide the diaphragm wall with more resistance to outside ground pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |title=\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431 \u0443 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430. |access-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317210545/http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* April 2014 \u2013 construction of foundation pit for the skyscraper is over.<ref>[http://karpovka.net/2014/04/02/137579/ \u0413\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref>\n* June 2014 \u2013 piling is completed. 264 piles were mounted for the tower of Lakhta Center, 848 piles were mounted for the mixed-use building and entrance arch and 968 piles were mounted for the stylobate (undergroung parking). All in all 2080 piles were dug in.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=892 All 2080 Piles in Lakhta Center Foundation]</ref>\n* September 2014 \u2013 excavation of the foundation pit for the mixed-use building has been finished. Foundation concreting has started.\n* February and March 2015 \u2013 the pouring of the bottom slab of the skyscraper's box shaped foundation over. 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were cast in the foundation.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2015/03/02/169/ Alexey Miller: First floors of the skyscraper in Lakhta will appear this year]</ref>\n* June 2015 \u2013 construction of the underground floors has finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 pouring of the 2m thick upper box foundation slab has been completed, which means that all works below zero elevation are finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 the construction of the first floors of the tower core is underway.<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=1087 Pouring of the Upper Slab of the Lakhta Center Tower Foundation]</ref>\n* January 2016 \u2013 construction of the succeeding ten floors of the tower; works on stylobate complex.\n* April 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 22-26. Installation of the metal farm in the 18-22nd floors of the tower.\n* May 2016 \u2013 glazing of the facade of the Tower has started.\n* September 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 46-50.<ref>[https://www.liebherr.com/en/deu/latest-news/news-press-releases/detail/liebherr-tower-cranes-in-action-erecting-the-highest-building-in-europe.html?news.type=press/ Liebherr tower cranes in action erecting the highest building in Europe]</ref>\n* December 2016 \u2013 installation of facade at floors 16-18; construction of the tower core at floors 57-61 \n* February 2017 \u2013 Lahkta Center's tower reaches height of 260 metres; floors 61-64 are under construction.\n* April 2017 -  height exceeds 300 meters, making Lakhta Center a [[supertall]] building (international classification), work is being done on the 67 floor.\n* May 2017 - the skyscraper reached the height 327,6 meters, working on the 78th floor.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2017/05/13/034/ Lakhta Center outgrew the tower]</ref>\n* August 2017 - Installation of the spire starts at 83 floors.\n* 5 October 2017 - Lakhta center became the tallest building in Europe when it reached a height of 374 meters.<ref>[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1280 European altitude record broken]</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/06/russian-skyscraper-becomes-europe-s-tallest-building# Russian skyscraper \u2018becomes Europe\u2019s tallest building]</ref>\n* 29 January 2018 - the height of Lakhta center project reached a height of 462 meters, the assembly of structures of the spire is completed. The glazing of the tower continues at floor 70.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Y-0SYU5sJU Lakhta Center reached the design height]</ref>\n* On 27 June 2018, the initial commissioning of the building was carried out. Technical documentation, building plan and technical passport were prepared.<ref>[https://www.archdaily.com/898132/europes-tallest-skyscraper-approaches-completion-in-st-petersburg Europe's Tallest Skyscraper Approaches Completion in St Petersburg]</ref>\n* On 16 October 2018, Lakhta Center MFC JSC received authorization for commissioning of the facility. The relevant document was officially published by the State Construction Supervision and Inspection Service of Saint Petersburg, Russia. There is about a year to go until the opening of Lakhta Center Multifunctional Complex, its dominant being the tallest skyscraper of Europe.<ref>[https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1321 Lakhta Center Officially Commissioned]</ref>\n\nNext to the already commissioned Lakhta Center, construction continues. To the four objects of the complex (tower, multi-purpose building, arch, stylobate) will be added one more. According to official documents, it takes place under the name \"Complex of buildings and structures\", or simply KZS.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/03/28/111/ \"Complex of buildings and structures\"]</ref>\n\nThe complex of buildings and structures is a single building consisting of two buildings connected by a courtyard. The authors of the project suggest that it will not only strengthen the office function of the Lakhta Center, but also complete the formation of the architectural ensemble, balancing the skyscraper in the horizontal.<ref>[https://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/345989-kzs-lahta \"Complex of buildings and structures\". It will be built at the \"Lakhta center\" in 2021]</ref> The total area of the Lakhta center is 400 000 m\u00b2. With the addition of the KZS, the total area of the complex is 570 000 m\u00b2.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=924846&sec=1679 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 Renaissance Construction]</ref>\n\n== Multi-functional building ==\nMulti-functional building (MFZ) - an object divided into two buildings - North and South, which are United by a common Foundation, stylobate and roof. The building resembles a boomerang. It has a variable number of storeys with a height difference from 7 to 17 floors, with the peak height being a little more than 80 meters. The building is approximately 300 meters long.  Feature - negative angle of the end facades due to the removal of the console on 25 m. Facades - glass, with a total area of more than 60 thousand m2.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371535/ Horizontal versus vertical. Or for? Why Lakhta Center \"recumbent\" dominant]</ref>\n\nConstructive scheme of the building - frame. More than 24 thousand tons of metal structures were used for the construction of this facility.\n\nThe main load-bearing elements are 4 reinforced concrete cores which perceive horizontal and vertical loadings, transferring them to the base executed in the form of the plate grillage leaning against piles. Between the Southern and Northern buildings of the MFZ along the entire height of the atrium, with a roof of translucent polymer membranes ETFE. In the space of the atrium, transitional bridges are spanned, which serve as observation points. Atrium is a pedestrian area from which you can get to any of the objects of the building.\n\nThe MFZ will house a number of public spaces - for example, a planetarium in the shape of a ball or a seven-storey hall-transformer, which can take different configurations: from the classical parquet to the amphitheater.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Facilities ===\nLakhta Center will contain offices, a [[co-working]] center, a sports center, a children's science center, and a conference center. Lakhta Center's project includes 1,500 square meters of indoor exhibition space. Part of the open area will be used to demonstrate objects of art, installations and sculptures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/ru/press/gallery/presentation/?id=445|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> There will be a free public observation deck at the top of the skyscraper at the height of 357m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/objects/viewpoint/|title=Observation deck {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/08/19/122/|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0443 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=2014-08-19|accessdate=2018-07-30|language=ru}}</ref> Planetarium - a 19-meter sparkling ball on the surface of which 1223 curved triangular stainless steel sheet, polished to a Shine. The most accurate projection of the starry sky is formed by a star machine (Japanese projector - Ohira Tech Megastar-IIA ), and larger objects, artificial aircraft, visual effects and much more \u2013 digital, created by a projection system with a resolution of 8K Meridian, which uses 10 laser 4K projectors SONY GTZ280. Five projectors illuminate the lower tier of the dome, four \u2013 the top, and one forms an image at the Zenith. Thus, the total resolution in 48 483 533 pixels.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/447764/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441! \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430]</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\n* The main entrance of Lakhta Center is designed to be an [[arch]]. The height of the arch is almost 24m while its length is 98m.\n* There will be 34 elevators in the tower, but not all of them will travel to the top floor. The mixed-use building will contain 62 elevators. Besides these elevators there will be special firefighter lifts constructed to be used in case of emergency. The total capacity of all elevators is up to 1,280 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nvspb.ru/stories/neboskreby-menyayut-soznanie-sociuma-52309|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0451\u0431\u044b \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0443\u043c\u0430\" {{!}} \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|website=www.nvspb.ru|language=ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* Lakhta Center's foundation is going to be concreted continuously in round-the-clock mode. Constructors plan to pour 24,000 cubic metres in 48 hours. The volume of concrete to be poured under the mixed-use building near the tower is 48,000 cubic metres. This volume is large enough to be included in the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=447425 Construction director of Lakhta Center Elena Morozova: \"We will become record-holders due to the volume of concrete poured\"]</ref>\n* Around 400,000 cubic meters of concrete will be used for Lakhta Center's construction. During the first stage of foundation concreting 8,500 cubic meters of concrete will be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dp.ru/a/2014/12/08/Beton_dlja_Lahta_Centra/|title=\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"|website=www.dp.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* The area of glazing of the Tower totals 72,500 square meters as the area of the glazing for the complex in the whole makes up 130,000 square meters.<ref>[http://www.megapolis-online.ru/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. 462 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f]</ref>\n* Lakhta Center is designed to a high safety standard, which allows it to stand on one core even if all ten supportive columns collapse. The core structure is up to the highest fire rating. The building is designed to be able to withstand a four-hour fire without any structural damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.popmech.ru/technologies/48791-kak-stroitsya-lakhta-tsentr-v-sankt-peterburge/#full|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u00ab\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435|work=Popmech.ru|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n* On December 31, 2018 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlwYShApM9U Green Christmas lights] were lit on the skyscraper, thus turning the building into the highest Christmas tree in Europe<ref>[https://forpost-sz.ru/a/2018-12-31/lakhta-centr-prevratili-v-samuyu-vysokuyu-yolku-evropy The tallest Christmas tree in Europe]</ref>\n* On June 28, 2019, an automatic weather station was installed at the highest point of the spire (462 meters), which monitors temperature, humidity, wind direction and speed.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/06/28/053/ From Lakhta Center will now monitor the weather. On the spire of the St. Petersburg skyscraper appeared weather station]</ref>\n* 2019 - the Lakhta center complex became the leader in the number of nominations for the Award of Excellence and Urban Habitat.<ref>[https://tallinnovation.com/program/projects-featured/ Award of Excellence Winners]</ref> It was a finalist in five categories: Best high-rise building of 400 meters and higher; Construction award; Award in the field of construction engineering; award in the field of geotechnical engineering; award for facade engineering.\n\n=== Innovations ===\nIn order to provide more effective fire-fighting, a HI-FOG water mist suppression system will be used. When the temperature exceeds 57&nbsp;\u00b0C, sprinklers creating a water mist will start working automatically. Along with the sprinklers, there will be drenchers which could be switched on manually or by the means of remote control in order to create a water curtain in an emergency.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e \u041e\u0431 \u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193513/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Lakhta Center is also set to be the first skyscraper in St. Petersburg where an ice formation control system will be used. Heating of the glass at high floors will prevent ice accumulation and help maintain good visibility. The spire of the Tower will be made from metal gauze to prevent a layer of ice forming in winter.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e. \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440: \u043b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043c] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193302/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> The consumption of material and energy resources will be decreased due to conversion of kinetic energy of the Center's workers and visitors' steps to electric energy.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.regnum.ru/news/realestate/1784199.html \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\" \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435: \u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0448\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\"]</ref>\nDuring migration periods of birds special illumination will be used to light the tower.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2015/05/06_a_6668381.shtml Lakhta Center Skyscraper Continues to Surprise with its Technologies]</ref>\n\n=== Environmental technologies ===\nWhile designing Lakhta Center several \"green\" and energy-saving technologies were planned for further application. They are\n\n* Double facade. Usage of double glazing will help to increase the level of thermal insulation, which allowed the designers to reduce costs for heating and conditioning.\n* Usage of the excess heat generated by working technical equipment for the heating of premises.\n* Usage of equipment with reduced noise level along with noise suppressors, sound-proof curtain walls and [[floating floor]]s.\n* Usage of economical infrared radiators.\n* Usage of contactless sensors or [[motion detectors]] for economizing electric energy and water.\n* Mounting of the systems supporting the optimal level of temperature and humidity inside the building.\n* Smart waste disposal system which improves hygiene and reduces CO2 emissions. Also wastes are sorted, which is one of the essential principles of green construction. Waste disposal is required by 20 times less frequent than in a conventional system.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html Lakhta Center: 462 meters above the sea level] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208073228/http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html |date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>\n* Constructing of the ice storages which will accumulate up to 1000 tons of ice at night for air conditioning during the daytime. It will help to reduce the differences in the usage of electricity during the night and day periods. It also allows reducing expenditures on electric power on the account of the differences in tariffs for day and night usage of electricity. As the cooling of the building is to be made using accumulative ice generators it will be possible to save on electricity expenditures up to 13 thousand rubles a day.\n* In support to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] and FLAP's (Fatal Light Awareness Program) \"Bird - Friendly Building Program\", Lakhta Center's illumination will be designed so to make the building bird-safe especially in the periods of migration of birds (autumn, winter). The system of the illumination intensity and color change is under development at the moment.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami Lakhta Center is eager to make friends with birds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428052153/http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami |date=28 April 2017 }}</ref>\n* Due to the peculiarities of the highly humid and windy climate in the North Western region of Russia the possibility of icing up of buildings is relatively high. In order to prevent complete icing up of the spire of the Lakhta Center's tower engineers changed glassing to the metal gauze.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=544242&sec=1671 \u0421\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e 13 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0440\u0443\u0431. \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n* In order to provide Lakhta Center and adjoining areas with electricity without making any extra burden on existing infrastructure a new standalone power substation \"Nevskaya guba\" will be constructed.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://asninfo.ru/news/v-lahte-postroyat-podstanciyu-nevskaya-guba \"Nevskaya guba\" power substation will be built in Lakhta]</ref>\n\nAll in all, while constructing Lakhta Center approximately 100 [[innovation]]s are to be used. It lets increase the indexes of energy saving by 40% compared to the buildings where standard technologies are in use.\n\nIn experts' opinion, period of recoupment of using green and energy-saving technologies in Lakhta Center may be at about 20 years though Lakhta Center's Projection department's specialists think that this figure is a bit overestimated.\n\n===Transportation development===\nLakhta Center's construction raises a problem of transportation development because of the expected growth of the traffic flow in the region. Two traffic circles are to be built near Lakhta Center. These will become part of the \u041c32\u0410 highway in the future.<ref>[http://www.spbdnevnik.ru/news/2014-07-10/dva-razvorotnykh-koltsa-poyavyatsya-v-primorskom-rayone/]</ref>\nA light rail service from [[Finland Railway Station]] and a new tram line from Primorskaya underground station will be built to serve Lakhta Center. Plans are ongoing to build a new underground station with the working title of \"Lakhta\".<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/transport/ Transport Infrastructure Development]</ref> Bicycle lanes near Lakhta Center with 90 parking places for bicycles are also planned.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/07/15/138/ \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044b \u041c-32 \u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043a\u0443]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f |access-date=18 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413143303/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\nAs the [[Historic Centre of Saint Petersburg and Related Groups of Monuments|historical center of St. Petersburg]] has become a [[World Heritage Site]] since 1990; The [[World Heritage Committee]] opposed the construction of the 400-metre tower of [[Okhta Center]] as it would affect the cityscape of historic Saint Petersburg.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/612 UNESCO welcomes backing by President of Russian Federation for the preservation of St Petersburg]</ref> In December 2006 [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre Director Francesco Bandarin reminded Russia about its obligations to preserve it and expressed concern over the project.<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2006/12/05/117081 UNESCO is worried] by Elena Ragozina, [[Vedomosti]] #229 (1756), 5 December 2006 (in Russian).</ref> In 2007, the [[World Monuments Fund]] placed the historic skyline of St. Petersburg on its 2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites due to the potential construction of the building, and in 2009 reported that the tower \"would damage the image of Russia.\"<ref name=BBCUNESCO>{{Cite news |title=Russian tower plans cause alarm |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8272401.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}</ref> During the 36 session of the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO held in Saint Petersburg in 2012 it was stated that a large area of Saint-Petersburg falls within preservation and buffer zones provided for UNESCO World Heritage Sites. That is why it is good for the city that the Okhta Center, which had been planned by Gazprom in front of Smolny Cathedral was moved to Lakhta.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/sessions/36COM 36th session of the Committee of the World Heritage Committee]</ref> Eleonora Mitrofanova, Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to UNESCO noticed that the approved construction project for Lakhta Center is located far from the buffer zone and the historical center, so in theory Gazprom is not even obliged to ask UNESCO. However, the government authorities will definitely have consultations for the project with UNESCO. Now we are working to clarify the boundaries of the World Heritage zone and the boundaries of the buffer zone.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=326845&sec=1671 \u0412\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0420\u0424 \u0432 \u042e\u041d\u0415\u0421\u041a\u041e]</ref>\n\nThe project being moved to Lakhta didn't stop the discussions. On 11 April 2012, ex-governor of St. Petersburg and now Federation Council chairwoman Valentina Matvienko said to journalists that the \"Lakhta center could become a new symbol of the city and attract the businessmen from all over the world to St. Petersburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/sorokina/876139-echo/ |title=\"In the light circle\", the interview with Ms.Matvienko at \"Echo Moskvy\" |publisher=Echo.msk.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Russia in 2011 the Chairman of the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] Professor Sang-Dae Kim was treated to a presentation of a project of Lakhta Center. Professor Kim commented on the \"modern shape\" of the proposed Lakhta Center, which according to him had \"nothing in common with ordinary boxes\".<ref>[http://www.ctbuh.org/Events/ToursVisits/ProfKimVisitstoSEAsiaRussia/ProfKimvisitRussia/tabid/2778/language/en-US/Default.aspx CTBUH Meeting: Russia]</ref> He also stated that something new ought to be created, which can be shown to new generations in 200\u2013300 years as for them what is created nowadays will be the same history as the architecture of the 18-19th centuries for us today. Professor also noticed that the project reminds him of an oriental concept [[Yin Yang]]: on the one hand, the historic part of the city with horizontal buildings and water, and on the other hand, a vertical which will add additional charm to the city. Lakhta Center combines an interesting form and modern technologies, so up to Mr. Kim, with the lapse of time the Center can become a new symbol of Saint Petersburg.<ref>[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2011/09/07_a_3759709.shtml Without skyscrapers Russia is the Kremlin and the Red Army]</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2012, St. Petersburg governor Georgiy Poltavchenko emphasized in his annual report for House of Assembly the necessity of building a new \"city\" in St. Petersburg. According to Mr Poltavchenko, there are three appropriate districts for that: Lakhta center, Pulkovo and [[aggradation|aggradated]] territories near Waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/05/15/056/ |title=Poltavchenko: Petersburg needs a new business center and town-planning dictation |publisher=Fontanka.ru |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Construction gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Site's view prior to construction.jpg|Site's view prior to construction, July 2012.\nFile:Aerial view of the construction site of Lakhta Center in Saint Petersburg, November 2014.jpg|Panoramic view of the construction site, November 2014.\nFile:Piling process.jpg|Piling process\nFile:Construction of the foundation under the Tower.jpg|Construction of the foundation under the Tower\nFile:Foundations of the Tower and mixed-use building are ready.jpg|Foundations of the tower and mixed-use building are ready\nFile:Lakhta Center.jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2015\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Feb, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0438\u044e\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Jul, 2016\nFile:Lakhta_Center_Oktober_2016.jpg|The state of the construction as of October, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Skyscraper at the end of 2016. Height is 245 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c 2017).jpg|Skyscraper in April 2017. Height is 310 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u0439 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2017. Height is 323 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in September 2017. Height is 365 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440, \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.jpg|Lakhta Center in January 2018. Installation of the spire, height of about 450 meters\nFile:Lakhta Center orig.jpg|Skyscraper at the end of February 2018. Installation of the spire is complete, glazing of the tower and spire continues.\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u044f\u043a).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2018.\nFile:Das Lachta Zentr- \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 2H1A5980WI.jpg| June 2018\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2018).jpg|Lakhta Center in November 2018\nFile:2-\u044f \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044c \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Construction of the 2nd stage (November 2018)\nFile:Lakhta Center at night in april 2019.jpg|April 2019\nFile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Skyscraper lighting\nFile:Lakhta Center, spire.jpg|The spire of the skyscraper (General view).\nFile:\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445 \u0448\u043f\u0438\u043b\u044f \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|The top of the spire. Floodlight projectors are integrated in it\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Russia]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n* [[List of twisted buildings]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/ Official site of Lakhta Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070401024640/http://www.ohta-center.ru/ Official Site of the Okhta Center project]\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/future/view/ Visual Analysis projecting the appearance of the tower at the Lakhta site, from various points in St. Petersburg]\n* [https://ru-ru.facebook.com/lakhtacenter.ru/ Official social media page]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Russia]]\n[[Category:Gazprom]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Twisted buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Galebazz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Improved grammar, made text more logical", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakhta_Center"}
{"title_page": "Lake, Isle of Wight", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England\n|official_name=            Lake\n|civil_parish=             \n|coordinates = {{coord|50.649938|-1.167813|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n |area_total_sq_mi= 0.938\n |area_footnotes = <ref>[https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/construct/submit.asp?forward=yes&menuopt=201&subcomp= Office of National Statistics: QS102EW - Population density] retrieved 30 May 2017</ref>\n|population=               5,117\n|population_ref=           (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11125367&c=PO36+9EF&d=16&e=62&g=6402168&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=0&s=1445265492570&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n|unitary_england=       [[Isle of Wight]]\n|map_type =                Isle of Wight\n|lieutenancy_england=   [[Isle of Wight]]\n|region =                  South East England  \n|constituency_westminster=  [[Isle of Wight (UK Parliament constituency)|Isle of Wight]]\n|post_town=                SANDOWN\n|postcode_district=        PO36\n|postcode_area=            PO   \n|dial_code=      01983              \n|os_grid_reference= SZ586836\n|static_image_name=Lake High Street at dusk.JPG\n|static_image_caption=Lake High Street at dusk\n}}\n\n'''Lake''' is a large village and [[civil parish]] located on [[Sandown Bay]], on the [[Isle of Wight]], [[England]]. It is six miles south-east of [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] situated between [[Sandown]] and [[Shanklin]], and {{convert|1 + 1/2|miles}} to the east of the hamlet of [[Apse Heath]].<ref>{{Google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Lake,+Sandown/@50.6528615,-1.1896893,14z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x48748a392ad364a5:0x858286c5db1468b2!8m2!3d50.6501569!4d-1.1716901}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nLake is named after the Old English \"Lacu\"{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} referring to the creek that ran along, and has been artificially widened into what is now [[Scotchells Brook]], which is between the [[Isle of Wight Airport]], the Morrisons Superstore and the ''Spithead Industrial Park''.\n\n==History==\nThe high street that runs through Lake has not changed much since the early 20th century.<ref name=LPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakeparishcouncil.org.uk/local-information/local-history/|title=A General History of Lake|publisher=Lake Parish Council|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> However, the village war memorial, constructed in 1920,<ref name=LPC/> has been relocated behind the Fairway Bus Shelter due to having been run down twice by carelessly driven lorries. The thatched cottage at Merrie Gardens dates from the 17th century and is the oldest surviving building in Lake.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Beach at Lake, Isle of Wight, UK.jpg|thumb|left|The beach at Lake below the cliffs]]\nLake is a seaside village situated above the cliffs on [[Sandown bay]], it stands at an elevation of {{convert|63|ft}} above sea-level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://getoutside.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/local/lake-isle-of-wight|title=About Lake, Isle of Wight|publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]]}}</ref> Lake's beach or 'Welcome Beach' has golden sands and reached by a steep path down the [[sandstone]] cliffs to the Revetment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isleofwight.com/item/lake-isle-of-wight/|title=Lake, Isle of Wight|website=Isle of Wight dot com|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> It has two cafes (Hinks and Strollers), beach huts, a Sea Scout hut and inshore lifeboat.\n\nA large public park called '''Los Altos''' starts at the boundary between Lake and [[Sandown]]. Another large park called '''Lake Cliff Gardens''' borders the cliffs that back onto the beach and stretches between Lake and Shanklin.\n\nLocal wildlife includes [[Pipistrelle]] bats at Los Altos, kestrels along the Cliff Path and Common Toads which spawn in the disused reservoir behind the Mall. The [[wetlands]] of the [[Eastern Yar|River Yar]] are an [[SSSI]] supporting newts, voles and [[wildfowl]].\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Flickr - ronsaunders47 - ISLE OF WIGHT BEACH HUTS. 5.jpg|thumb|Beach huts at Lake]]\nThe village has the Broadlea primary school at Blackpan and The Bay School (Church of England primary and secondary) at the north end of the Fairway. There are several pubs including The Stag, plus The Porter Club (formerly Lake Working Men's Club) and a Townswomens' Guild.\n\nLocal businesses include Downer & White undertakers, Swinton Insurance, Allegri accountants, [[RSPCA]] charity shop and a veterinary practice. The village also features an Indian and Chinese Restaurant plus two Chinese takeaways, a kebab shop and Lake Fish Bar. There are a doctor's surgery and pharmacy. The disused medical clinic at the corner of Lake Hill and the Fairway is now a Co-Operative funeral parlour.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThere were recently two pubs in the village - The Stag and the Manor House. The Manor House was closed and has since reopened as a [[Tesco Metro]]. However, another pub, \"The Merrie Garden\" has recently opened near the Morrison's store. Alongside The Merrie Garden pub, a new [[Premier Inn]] has recently been built. It opened in late 2015.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} A branch of [[KFC]] opened in December 2018 nearby.<ref>{{cite web |title=Building of new KFC to begin In Lake next month |url=https://iwradio.co.uk/2018/07/25/building-of-new-kfc-to-begin-in-lake-next-month/ |website=[[Isle of Wight Radio]] Online}}</ref>\n\nSandown & Shanklin Golf Course is behind the Academy School and the Rugby Club in front.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Lake Methodist Church, Sandown Road, Lake, Isle of Wight (July 2016) (2).JPG|thumb|left|Lake Methodist Church]]\n[[File:Church of The Good Shepherd, Lake Road, Lake, Isle of Wight (July 2016) (5).JPG|thumb|The Church of The Good Shepherd]]\n\nThe village has a [[Methodist Church]] which was opened in 1956 and upgraded from 2009-11 with the addition of a church hall. The old church, built in 1877, complete with a hall and schoolroom (added in 1923) is now a multi-purpose building with both halls being converted into housing.<ref>[http://www.lakemethodist.org.uk/history/ Lake Methodist History] - Lake Methodist Church Website</ref>\n\nThe [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] [[Church of The Good Shepherd, Lake|Church of the Good Shepherd]], which was constructed designed in 1892, is also in the village.<ref>[https://www.portsmouth.anglican.org/acny/church/72/ The Good Shepherd] - Diocese of Portsmouth</ref> Construction finished in May 1894 and it replaced the  former ''Little Iron Church'' of 1876.<ref name=LPC/>\n\nThere also is a Kingdom Hall of [[Jehovah's Witnesses]].\n\n==Transportation==\nPublic transport is provided by [[Southern Vectis]] bus routes 2, 3 and 8 - which run between [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]], [[Ryde]], [[Sandown]], [[Shanklin]], [[Ventnor]] and [[Bembridge]]. Night buses operate on Friday and Saturday nights.<ref name=\"Southern Vectis bus routes\">{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.islandbuses.info/routelist.shtml |title=Southern Vectis - bus routes |publisher=www.islandbuses.info |accessdate=2008-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130004912/http://www.islandbuses.info/routelist.shtml |archivedate=2009-11-30 }}</ref>\n\nHaving opened in 1987, [[Lake railway station]] was the newest on the island until the construction of a station at [[Smallbrook Junction railway station|Smallbrook Junction]] in 1994. The station is placed in the heart of a quiet residential area close to Lake Cliff Gardens.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.wightonline.co.uk/gallery/lake/ Some current photographs]\n*[http://www.francisfrith.com/search/england/isle+of+wight/lake/lake.htm Historical photographs of Lake from the Francis Frith collection]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904215507/http://www.bags4vacs.co.uk/27101.html Hilton Price's Nostalgic Lake]\n{{Isle of Wight box}}\n{{Settlements on the Isle of Wight}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages on the Isle of Wight]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in the Isle of Wight]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England\n|official_name=            Lake\n|civil_parish=             \n|coordinates = {{coord|50.649938|-1.167813|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n |area_total_sq_mi= 0.938\n |area_footnotes = <ref>[https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/construct/submit.asp?forward=yes&menuopt=201&subcomp= Office of National Statistics: QS102EW - Population density] retrieved 30 May 2017</ref>\n|population=               5,117\n|population_ref=           (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11125367&c=PO36+9EF&d=16&e=62&g=6402168&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=0&s=1445265492570&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n|unitary_england=       [[Isle of Wight]]\n|map_type =                Isle of Wight\n|lieutenancy_england=   [[Isle of Wight]]\n|region =                  South East England  \n|constituency_westminster=  [[Isle of Wight (UK Parliament constituency)|Isle of Wight]]\n|post_town=                SANDOWN\n|postcode_district=        PO36\n|postcode_area=            PO   \n|dial_code=      01983              \n|os_grid_reference= SZ586836\n|static_image_name=Lake High Street at dusk.JPG\n|static_image_caption=Lake High Street at dusk\n}}\n\n'''Lake''' is a large village and [[civil parish]] located on [[Sandown Bay]], on the [[Isle of Wight]], [[England]]. It is six miles south-east of [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]] situated between [[Sandown]] and [[Shanklin]], and {{convert|1 + 1/2|miles}} to the east of the hamlet of [[Apse Heath]].<ref>{{Google maps|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Lake,+Sandown/@50.6528615,-1.1896893,14z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x48748a392ad364a5:0x858286c5db1468b2!8m2!3d50.6501569!4d-1.1716901}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nLake is named after the Old English \"Lacu\"{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} referring to the creek that ran along, and has been artificially widened into what is now [[Scotchells Brook]], which is between the [[Isle of Wight Airport]], the Morrisons Superstore and the ''Spithead Industrial Park''.\n\n==History==\nThe high street that runs through Lake has not changed much since the early 20th century.<ref name=LPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.lakeparishcouncil.org.uk/local-information/local-history/|title=A General History of Lake|publisher=Lake Parish Council|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> However, the village war memorial, constructed in 1920,<ref name=LPC/> has been relocated behind the Fairway Bus Shelter due to having been run down twice by carelessly driven lorries. The thatched cottage at Merrie Gardens dates from the 17th century and is the oldest surviving building in Lake.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Beach at Lake, Isle of Wight, UK.jpg|thumb|left|The beach at Lake below the cliffs]]\nLake is a seaside village situated above the cliffs on [[Sandown bay]], it stands at an elevation of {{convert|63|ft}} above sea-level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://getoutside.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/local/lake-isle-of-wight|title=About Lake, Isle of Wight|publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]]}}</ref> Lake's beach or 'Welcome Beach' has golden sands and reached by a steep path down the [[sandstone]] cliffs to the Revetment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isleofwight.com/item/lake-isle-of-wight/|title=Lake, Isle of Wight|website=Isle of Wight dot com|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> It has two cafes (Hinks and Strollers), beach huts, a Sea Scout hut and inshore lifeboat.\n\nA large public park called '''Los Altos''' starts at the boundary between Lake and [[Sandown]]. Another large park called '''Lake Cliff Gardens''' borders the cliffs that back onto the beach and stretches between Lake and Shanklin.\n\nLocal wildlife includes [[Pipistrelle]] bats at Los Altos, kestrels along the Cliff Path and Common Toads which spawn in the disused reservoir behind the Mall. The [[wetlands]] of the [[Eastern Yar|River Yar]] are an [[SSSI]] supporting newts, voles and [[wildfowl]].\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Flickr - ronsaunders47 - ISLE OF WIGHT BEACH HUTS. 5.jpg|thumb|Beach huts at Lake]]\nThe village has the Broadlea primary school at Blackpan and The Bay School (Church of England primary and secondary) at the north end of the Fairway. There are several pubs including The Stag, plus The Porter Club (formerly Lake Working Men's Club) and a Townswomens' Guild.\n\nLocal businesses include Downer & White undertakers, Swinton Insurance, Allegri accountants, [[RSPCA]] charity shop and a veterinary practice. The village also features an Indian and Chinese Restaurant plus two Chinese takeaways, a kebab shop and Lake Fish Bar. There are a doctor's surgery and pharmacy. The disused medical clinic at the corner of Lake Hill and the Fairway is now a Co-Operative funeral parlour.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThere were recently two pubs in the village - The Stag and the Manor House. The Manor House was closed and has since reopened as a [[Tesco Metro]]. However, another pub, \"The Merrie Garden\" has recently opened near the Morrison's store. Alongside The Merrie Garden pub, a new [[Premier Inn]] has recently been built. It opened in late 2015.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} A branch of [[KFC]] opened in December 2018 nearby.<ref>{{cite web |title=Building of new KFC to begin In Lake next month |url=https://iwradio.co.uk/2018/07/25/building-of-new-kfc-to-begin-in-lake-next-month/ |website=[[Isle of Wight Radio]] Online}}</ref>\n\nSandown & Shanklin Golf Course is behind the Academy School and the Rugby Club in front.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Lake Methodist Church, Sandown Road, Lake, Isle of Wight (July 2016) (2).JPG|thumb|left|Lake Methodist Church]]\n[[File:Church of The Good Shepherd, Lake Road, Lake, Isle of Wight (July 2016) (5).JPG|thumb|The Church of The Good Shepherd]]\n\nThe village has a [[Methodist Church]] which was opened in 1956 and upgraded from 2009-11 with the addition of a church hall. The old church, built in 1877, compleat with a hall and schoolroom (added in 1923) is now a multi-purpose building with both halls being converted into housing.<ref>[http://www.lakemethodist.org.uk/history/ Lake Methodist History] - Lake Methodist Church Website</ref>\n\nThe [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] [[Church of The Good Shepherd, Lake|Church of the Good Shepherd]], which was constructed designed in 1892, is also in the village.<ref>[https://www.portsmouth.anglican.org/acny/church/72/ The Good Shepherd] - Diocese of Portsmouth</ref> Construction finished in May 1894 and it replaced the  former ''Little Iron Church'' of 1876.<ref name=LPC/>\n\nThere also is a Kingdom Hall of [[Jehovah's Witnesses]].\n\n==Transportation==\nPublic transport is provided by [[Southern Vectis]] bus routes 2, 3 and 8 - which run between [[Newport, Isle of Wight|Newport]], [[Ryde]], [[Sandown]], [[Shanklin]], [[Ventnor]] and [[Bembridge]]. Night buses operate on Friday and Saturday nights.<ref name=\"Southern Vectis bus routes\">{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.islandbuses.info/routelist.shtml |title=Southern Vectis - bus routes |publisher=www.islandbuses.info |accessdate=2008-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130004912/http://www.islandbuses.info/routelist.shtml |archivedate=2009-11-30 }}</ref>\n\nHaving opened in 1987, [[Lake railway station]] was the newest on the island until the construction of a station at [[Smallbrook Junction railway station|Smallbrook Junction]] in 1994. The station is placed in the heart of a quiet residential area close to Lake Cliff Gardens.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.wightonline.co.uk/gallery/lake/ Some current photographs]\n*[http://www.francisfrith.com/search/england/isle+of+wight/lake/lake.htm Historical photographs of Lake from the Francis Frith collection]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904215507/http://www.bags4vacs.co.uk/27101.html Hilton Price's Nostalgic Lake]\n{{Isle of Wight box}}\n{{Settlements on the Isle of Wight}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages on the Isle of Wight]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in the Isle of Wight]]\n", "name_user": "Rpllpr", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReligion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake,_Isle_of_Wight"}
{"title_page": "Limmud", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Limmud\n| logo   = Limmud_logo.png\n| type   = Jewish educational [[Charitable organization|charity]]<ref name=\"Charity\">Limmud is registered with the [[Charity Commission]] as charity no. 1083414. According to the Charity Commission, Limmud operates throughout England and Wales and also in Argentina, Australia, Austria, Belarus, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Brazil, Bulgaria, Canada, China, Croatia, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Hungary, India, Israel, Italy, Lithuania, Macedonia, Netherlands, New Zealand, Peru, Poland, Romania, Russia, Scotland, Serbia, South Africa, Sweden, Turkey, Ukraine and the United States of America.  {{cite web | url=http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/find-charities/ | title=Limmud | publisher=[[Charity Commission]] | work=Find charities |date= 2 January 2014 |accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref>\n| founded_date      = 1980\n| founders           = [[Clive Lawton]], [[Alastair Falk]], Michael May, Jonathan Benjamin\n| location          = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| origins           = \n| key_people        = {{unbulleted list|Shoshana Bloom (Chair)<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/how-limmud-head-is-planning-for-the-future-as-the-festival-reaches-40-1.489711 | title=How Limmud head is planning for the future as the festival reaches 40 | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=4 October 2019  | accessdate=5 October 2019 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref>| Eli Ovits (Chief Executive)}}\n| area_served       = Worldwide\n| product           =\n| focus             = \n| method            = \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = \n| subsid            = \n| owner             = \n| Non-profit_slogan = Wherever you find yourself, Limmud will take you one step further on your Jewish journey\n| homepage          = {{url|https://www.limmud.org}}\n| dissolved         = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Limmud''' is a [[British Jews|British-Jewish]] educational charity<ref name=\"Charity\"/> which, in the UK, produces a large annual winter festival and several other regional events throughout the year on the theme of Jewish learning. Limmud is not affiliated to any strand of Judaism, stating \"We have no part to play in the debates between/across denominations\" in its mission statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://limmud.org/inside-limmud/about-limmud/mission-values/|title=Mission & Values|website=Limmud|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> Limmud markets itself as open to \"anyone interested in Jewish learning\".\n\nLimmud (from the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] word meaning \"to learn\")<ref name=\"Jeffay\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/dec/16/limmud | title='It's more academic than academia' | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=16 December 2008 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Jeffay, Nathan}}</ref> was originally a conference for \"educators\",<ref name=\"Jeffay\"/> basing itself on [[CAJE]], the Conference on Alternatives in Jewish Education of North America.<ref name=\"Falk interview\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/122247/the-man-leading-front-class | title=The man leading from the front of the class  | work=Interview with Alastair Falk in [[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=5 September 2014 | accessdate=5 September 2014 | author=Oliver, Charlotte}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  Taking CAJE's volunteer ethos, not paying presenters and not using people's titles, Limmud has grown to be a large international organisation. During the 1990s there was the significant change as Limmud reinvented itself as a community gathering, giving rise to a significant increase in the number of attendees and leading it to be described as \"British Jewry's greatest export\".<ref name=\"Export\">{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/week-s-end/all-jewish-all-the-time-1.335748 | title=All Jewish, all the time | work=[[Haaretz]] | date=7 January 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Harman, Danna}}</ref>  The Limmud model has now spread to many other countries.<ref name=\"Charity\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA distinctive feature of Limmud is that the events are organised by volunteers,<ref name=\" Kustanowitz \">{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/misc/iphone-article/.premium-1.557408 | title=Seven ways to disrupt a Jewish conference | work=[[Haaretz]] | date=11 November 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Kustanowitz, Esther D}}</ref><ref name=\"Tulane\">{{cite web|url=https://tulane.edu/news/newwave/030810_limmud_fest.cfm |title=\u2018Volunticipants\u2019 Needed for Jewish Fest |publisher=[[Tulane University]] |work=New Wave |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116085307/https://tulane.edu/news/newwave/030810_limmud_fest.cfm |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> who also take part as equals in what is now called the Limmud Festival.<ref name=\"Export\"/><ref name=\"Eisner\"/>  Limmud's largest group of volunteers are in their 20s and 30s.<ref name=\"Eisner\">{{cite news | url=http://forward.com/articles/190369/what-limmud-can-teach-us/ | title=What Limmud Can Teach Us | work=[[The Forward]] | date=7 January 2014 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Eisner, Jane | location=[[New York City|New York]]}}</ref> Around half of the UK \"Forty under 40\" (a community-wide initiative to identify the future leaders of British Jewry, published by ''[[Jewish News]]'') have volunteered for Limmud and a former Chair of Limmud, Elliott Goldstein, topped the list.<ref name=\"Elliott\">{{cite news | url=http://archive.totallyjewish.com/news/elliott-is-number-one/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826120511/http://archive.totallyjewish.com/news/elliott-is-number-one/ | title=Elliott is number one | url-status=dead | work=[[Jewish News]] | date=17 June 2010 | accessdate=1 January 2020 |archive-date=26 August 2016 | author=Marin, James | location=London}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nLimmud held its first conference in 1980 for 80 people organised by [[Alastair Falk]], Michael May, Jonathan Benjamin and [[Clive Lawton]], inspired by a visit to the Coalition for the Advancement of Jewish Education (CAJE) in North America. Its aim was to build bridges between professional and nonprofessional educators and between those of differing religious commitments. The next year participation had doubled and all aspects of Jewish learning were covered.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://limmud.org/inside-limmud/about-limmud/history/|title=History|website=Limmud|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nBy 1996 the main Limmud conference had expanded and moved to Oxford with attendance of over 1,000, 250 sessions and 140 speakers, becoming the largest Jewish conference in Europle. During this period the organisation also held smaller one day events in Glasgow and Leeds.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1999 the first non-UK Limmud was held in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n2006 saw Limmud appoint its first full-time Executive Director, [[Raymond Simonson]]. Prior to this Limmud had been run by part-time directors.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe late 2000s saw Limmud participation in the UK grow dramatically. In 2007 Limmud held their conference at Warwick University, with 2,000 participants and 600 at Limmud Fest, a smaller summer festival. With numbers more than doubling in 2008 to 7,000 for their UK events. International conferences were now held in [[Cape Town]], [[Johannesburg]], [[Hungary]], [[Atlanta]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Poland]], [[Stockholm]], [[Ukraine]], [[Germany]], [[Turkey]], [[Toronto]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[France]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLimmud Conference moved to [[Birmingham]] for Conference 2015, with a record 2,800 participants. New Limmud groups include [[Arizona]], [[Mar del Plata]], [[Australia]], [[Tel Aviv]], [[Chile]] and [[Essen]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018 Limmud Conference became Limmud Festival. Limmud set up affiliates in [[North America]] and [[Israel]]. Limmud estimates there are 40,000 participants annually in a Limmud worldwide, run by 4,000 volunteers. In 2017 Limmud was also awarded the [[Jerusalem Unity Prize]] for contribution to Jewish life, presented by Israeli President Rivlin.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Organisation==\nLimmud is a company and a charity. It is run by a board of directors and trustees, all of whom are volunteers. Initially, there was no difference between Limmud the organisation and Limmud Conference, the annual event, so the chairs of the Conference/Festival team were the chairs of the organisation. In 1990, a chair for the organisation who was separate from the Conference chairs was appointed for the first time. In 2006, [[Limmud International]] was created, as a separate unit within Limmud to manage relationships with other Limmud groups around the world. Limmud International was absorbed back into Limmud at the end of 2016.\n\n'''Chairs of Limmud Conference/Festival'''\n\n1980\u20131981 Alistair Falk, Michael May, Jonathan Benjamin, Clive Lawton\n\n1982\u20131984 Steve Miller\n\n1985 Tina Elliott\n\n1986 Jonathan Benjamin\n\n1987 Alan Wilkinson\n\n1988 Madeline Ismach\n\n1989 Alistair Falk\n\n1990\u20131994 Andrew Gilbert\n\n1995 Natan Tiefenbrun\n\n1996 Yvonne Krasner, Marc Soloway, Judy Trotter\n\n1997 Micah Gold, Jonny Persey, Marc Soloway\n\n1998 Micah Gold\n\n1999 Jacqueline Nicholls, Claire Straus\n\n2000 Andrew Levy, Abe Sterne\n\n2001 Claire Mandel, Carolyn Bogush\n\n2002 Juliet Simmons\n\n2003 Fleurise Luder, Eliot Kaye\n\n2004 Batya Elliott, Paul Turner\n\n2005 David Century, Shoshana Bloom\n\n2006 Jason Caplin, Natalie Grazin\n\n2007 Kevin Sefton\n\n2008 Libby Burkeman and Charles Darwish\n\n2009 Rebecca Lester and David Israel\n\n2010 Danielle Nagler and Steven Fisher\n\n2011 Shoshana Bloom and Jonathan Walters\n\n2012 David Renton\n\n2013 Oliver Marcus and Richard Verber\n\n2014 Shana Boltin and Jonathan Robinson\n\n2015 Joanna Ish-Horowicz, Michael Gladstone and Claire Samuel\n\n2016 Benjamin Crowne and Steven Weller\n\n2017 Abigail Jacobi and Anna Lawton\n\n2018 Jonathan Robinson\n\n2019 Ben Lewis, Hannah Brady and Dan Heller\n\n2020 Elliot Jebreel and Robert Simmons\n\n'''Chairs of Limmud'''\n\n1990\u20131997 Andrew Gilbert\n\n1998\u20132001 Judy Trotter\n\n1998\u20132000 Natan Tiefenbrun\n\n2001\u20132003 Claire Straus\n\n2003\u20132005 Claire Mandel\n\n2006\u20132009 Elliott Goldstein\n\n2010\u20132012 Carolyn Bogush\n\n2013\u20132015 Kevin Sefton\n\n2016\u20132019 David Hoffman\n\n2019\u2013  Shoshana Bloom\n\n'''Chairs of Limmud International'''\n\n2006\u20132009 Andrew Gilbert\n\n2010\u20132012 Uri Berkowitz, Helena Miller\n\n2013\u20132014 David Hoffman\n\n2015\u20132016 David Bilchitz<ref>{{Cite book|title=Limmud Conference / Festival handbooks|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2002\u20132017|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n'''Chair of Limmud North America'''\n\n2017\u20132019 Shep Rosenman<ref>{{Cite book|title=Limmud Conference / Festival handbooks|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2002\u20132018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n2019\u2013 Faye Rosenberg-Cohen, Sivie Twersky\n\n'''Chair of Limmud Israel'''\n\n2018\u2013 Danielle Nagler<ref name=\"Nagler\">{{cite news | url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/spotlight/times-of-israel-presents-limmud-israel-tel-aviv-after-dark-on-oct-22/ | title=Times of Israel Presents: Limmud Israel \u2014 Tel Aviv After Dark, on Oct. 22 | work=[[The Times of Israel]] | date=15 October 2018 | accessdate=30 November 2018 | author=TOI Staff}}</ref>\n\nLimmud's first professional appointment in 1998 was of [[Clive Lawton]] as part-time Executive Director; he gradually became backed by a full-time administrator. In 2006 Limmud recruited its first full-time Executive Director, [[Raymond Simonson]], former Director of UJIA Makor: The Centre for Informal Jewish Education.<ref name=\"Simonson\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/70784/limmud-leader-simonson-heads-jcc | title=Limmud leader Simonson heads for the JCC | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=2 August 2012 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Lipman, Jennifer}}</ref> When Simonson became Chief Executive of London's Jewish Community Centre,<ref name=\"Simonson\" /> now [[JW3]], in 2012, he was succeeded by Shelley Marsh.<ref name=\"Marsh\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/limmud-picks-shelley-marsh-for-top-job-1.36808 | title=Limmud picks Shelley Marsh for top job | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=4 October 2012 | accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> She stepped down from the role in 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/132571/limmud-director-steps-down | title=Limmud director steps down | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=25 March 2015 | accessdate=27 March 2015 | author=Doherty, Rosa}}</ref> Mike Schindler was the Limmud Director of Operations and the senior professional in the organisation between March and August 2015,<ref name=\"Structure\">{{cite web|url=https://limmud.org/volunteers/structure/ |title=Limmud the organisation&nbsp;\u2013 who's who |publisher=Limmud |accessdate=2 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203174601/http://limmud.org/volunteers/structure/ |archivedate= 3 February 2016 }}</ref> and then Dani Serlin was Acting Executive Director until February 2016. In February 2016, Limmud appointed the current Chief Executive, Eli Ovits, as senior professional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/2016/02/01/global/global-limmud-names-jerusalem-us-eli-ovits-as-executive-director|title=Global Limmud names Jerusalem U's Eli Ovits as executive director|date=2016-02-01|website=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Limmud events in the UK==\n===Limmud Festival===\n'''Limmud Festival''' (until 2017 known as '''Limmud Conference'''),  takes place every year in the last week of December<ref name=\" Kahn-Harris\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2010/dec/29/limmud-conference-jewish | title=Limmud: a great Jewish alternative to Christmas | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=29 December 2010 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=[[Keith Kahn-Harris|Kahn-Harris, Keith]]}}</ref> and is the organisation's [[flagship]] event.  It was inspired by the [[CAJE]] conference in the United States [http://www.caje.org/] and now attracts more than 2,000 participants annually;<ref name=\"Jeffay\"/><ref name=\" Kahn-Harris\"/> in 2015 the numbers rose to 2,750.<ref name=\"2015 pictures\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/galleries/news-galleries/limmud-2015-pictures | title=Limmud 2015 in pictures | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=31 December 2015 | accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> A typical day at Limmud Festival includes around 200 sessions spanning religious, cultural and political aspects of Jewish life.  After the first conferences at [[Carmel College (Oxfordshire)]],<ref name=\"Growth\"/> Limmud Conference has been held at [[University of Portsmouth|Portsmouth Polytechnic]] (1984),<ref name=\"Growth\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/114276/how-limmud-has-grown | title=How Limmud has grown | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=23 December 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Easterman, Daniel}}</ref> [[Oxford Brookes University]] (1986\u20131994),<ref name=\"Growth\"/> Worcester (1995\u201396), Manchester (1997), the [[University of Nottingham]] (1998\u20132006) and [[Warwick University]] (2007\u201314).<ref name=\"Growth\"/> Since 2015 this annual event has been held at the hotels surrounding Pendigo Lake, near [[Birmingham]].<ref name=\"Conference 2015\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/151538/limmuds-new-venue-should-make-year-best-conference-yet-say-organisers | title=Limmud's new venue should make this year the best conference yet, say organisers | work=[[the Jewish Chronicle]]| author=Rocker, Simon | date= 21 December 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackman \">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/127523/limmud-2014-organisers-promise-bigger-event-next-year | title=Limmud 2014: Organisers promise bigger event next year | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=31 December 2014 | accessdate=31 December 2014 |author1=Dysch, Marcus |author2=Firsht, Naomi |author3=Jackman, Josh }}</ref>\n\n===Limmud summer events===\nLimmud held a summer event in the last week of August which was called Limmud Fest from 2004 to 2012 and Limmud in the Woods from 2013 to 2016.<ref name=\"Sheinman\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/110132/limmud-goes-camping-woods | title=Limmud goes camping in the Woods | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 August 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Sheinman, Anna}}</ref> It involved camping as well as staying indoors,<ref name=\"Sheinman\"/> had a less intense programme centred on [[Shabbat]] and is more cultural and outdoors-focused than its winter sibling. Limmud Fest had a peak attendance of 650 people; Limmud in the Woods was attended by around 200\u2013250 young adults and young families.<ref name=\"Sheinman\"/>\n\n===Day and weekend Limmud events===\nThe first Day Limmud was in Sheffield in the early 1980s, followed by Leeds in the mid-1990s. Day and weekend Limmuds are now held at a number of venues in the UK, including Birmingham,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://limmud.org/day/birmingham-wm/ |title=Limmud Birmingham WM 2016 |publisher=Limmud |publication-date=2016| accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> Cambridge,<ref name=\"Cambridge 2013\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/112992/cambridge-the-rolls-royce-day-limmuds | title=Cambridge: 'The Rolls-Royce of day Limmuds' | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 November 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref><ref name=\"Cambridge 2011\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/58071/limmuds-cambridge-education-finds-a-highly-receptive-audience | title=Limmud's Cambridge education finds a highly receptive audience | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=10 November 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Josephs, Bernard}}</ref> Harrow,<ref name=\"Harrow\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/103136/hundreds-flock-harrow-limmud | title=Hundreds flock to Harrow Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 March 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Hull,<ref name=\"Hull\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.leedsjewishcommunity.com/join-in/2017/03/01/limmud-in-hull/ |title=Book your place at a unique 'pop up' day Limmud in Hull \u2013 the UK city of culture \u2013 7th May 2017 |date=1 March 2017 |publisher=Leeds Jewish Community |access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref> Leeds,<ref name=\"Leeds 2011\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/46452/leeds-loves-limmud-experience | title=Leeds loves Limmud experience | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 March 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Kalmus, Jonathan}}</ref><ref name=\"Leeds 2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/89997/leeds-ignites-limmud-fireworks | title=Leeds ignites Limmud fireworks | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=8 November 2012 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Fisher, John}}</ref> Liverpool,<ref name=\"Liverpool 2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/local-news/65581/limmud-shows-its-political-influences | title=Limmud shows its political influences | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=22 March 2012 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Greenberg, Sue}}</ref><ref name=\"Liverpool 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/31443/liverpool-loves-limmud | title=Liverpool loves Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=6 May 2010 | accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Manchester,<ref name=\"Manchester\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/114566/manchester-gears-its-own-limmud | title=Manchester gears up for its own Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=10 January 2014 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Kalmus, Jonathan}}</ref> and the Thames Valley.<ref name=\"Thames\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/thames-class-act-at-limmud-1.18820| title=Thames' class act at Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=14 October 2010 | accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, Limmud events have also been held in Bournemouth,<ref name=\"Bournemouth 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/32169/limmud-sunny-bournemouth | title=Limmud in Sunny Bournemouth | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=27 May 2010 | accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> Brighton,<ref name=\"Brighton 2011\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/brighton-rocks-to-the-beat-of-limmud-1.23391| title=Brighton rocks to the beat of Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=26 May 2011 | accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Glasgow,<ref name=\"Glasgow 2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/92788/scots-love-their-limmud | title=Scots love their Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=29 November 2012 | accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Glasgow 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/28323/scotlands-limmud-weekend | title=Scotland's Limmud weekend | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=18 February 2010 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Brickman,  Stephanie}}</ref> Hackney,<ref name=\"Hackney 2008\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/galleries/the-guest-list/a-big-crowd-flocks-hackney%E2%80%99s-first-limmud | title=A big crowd flocks to Hackney's first Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=3 October 2008 | accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> Newcastle, South London<ref name=\"South London\">{{Cite web |url=http://limmud.org/day/south-london/ |title=South London Day Limmud \u2013 1 July 2012 |website=Limmud |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> and South East London.\n\n===Other Limmud events in UK===\nOther events run by Limmud in the UK. either on their own or in partnership with others. have included music events and the [[Florence Melton]] Adult Mini-School, organised in partnership with the [[London Jewish Cultural Centre]].\n\n==Limmuds around the world==\n{{main|Limmud International}}\nThe Limmud model has now spread to many other countries.<ref name=\"Charity\"/>  More than ninety communities in 42 countries on six continents have hosted Limmud events including, in 2013 for the first time, Hong Kong,<ref name=\"HK\">{{cite web | url=http://ejewishphilanthropy.com/hong-kong-is-finally-limmud-trending/ | title=Hong Kong is Finally Limmud Trending | publisher=eJewish Philanthropy | date=13 March 2013 | accessdate=17 February 2014 | author=Lyons, Erica}}</ref> Peru,<ref name=\"Peru\">{{cite news | url= http://www.jta.org/2013/10/15/news-opinion/world/limmud-debut-in-peru-draws-600#ixzz3FY3MkWiq | title=Limmud debut in Peru draws more than 600 | work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency | date=15 October 2013 | accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> India<ref name=\"Mumbai\">{{cite news | url=http://ejewishphilanthropy.com/first-limmud-mumbai-event-draws-jews-from-across-the-subcontinent/ | title= First Limmud Mumbai Event Draws Jews from Across the Subcontinent | work= Jewish Philanthropy | date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=8 October 2014 | author=EJP}}</ref> and Montenegro.\n\n'''UK\n'''\n[http://www.limmudbristolsw.co.uk/ Limmud Bristol SW], [http://limmud.org/day/cambridge/ Limmud Cambridge], [http://limmud.org/festival/ Limmud Festival], Limmud Harrow, [http://limmud.org/day/hull/hull/ Limmud Hull], [http://limmud.org/day/leeds/Leeds/ Limmud Leeds], [http://limmud.org/day/liverpool/ Limmud Liverpool], [http://limmud.org/day/manchester/ Limmud Manchester], [http://limmud.org/day/midlands Limmud Midlands], Limmud Scotland, Limmud Thames Valley\n\n'''Africa, Asia and Australasia'''\n\nAustralia- [http://limmudshavuot.weebly.com/ Limmud Canberra], [http://www.limmudoz.com.au/ Limmud Oz Melbourne], [http://www.facebook.com/lemidabekehila/ Limmud Oz Perth], [http://www.shalom.edu.au/shalom-programs/limmud/ Limmud Oz Sydney]<br />\n[http://limmud.org.nz/ Limmud New Zealand] <br />\n[http://www.limmudchina.org/ Limmud China]- Limmud Beijing, Limmud Shanghai <br />\n[https://www.facebook.com/groups/601703429881645/ Limmud India] <br />\n[http://www.limoud.re Limmud R\u00e9union] <br />\n[[Limmud South Africa|Limmud SA]]- Limmud Cape Cape Town, Limmud Durban, Limmud Johannesburg\n\n'''North America'''\n\nUSA- [http://limmudaz.org/ Limmud AZ], [http://www.limmudbayarea.org/ Limmud Bay Area], [http://www.limmudboca.org Limmud Boca], [https://limmudboston.org/ Limmud Boston], [http://www.limmudchi.org/ Limmud Chicago + MW], [http://www.limmudla.org/ Limmud LA], [http://www.limmudmiami.org/ Limmud Miami], [http://www.limmudmichigan.org/ Limmud Michigan], [http://www.limmudnola.org/ Limmud NOLA], [http://limmudny.org/ Limmud NY], [http://centercityjews.org/limmudphilly/ Limmud Philly], [http://www.limmudseattle.org/ Limmud Seattle], \nCanada- Limmud Kingston, [http://limmudottawa.ca Limmud Ottawa], [http://limmud.ca/ Limmud Toronto], [http://www.limmudvancouver.ca/ Limmud Vancouver], [http://www.limmudwinnipeg.org/ Limmud Winnipeg]\n\n'''Latin America'''\n\nArgentina- [http://www.limudba.org/ Limmud Buenos Aires], [http://www.limudmdq.org Limmud Mar Del Plata]\n[http://www.limmudbogota.org/ Limmud Bogota]\n[http://www.limudcaracas.com/ Limmud Caracas]\n[http://www.limud.cl/ Limmud Chile]\nLimmud Costa Rica\n[http://limudmexico.org/ Limmud Mexico]\n\n'''Europe'''\n\n[http://limmudbaltics.eu/ Limmud Baltics] (covers Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania)\n[https://www.limmud.cz/ Limmud Czech Republic- Slovak Republic]\n[https://www.facebook.com/limmudexyu/ Limmud ExYu] (covers Macedonia, Montenegro and Serbia)\n[http://www.limoud.org/ Limmud France]- Limmud Paris, Limmud Marseille\n[http://limmud.de Limmud Germany]- Limmud Berlin, Limmud Cologne, Limmud Essen, Limmud Frankfurt A.M, Limmud Freiburg, Limmud Hamburg, Limmud Munich\n[http://www.limud.fi/ Limmud Helsinki]\n[http://limmud.hu/ Limmud Hungary]\n[http://www.limmud-italia.it/ Limmud Italia] -Limmud Italia in Jerusalem\n[http://www.limmud.eu/ Limmud Keshet Bulgaria]\n[https://www.lzb.lt/limmud-lietuva-2018/ Limmud Latvia]\n[https://www.lzb.lt/limmud-lietuva-2018/ Limmud Lithuania]\n[http://www.limmoed.nl/ Limmud Netherlands]\n[http://www.oresundslimmud.org/%20http://www.oresundslimmud.se/%20http://www.oresundslimmud.dk/ Limmud Oresund] (covers Copenhagen, Lund and Malmo)\n[http://limmudpoland.org/en/ Limmud Poland]- [https://www.facebook.com/limmudwroclaw/ Limmud Wroc\u0142aw]\nSpain- [http://www.limudbarcelona.org/ Limmud Barcelona], [https://sites.google.com/view/limmud-madrid Limmud Madrid], [https://www.limudmallorca.com/ Limmud Mallorca]\n[http://limmud.se/ Limmud Stockholm]\n[http://www.limmudtr.org/ Limmud Turkey]\n[http://www.limmudwien.org/ Limmud Vienna]\n\n'''Israel'''\n\n[http://www.jewishagency.org/he/limmud-arava/content/31351 Limmud Arava]\n[http://www.limmudgalil.com/ Limmud Galil]\n[http://golan.org.il/limud/ Limmud Golan]\n[http://limmudhaifa.wixsite.com/kenes/lectures Limmud Haifa]\n[http://www.limmudjerusalem.org.il/hhome.php Limmud Jerusalem]\n[https://www.facebook.com/limmud.modiin/ Limmud Modi'in]\n[https://www.limmudtlv.org/ Limmud Tel Aviv]\n[http://www.bamidbar.org/ Limmud Yeroham]\n\n'''[[Limmud FSU]]'''\n\n[http://www.limmudfsu.by/en Limmud FSU Belarus]\n[http://www.limmudfsucanada.org/ Limmud FSU Canada]\n[http://www.limmudfsu.eu/ Limmud FSU Europe]\n[http://www.limmudfsu.org.il Limmud FSU Israel]\n[https://www.jcm.md/ru/ Limmud FSU Moldova]\n[http://www.limmud.ru/ Limmud FSU Moscow]\n[http://www.limmudfsuus.org/ Limmud FSU NY]\n[http://limmud.spb.ru/ Limmud FSU St Petersburg]\n[http://www.limmud.org.ua/ Limmud FSU Ukraine]\n[http://2015.limmudvu.ru/ Limmud FSU Volga-Urals]\n[http://westcoast.limmudfsuus.org/ Limmud FSU West Coast]\n\n'''Events based upon the Limmud concept'''\n\nSwitzerland- [http://jomijun.ch/ Jom Ijun]<br />\nRussia- [http://lsaran.org/ Lsaran]<br />\nUnited Kingdom- [http://www.nhorizons.org/events/item/british-islam-conference-18 British Islam Conference]<br />\nUnited States- [http://www.simonfamilyjcc.org/yom-limmud-mobile/ Tidewater Yom Limmud], [https://jewishnaples.org/jcdl Jewish Community Day of Learning Naples]\n\n==Relationships with Orthodoxy in Britain==\nThe former London [[United Synagogue]] [[Beth Din]]'s Head [[Dayan (rabbinic judge)]], [[Chanoch Ehrentreu]], advised Orthodox rabbis not to attend Limmud Conference.<ref name=\"Lebens\">{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/the-jewish-thinker/.premium-1.553846 | title=Why Orthodox rabbis shouldn\u2019t boycott Limmud | work=[[Haaretz]] | date=22 October 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Lebens, Samuel}}</ref> However, in the UK many United Synagogue pulpit rabbis have attended Limmud. In December 2010 Rabbi [[Yitzchak Schochet]] of Mill Hill United Synagogue, who had been seen as a notable absentee and critic of Limmud, attended, took part in and taught at Limmud's 30th annual Conference. Following this he wrote on the synagogue's website: \"upon return all I could ask myself was, 'where was I until now?\"<ref name=\"Schochet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.shul.co.uk/readArticle.php?article=301 | title=When Lightning Didn\u2019t Strike | publisher=Mill Hill, United Synagogue | work=Rabbi's Blog | date=3 January 2011 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=[[Yitzchak Schochet|Schochet, Yitzchak]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Jonathan Sacks]] did not attend Limmud whilst being Chief Rabbi but attended when he was the head of [[Jews College]]. Sacks, when looking back on his rabbinate, considers Limmud to be one of the great successes of his time.<ref name=\"Big Think\">{{cite web | url=http://bigthink.com/videos/big-think-interview-with-lord-rabbi-jonathan-sacks | title=Big Think Interview With Lord Rabbi Jonathan Sacks | publisher=Big Think | date=12 July 2010 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Liebman, Jessica}}</ref>\n\nControversy erupted again in 2013 when newly elected Chief Rabbi [[Ephraim Mirvis]] announced his decision to attend.<ref name=\"Lebens\"/> Subsequently, a public notice signed by seven leading Orthodox rabbis including Dayan [[Chanoch Ehrentreu]] and Rabbi [[Avrohom Gurwicz]] was published in the ''[[Jewish Tribune (UK)|Jewish Tribune]]'', highly critical of pluralism and urged \"God-fearing Jews\" not to participate in Limmud.<ref name=\"Lebens\"/> This sparked condemnation by non-[[Charedi]] communal leaders, with [[Jewish Leadership Council]] chairman [[Mick Davis]], [[Board of Deputies]] president [[Vivian Wineman]] and United Synagogue president Stephen Pack writing to ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' describing the statement as showing \"a shocking failure of leadership\".<ref name=\"Backlash\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/112475/limmud-backlash-over-visit-chief | title=Limmud backlash over visit by Chief | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=17 October 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref> ''The Jewish Chronicle'' itself described the statement as \"crass, ill-judged and ultimately self-defeating\".<ref name=\"Silence\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/comment-and-debate/leader/112494/chief-rabbi-mirviss-dignified-silence | title=Chief Rabbi Mirvis's dignified silence | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=17 October 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> Mirvis's attendance at the 2013 Limmud Conference was well received by fellow participants.<ref name=\"Mirvis\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jewishtelegraph.com/limmud_2.html | title=Mirvis: Great to be Jewish at Limmud | work=[[Jewish Telegraph]] | year=2013 | accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> At least nine other United Synagogue rabbis also attended the event.<ref name=\"US rabbis\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/node/114428 | title=We\u2019ll be there again next year, say US rabbis | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=2 January 2014 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Clive Lawton]]\n*[[Limmud FSU]]\n*[[Limmud International]]\n*[[Limmud South Africa]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.limmud.org Limmud] (UK parent organisation)\n\n{{British Jewry}}\n\n[[Category:1980 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Educational charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish British culture]]\n[[Category:Jewish charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish educational organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1980]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Limmud\n| logo   = Limmud_logo.png\n| type   = Jewish educational [[Charitable organization|charity]]<ref name=\"Charity\">Limmud is registered with the [[Charity Commission]] as charity no. 1083414. According to the Charity Commission, Limmud operates throughout England and Wales and also in Argentina, Australia, Austria, Belarus, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Brazil, Bulgaria, Canada, China, Croatia, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Hungary, India, Israel, Italy, Lithuania, Macedonia, Netherlands, New Zealand, Peru, Poland, Romania, Russia, Scotland, Serbia, South Africa, Sweden, Turkey, Ukraine and the United States of America.  {{cite web | url=http://www.charitycommission.gov.uk/find-charities/ | title=Limmud | publisher=[[Charity Commission]] | work=Find charities |date= 2 January 2014 |accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref>\n| founded_date      = 1980\n| founders           = [[Clive Lawton]], [[Alastair Falk]], Michael May, Jonathan Benjamin\n| location          = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| origins           = \n| key_people        = {{unbulleted list|Shoshana Bloom (Chair)<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/how-limmud-head-is-planning-for-the-future-as-the-festival-reaches-40-1.489711 | title=How Limmud head is planning for the future as the festival reaches 40 | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=4 October 2019  | accessdate=5 October 2019 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref>| Eli Ovits (Chief Executive)}}\n| area_served       = Worldwide\n| product           =\n| focus             = \n| method            = \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = \n| subsid            = \n| owner             = \n| Non-profit_slogan = Wherever you find yourself, Limmud will take you one step further on your Jewish journey\n| homepage          = {{url|https://www.limmud.org}}\n| dissolved         = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Limmud''' is a [[British Jews|British-Jewish]] educational charity<ref name=\"Charity\"/> which, in the UK, produces a large annual winter festival and several other regional events throughout the year on the theme of Jewish learning. Limmud is not affiliated to any strand of Judaism, stating \"We have no part to play in the debates between/across denominations\" in its mission statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://limmud.org/inside-limmud/about-limmud/mission-values/|title=Mission & Values|website=Limmud|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> Limmud markets itself as open to \"anyone interested in Jewish learning\".\n\nLimmud (from the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] word meaning \"to learn\")<ref name=\"Jeffay\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/dec/16/limmud | title='It's more academic than academia' | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=16 December 2008 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Jeffay, Nathan}}</ref> was originally a conference for \"educators\",<ref name=\"Jeffay\"/> basing itself on [[CAJE]], the Conference on Alternatives in Jewish Education of North America.<ref name=\"Falk interview\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/122247/the-man-leading-front-class | title=The man leading from the front of the class  | work=Interview with Alastair Falk in [[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=5 September 2014 | accessdate=5 September 2014 | author=Oliver, Charlotte}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  Taking CAJE's volunteer ethos, not paying presenters and not using people's titles, Limmud has grown to be a large international organisation. During the 1990s there was the significant change as Limmud reinvented itself as a community gathering, giving rise to a significant increase in the number of attendees and leading it to be described as \"British Jewry's greatest export\".<ref name=\"Export\">{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/week-s-end/all-jewish-all-the-time-1.335748 | title=All Jewish, all the time | work=[[Haaretz]] | date=7 January 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Harman, Danna}}</ref>  The Limmud model has now spread to many other countries.<ref name=\"Charity\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA distinctive feature of Limmud is that the events are organised by volunteers,<ref name=\" Kustanowitz \">{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/misc/iphone-article/.premium-1.557408 | title=Seven ways to disrupt a Jewish conference | work=[[Haaretz]] | date=11 November 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Kustanowitz, Esther D}}</ref><ref name=\"Tulane\">{{cite web|url=https://tulane.edu/news/newwave/030810_limmud_fest.cfm |title=\u2018Volunticipants\u2019 Needed for Jewish Fest |publisher=[[Tulane University]] |work=New Wave |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116085307/https://tulane.edu/news/newwave/030810_limmud_fest.cfm |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> who also take part as equals in what is now called the Limmud Festival.<ref name=\"Export\"/><ref name=\"Eisner\"/>  Limmud's largest group of volunteers are in their 20s and 30s.<ref name=\"Eisner\">{{cite news | url=http://forward.com/articles/190369/what-limmud-can-teach-us/ | title=What Limmud Can Teach Us | work=[[The Forward]] | date=7 January 2014 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Eisner, Jane | location=[[New York City|New York]]}}</ref> Around half of the UK \"Forty under 40\" (a community-wide initiative to identify the future leaders of British Jewry, published by ''[[Jewish News]]'') have volunteered for Limmud and a former Chair of Limmud, Elliott Goldstein, topped the list.<ref name=\"Elliott\">{{cite news | url=http://archive.totallyjewish.com/news/elliott-is-number-one/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826120511/http://archive.totallyjewish.com/news/elliott-is-number-one/ | title=Elliott is number one | url-status=dead | work=[[Jewish News]] | date=17 June 2010 | accessdate=1 January 2020 |archive-date=26 August 2016 | author=Marin, James | location=London}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nLimmud held its first conference in 1980 for 80 people organised by [[Alastair Falk]], Michael May, Jonathan Benjamin and [[Clive Lawton]], inspired by a visit to the Coalition for the Advancement of Jewish Education (CAJE) in North America. Its aim was to build bridges between professional and nonprofessional educators and between those of differing religious commitments. The next year participation had doubled and all aspects of Jewish learning were covered.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://limmud.org/inside-limmud/about-limmud/history/|title=History|website=Limmud|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nBy 1996 the main Limmud conference had expanded and moved to Oxford with attendance of over 1,000, 250 sessions and 140 speakers, becoming the largest Jewish conference in Europle. During this period the organisation also held smaller one day events in Glasgow and Leeds.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1999 the first non-UK Limmud was held in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n2006 saw Limmud appoint its first full-time Executive Director, [[Raymond Simonson]]. Prior to this Limmud had been run by part-time directors.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe late 2000s saw Limmud participation in the UK grow dramatically. In 2007 Limmud held their conference at Warwick University, with 2,000 participants and 600 at Limmud Fest, a smaller summer festival. With numbers more than doubling in 2008 to 7,000 for their UK events. International conferences were now held in [[Cape Town]], [[Johannesburg]], [[Hungary]], [[Atlanta]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Poland]], [[Stockholm]], [[Ukraine]], [[Germany]], [[Turkey]], [[Toronto]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[France]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLimmud Conference moved to [[Birmingham]] for Conference 2015, with a record 2,800 participants. New Limmud groups include [[Arizona]], [[Mar del Plata]], [[Australia]], [[Tel Aviv]], [[Chile]] and [[Essen]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018 Limmud Conference became Limmud Festival. Limmud set up affiliates in [[North America]] and [[Israel]]. Limmud estimates there are 40,000 participants annually in a Limmud worldwide, run by 4,000 volunteers. In 2017 Limmud was also awarded the [[Jerusalem Unity Prize]] for contribution to Jewish life, presented by Israeli President Rivlin.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Organisation==\nLimmud is a company and a charity. It is run by a board of directors and trustees, all of whom are volunteers. Initially, there was no difference between Limmud the organisation and Limmud Conference, the annual event, so the chairs of the Conference/Festival team were the chairs of the organisation. In 1990, a chair for the organisation who was separate from the Conference chairs was appointed for the first time. In 2006, [[Limmud International]] was created, as a separate unit within Limmud to manage relationships with other Limmud groups around the world. Limmud International was absorbed back into Limmud at the end of 2016.\n\n'''Chairs of Limmud Conference/Festival'''\n\n1980\u20131981 Alistair Falk, Michael May, Jonathan Benjamin, Clive Lawton\n\n1982\u20131984 Steve Miller\n\n1985 Tina Elliott\n\n1986 Jonathan Benjamin\n\n1987 Alan Wilkinson\n\n1988 Madeline Ismach\n\n1989 Alistair Falk\n\n1990\u20131994 Andrew Gilbert\n\n1995 Natan Tiefenbrun\n\n1996 Yvonne Krasner, Marc Soloway, Judy Trotter\n\n1997 Micah Gold, Jonny Persey, Marc Soloway\n\n1998 Micah Gold\n\n1999 Jacqueline Nicholls, Claire Straus\n\n2000 Andrew Levy, Abe Sterne\n\n2001 Claire Mandel, Carolyn Bogush\n\n2002 Juliet Simmons\n\n2003 Fleurise Luder, Eliot Kaye\n\n2004 Batya Elliott, Paul Turner\n\n2005 David Century, Shoshana Bloom\n\n2006 Jason Caplin, Natalie Grazin\n\n2007 Kevin Sefton\n\n2008 Libby Burkeman and Charles Darwish\n\n2009 Rebecca Lester and David Israel\n\n2010 Danielle Nagler and Steven Fisher\n\n2011 Shoshana Bloom and Jonathan Walters\n\n2012 David Renton\n\n2013 Oliver Marcus and Richard Verber\n\n2014 Shana Boltin and Jonathan Robinson\n\n2015 Joanna Ish-Horowicz, Michael Gladstone and Claire Samuel\n\n2016 Benjamin Crowne and Steven Weller\n\n2017 Abigail Jacobi and Anna Lawton\n\n2018 Jonathan Robinson\n\n2019 Ben Lewis, Hannah Brady and Dan Heller\n\n2020 Elliot Jebreel and Robert Simmons\n\n'''Chairs of Limmud'''\n\n1990\u20131997 Andrew Gilbert\n\n1998\u20132001 Judy Trotter\n\n1998\u20132000 Natan Tiefenbrun\n\n2001\u20132003 Claire Straus\n\n2003\u20132005 Claire Mandel\n\n2006\u20132009 Elliott Goldstein\n\n2010\u20132012 Carolyn Bogush\n\n2013\u20132015 Kevin Sefton\n\n2016\u20132019 David Hoffman\n\n2019\u2013  Shoshana Bloom\n\n'''Chairs of Limmud International'''\n\n2006\u20132009 Andrew Gilbert\n\n2010\u20132012 Uri Berkowitz, Helena Miller\n\n2013\u20132014 David Hoffman\n\n2015\u20132016 David Bilchitz<ref>{{Cite book|title=Limmud Conference / Festival handbooks|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2002\u20132017|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n'''Chair of Limmud North America'''\n\n2017\u20132019 Shep Rosenman<ref>{{Cite book|title=Limmud Conference / Festival handbooks|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2002\u20132018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n2019\u2013 Faye Rosenberg-Cohen, Sivie Twersky\n\n'''Chair of Limmud Israel'''\n\n2018\u2013 Danielle Nagler<ref name=\"Nagler\">{{cite news | url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/spotlight/times-of-israel-presents-limmud-israel-tel-aviv-after-dark-on-oct-22/ | title=Times of Israel Presents: Limmud Israel \u2014 Tel Aviv After Dark, on Oct. 22 | work=[[The Times of Israel]] | date=15 October 2018 | accessdate=30 November 2018 | author=TOI Staff}}</ref>\n\nLimmud's first professional appointment in 1998 was of [[Clive Lawton]] as part-time Executive Director; he gradually became backed by a full-time administrator. In 2006 Limmud recruited its first full-time Executive Director, [[Raymond Simonson]], former Director of UJIA Makor: The Centre for Informal Jewish Education.<ref name=\"Simonson\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/70784/limmud-leader-simonson-heads-jcc | title=Limmud leader Simonson heads for the JCC | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=2 August 2012 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Lipman, Jennifer}}</ref> When Simonson became Chief Executive of London's Jewish Community Centre,<ref name=\"Simonson\" /> now [[JW3]], in 2012, he was succeeded by Shelley Marsh.<ref name=\"Marsh\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/limmud-picks-shelley-marsh-for-top-job-1.36808 | title=Limmud picks Shelley Marsh for top job | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=4 October 2012 | accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> She stepped down from the role in 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/132571/limmud-director-steps-down | title=Limmud director steps down | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=25 March 2015 | accessdate=27 March 2015 | author=Doherty, Rosa}}</ref> Mike Schindler was the Limmud Director of Operations and the senior professional in the organisation between March and August 2015,<ref name=\"Structure\">{{cite web|url=https://limmud.org/volunteers/structure/ |title=Limmud the organisation&nbsp;\u2013 who's who |publisher=Limmud |accessdate=2 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203174601/http://limmud.org/volunteers/structure/ |archivedate= 3 February 2016 }}</ref> and then Dani Serlin was Acting Executive Director until February 2016. In February 2016, Limmud appointed the current Chief Executive, Eli Ovits, as senior professional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/2016/02/01/global/global-limmud-names-jerusalem-us-eli-ovits-as-executive-director|title=Global Limmud names Jerusalem U's Eli Ovits as executive director|date=2016-02-01|website=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Limmud events in the UK==\n===Limmud Festival===\n'''Limmud Festival''' (until 2017 known as '''Limmud Conference'''),  takes place every year in the last week of December<ref name=\" Kahn-Harris\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2010/dec/29/limmud-conference-jewish | title=Limmud: a great Jewish alternative to Christmas | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=29 December 2010 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=[[Keith Kahn-Harris|Kahn-Harris, Keith]]}}</ref> and is the organisation's [[flagship]] event.  It was inspired by the [[CAJE]] conference in the United States [http://www.caje.org/] and now attracts more than 2,000 participants annually;<ref name=\"Jeffay\"/><ref name=\" Kahn-Harris\"/> in 2015 the numbers rose to 2,750.<ref name=\"2015 pictures\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/galleries/news-galleries/limmud-2015-pictures | title=Limmud 2015 in pictures | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=31 December 2015 | accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> A typical day at Limmud Festival includes around 200 sessions spanning religious, cultural and political aspects of Jewish life.  After the first conferences at [[Carmel College (Oxfordshire)]],<ref name=\"Growth\"/> Limmud Conference has been held at [[University of Portsmouth|Portsmouth Polytechnic]] (1984),<ref name=\"Growth\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/114276/how-limmud-has-grown | title=How Limmud has grown | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=23 December 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Easterman, Daniel}}</ref> [[Oxford Brookes University]] (1986\u20131994),<ref name=\"Growth\"/> Worcester (1995\u201396), Manchester (1997), the [[University of Nottingham]] (1998\u20132006) and [[Warwick University]] (2007\u201314).<ref name=\"Growth\"/> Since 2015 this annual event has been held at the hotels surrounding Pendigo Lake, near [[Birmingham]].<ref name=\"Conference 2015\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/151538/limmuds-new-venue-should-make-year-best-conference-yet-say-organisers | title=Limmud's new venue should make this year the best conference yet, say organisers | work=[[the Jewish Chronicle]]| author=Rocker, Simon | date= 21 December 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackman \">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/127523/limmud-2014-organisers-promise-bigger-event-next-year | title=Limmud 2014: Organisers promise bigger event next year | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=31 December 2014 | accessdate=31 December 2014 |author1=Dysch, Marcus |author2=Firsht, Naomi |author3=Jackman, Josh }}</ref>\n\n===Limmud summer events===\nLimmud held a summer event in the last week of August which was called Limmud Fest from 2004 to 2012 and Limmud in the Woods from 2013 to 2016.<ref name=\"Sheinman\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/110132/limmud-goes-camping-woods | title=Limmud goes camping in the Woods | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 August 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Sheinman, Anna}}</ref> It involved camping as well as staying indoors,<ref name=\"Sheinman\"/> had a less intense programme centred on [[Shabbat]] and is more cultural and outdoors-focused than its winter sibling. Limmud Fest had a peak attendance of 650 people; Limmud in the Woods was attended by around 200\u2013250 young adults and young families.<ref name=\"Sheinman\"/>\n\n===Day and weekend Limmud events===\nThe first Day Limmud was in Sheffield in the early 1980s, followed by Leeds in the mid-1990s. Day and weekend Limmuds are now held at a number of venues in the UK, including Birmingham,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://limmud.org/day/birmingham-wm/ |title=Limmud Birmingham WM 2016 |publisher=Limmud |publication-date=2016| accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> Cambridge,<ref name=\"Cambridge 2013\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/112992/cambridge-the-rolls-royce-day-limmuds | title=Cambridge: 'The Rolls-Royce of day Limmuds' | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 November 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref><ref name=\"Cambridge 2011\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/58071/limmuds-cambridge-education-finds-a-highly-receptive-audience | title=Limmud's Cambridge education finds a highly receptive audience | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=10 November 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Josephs, Bernard}}</ref> Harrow,<ref name=\"Harrow\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/103136/hundreds-flock-harrow-limmud | title=Hundreds flock to Harrow Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 March 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Hull,<ref name=\"Hull\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.leedsjewishcommunity.com/join-in/2017/03/01/limmud-in-hull/ |title=Book your place at a unique 'pop up' day Limmud in Hull \u2013 the UK city of culture \u2013 7th May 2017 |date=1 March 2017 |publisher=Leeds Jewish Community |access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref> Leeds,<ref name=\"Leeds 2011\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/46452/leeds-loves-limmud-experience | title=Leeds loves Limmud experience | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=11 March 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Kalmus, Jonathan}}</ref><ref name=\"Leeds 2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/89997/leeds-ignites-limmud-fireworks | title=Leeds ignites Limmud fireworks | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=8 November 2012 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Fisher, John}}</ref> Liverpool,<ref name=\"Liverpool 2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/local-news/65581/limmud-shows-its-political-influences | title=Limmud shows its political influences | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=22 March 2012 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Greenberg, Sue}}</ref><ref name=\"Liverpool 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/31443/liverpool-loves-limmud | title=Liverpool loves Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=6 May 2010 | accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Manchester,<ref name=\"Manchester\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/114566/manchester-gears-its-own-limmud | title=Manchester gears up for its own Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=10 January 2014 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Kalmus, Jonathan}}</ref> and the Thames Valley.<ref name=\"Thames\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/thames-class-act-at-limmud-1.18820| title=Thames' class act at Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=14 October 2010 | accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, Limmud events have also been held in Bournemouth,<ref name=\"Bournemouth 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/32169/limmud-sunny-bournemouth | title=Limmud in Sunny Bournemouth | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=27 May 2010 | accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> Brighton,<ref name=\"Brighton 2011\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/brighton-rocks-to-the-beat-of-limmud-1.23391| title=Brighton rocks to the beat of Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=26 May 2011 | accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Glasgow,<ref name=\"Glasgow 2012\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/92788/scots-love-their-limmud | title=Scots love their Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=29 November 2012 | accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Glasgow 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/28323/scotlands-limmud-weekend | title=Scotland's Limmud weekend | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=18 February 2010 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Brickman,  Stephanie}}</ref> Hackney,<ref name=\"Hackney 2008\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/galleries/the-guest-list/a-big-crowd-flocks-hackney%E2%80%99s-first-limmud | title=A big crowd flocks to Hackney's first Limmud | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=3 October 2008 | accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref> Newcastle, South London<ref name=\"South London\">{{Cite web |url=http://limmud.org/day/south-london/ |title=South London Day Limmud \u2013 1 July 2012 |website=Limmud |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> and South East London.\n\n===Other Limmud events in UK===\nOther events run by Limmud in the UK. either on their own or in partnership with others. have included music events and the [[Florence Melton]] Adult Mini-School, organised in partnership with the [[London Jewish Cultural Centre]].\n\n==Limmuds around the world==\n{{main|Limmud International}}\nThe Limmud model has now spread to many other countries.<ref name=\"Charity\"/>  More than ninety communities in 42 countries on six continents have hosted Limmud events including, in 2013 for the first time, Hong Kong,<ref name=\"HK\">{{cite web | url=http://ejewishphilanthropy.com/hong-kong-is-finally-limmud-trending/ | title=Hong Kong is Finally Limmud Trending | publisher=eJewish Philanthropy | date=13 March 2013 | accessdate=17 February 2014 | author=Lyons, Erica}}</ref> Peru,<ref name=\"Peru\">{{cite news | url= http://www.jta.org/2013/10/15/news-opinion/world/limmud-debut-in-peru-draws-600#ixzz3FY3MkWiq | title=Limmud debut in Peru draws more than 600 | work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency | date=15 October 2013 | accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> India<ref name=\"Mumbai\">{{cite news | url=http://ejewishphilanthropy.com/first-limmud-mumbai-event-draws-jews-from-across-the-subcontinent/ | title= First Limmud Mumbai Event Draws Jews from Across the Subcontinent | work= Jewish Philanthropy | date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=8 October 2014 | author=EJP}}</ref> and Montenegro.\n\n'''UK\n'''\n[http://www.limmudbristolsw.co.uk/ Limmud Bristol SW], [http://limmud.org/day/cambridge/ Limmud Cambridge], [http://limmud.org/festival/ Limmud Festival], Limmud Harrow, [http://limmud.org/day/hull/hull/ Limmud Hull], [http://limmud.org/day/leeds/Leeds/ Limmud Leeds], [http://limmud.org/day/liverpool/ Limmud Liverpool], [http://limmud.org/day/manchester/ Limmud Manchester], [http://limmud.org/day/midlands Limmud Midlands], Limmud Scotland, Limmud Thames Valley\n\n'''Africa, Asia and Australasia'''\n\nAustralia- [http://limmudshavuot.weebly.com/ Limmud Canberra], [http://www.limmudoz.com.au/ Limmud Oz Melbourne], [http://www.facebook.com/lemidabekehila/ Limmud Oz Perth], [http://www.shalom.edu.au/shalom-programs/limmud/ Limmud Oz Sydney]<br />\n[http://limmud.org.nz/ Limmud New Zealand] <br />\n[http://www.limmudchina.org/ Limmud China]- Limmud Beijing, Limmud Shanghai <br />\n[https://www.facebook.com/groups/601703429881645/ Limmud India] <br />\n[http://www.limoud.re Limmud R\u00e9union] <br />\n[[Limmud South Africa|Limmud SA]]- Limmud Cape Cape Town, Limmud Durban, Limmud Johannesburg\n\n'''North America'''\n\nUSA- [http://limmudaz.org/ Limmud AZ], [http://www.limmudbayarea.org/ Limmud Bay Area], [http://www.limmudboca.org Limmud Boca], [https://limmudboston.org/ Limmud Boston], [http://www.limmudchi.org/ Limmud Chicago + MW], [http://www.limmudla.org/ Limmud LA], [http://www.limmudmiami.org/ Limmud Miami], [http://www.limmudmichigan.org/ Limmud Michigan], [http://www.limmudnola.org/ Limmud NOLA], [http://limmudny.org/ Limmud NY], [http://centercityjews.org/limmudphilly/ Limmud Philly], [http://www.limmudseattle.org/ Limmud Seattle], \nCanada- Limmud Kingston, [http://limmudottawa.ca Limmud Ottawa], [http://limmud.ca/ Limmud Toronto], [http://www.limmudvancouver.ca/ Limmud Vancouver], [http://www.limmudwinnipeg.org/ Limmud Winnipeg]\n\n'''Latin America'''\n\nArgentina- [http://www.limudba.org/ Limmud Buenos Aires], [http://www.limudmdq.org Limmud Mar Del Plata]\n[http://www.limmudbogota.org/ Limmud Bogota]\n[http://www.limudcaracas.com/ Limmud Caracas]\n[http://www.limud.cl/ Limmud Chile]\nLimmud Costa Rica\n[http://limudmexico.org/ Limmud Mexico]\n\n'''Europe'''\n\n[http://limmudbaltics.eu/ Limmud Baltics] (covers Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania)\n[https://www.limmud.cz/ Limmud Czech Republic- Slovak Republic]\n[https://www.facebook.com/limmudexyu/ Limmud ExYu] (covers Macedonia, Montenegro and Serbia)\n[http://www.limoud.org/ Limmud France]- Limmud Paris, Limmud Marseille\n[http://limmud.de Limmud Germany]- Limmud Berlin, Limmud Cologne, Limmud Essen, Limmud Frankfurt A.M, Limmud Freiburg, Limmud Hamburg, Limmud Munich\n[http://www.limud.fi/ Limmud Helsinki]\n[http://limmud.hu/ Limmud Hungary]\n[http://www.limmud-italia.it/ Limmud Italia] -Limmud Italia in Jerusalem\n[http://www.limmud.eu/ Limmud Keshet Bulgaria]\n[https://www.lzb.lt/limmud-lietuva-2018/ Limmud Latvia]\n[https://www.lzb.lt/limmud-lietuva-2018/ Limmud Lithuania]\n[http://www.limmoed.nl/ Limmud Netherlands]\n[http://www.oresundslimmud.org/%20http://www.oresundslimmud.se/%20http://www.oresundslimmud.dk/ Limmud Oresund] (covers Copenhagen, Lund and Malmo)\n[http://limmudpoland.org/en/ Limmud Poland]- [https://www.facebook.com/limmudwroclaw/ Limmud Wroc\u0142aw]\nSpain- [http://www.limudbarcelona.org/ Limmud Barcelona], [https://sites.google.com/view/limmud-madrid Limmud Madrid], [https://www.limudmallorca.com/ Limmud Mallorca]\n[http://limmud.se/ Limmud Stockholm]\n[http://www.limmudtr.org/ Limmud Turkey]\n[http://www.limmudwien.org/ Limmud Vienna]\n\n'''Israel'''\n\n[http://www.jewishagency.org/he/limmud-arava/content/31351 Limmud Arava]\n[http://www.limmudgalil.com/ Limmud Galil]\n[http://golan.org.il/limud/ Limmud Golan]\n[http://limmudhaifa.wixsite.com/kenes/lectures Limmud Haifa]\n[http://www.limmudjerusalem.org.il/hhome.php Limmud Jerusalem]\n[https://www.facebook.com/limmud.modiin/ Limmud Modi'in]\n[https://www.limmudtlv.org/ Limmud Tel Aviv]\n[http://www.bamidbar.org/ Limmud Yeroham]\n\n'''[[Limmud FSU]]'''\n\n[http://www.limmudfsu.by/en Limmud FSU Belarus]\n[http://www.limmudfsucanada.org/ Limmud FSU Canada]\n[http://www.limmudfsu.eu/ Limmud FSU Europe]\n[http://www.limmudfsu.org.il Limmud FSU Israel]\n[https://www.jcm.md/ru/ Limmud FSU Moldova]\n[http://www.limmud.ru/ Limmud FSU Moscow]\n[http://www.limmudfsuus.org/ Limmud FSU NY]\n[http://limmud.spb.ru/ Limmud FSU St Petersburg]\n[http://www.limmud.org.ua/ Limmud FSU Ukraine]\n[http://2015.limmudvu.ru/ Limmud FSU Volga-Urals]\n[http://westcoast.limmudfsuus.org/ Limmud FSU West Coast]\n\n'''Events based upon the Limmud concept'''\n\nSwitzerland- [http://jomijun.ch/ Jom Ijun]<br />\nRussia- [http://lsaran.org/ Lsaran]<br />\nUnited Kingdom- [http://www.nhorizons.org/events/item/british-islam-conference-18 British Islam Conference]<br />\nUnited States- [http://www.simonfamilyjcc.org/yom-limmud-mobile/ Tidewater Yom Limmud], [https://jewishnaples.org/jcdl Jewish Community Day of Learning Naples]\n\n==Relationships with Orthodoxy in Britain==\nThe former London [[United Synagogue]] [[Beth Din]]'s Head [[Dayan (rabbinic judge)]], [[Chanoch Ehrentreu]], advised Orthodox rabbis not to attend Limmud Conference.<ref name=\"Lebens\">{{cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/the-jewish-thinker/.premium-1.553846 | title=Why Orthodox rabbis shouldn\u2019t boycott Limmud | work=[[Haaretz]] | date=22 October 2013 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Lebens, Samuel}}</ref> However, in the UK many United Synagogue pulpit rabbis have attended Limmud. In December 2010 Rabbi [[Yitzchak Schochet]] of Mill Hill United Synagogue, who had been seen as a notable absentee and critic of Limmud, attended, took part in and taught at Limmud's 30th annual Conference. Following this he wrote on the synagogue's website: \"upon return all I could ask myself was, 'where was I until now?\"<ref name=\"Schochet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.shul.co.uk/readArticle.php?article=301 | title=When Lightning Didn\u2019t Strike | publisher=Mill Hill, United Synagogue | work=Rabbi's Blog | date=3 January 2011 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=[[Yitzchak Schochet|Schochet, Yitzchak]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Jonathan Sacks]] did not attend Limmud whilst being Chief Rabbi but attended when he was the head of [[Jews College]]. Sacks, when looking back on his rabbinate, considers Limmud to be one of the great successes of his time.<ref name=\"Big Think\">{{cite web | url=http://bigthink.com/videos/big-think-interview-with-lord-rabbi-jonathan-sacks | title=Big Think Interview With Lord Rabbi Jonathan Sacks | publisher=Big Think | date=12 July 2010 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Liebman, Jessica}}</ref>\n\nControversy erupted again in 2013 when newly elected Chief Rabbi [[Ephraim Mirvis]] announced his decision to attend.<ref name=\"Lebens\"/> Subsequently, a public notice signed by seven leading Orthodox rabbis including Dayan [[Chanoch Ehrentreu]] and Rabbi [[Avrohom Gurwicz]] was published in the ''[[Jewish Tribune (UK)|Jewish Tribune]]'', highly critical of pluralism and urged \"God-fearing Jews\" not to participate in Limmud.<ref name=\"Lebens\"/> This sparked condemnation by non-[[Charedi]] communal leaders, with [[Jewish Leadership Council]] chairman [[Mick Davis]], [[Board of Deputies]] president [[Vivian Wineman]] and United Synagogue president Stephen Pack writing to ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' describing the the statement as showing \"a shocking failure of leadership\".<ref name=\"Backlash\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/112475/limmud-backlash-over-visit-chief | title=Limmud backlash over visit by Chief | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=17 October 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref> ''The Jewish Chronicle'' itself described the statement as \"crass, ill-judged and ultimately self-defeating\".<ref name=\"Silence\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/comment-and-debate/leader/112494/chief-rabbi-mirviss-dignified-silence | title=Chief Rabbi Mirvis's dignified silence | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=17 October 2013 | accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> Mirvis's attendance at the 2013 Limmud Conference was well received by fellow participants.<ref name=\"Mirvis\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jewishtelegraph.com/limmud_2.html | title=Mirvis: Great to be Jewish at Limmud | work=[[Jewish Telegraph]] | year=2013 | accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> At least nine other United Synagogue rabbis also attended the event.<ref name=\"US rabbis\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thejc.com/node/114428 | title=We\u2019ll be there again next year, say US rabbis | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=2 January 2014 | accessdate=14 January 2014 | author=Rocker, Simon}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Clive Lawton]]\n*[[Limmud FSU]]\n*[[Limmud International]]\n*[[Limmud South Africa]]