{"title_page": "Simele", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|pushpin_map = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location in Iraq\n|official_name          = Simele\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            =\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  =\n|image          =\n|image_caption          = \n|population        = 71,600\n|population_as_of  = 2018\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Autonomous region\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Kurdistan Region}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krg.org/articles/detail.asp?lngnr=12&smap=03010300&rnr=140&anr=23911 |title=Kurdistan Regional Government |publisher=KRG |date= |accessdate=2012-05-21}}</ref>\n|subdivision_type2      = Governorate\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|coordinates            = {{coord|36|51|30|N|42|51|0.35|E|region:IQ|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Simele''' ({{lang-ku|S\u00eam\u00eal ,\u0633\u06ce\u0645\u06ce\u0644}})<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal asiatique |date=1910 |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 asiatique |location=Paris, France |page=131}}</ref> is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simele Massacre & the Unsung Hero of the Genocide Convention |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/07/simele-massacre-1933-assyrian-victims-still-seek-justice/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |agency=[[National Review]] |date=27 July 2018}}</ref> and [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ronald Sempill Stafford |title=The Tragedy of the Assyrian Minority in Iraq |date=1935 |page=187}}</ref> town located in the [[Dohuk Governorate|Dohuk province]] of [[Kurdistan Region]] in northern [[Iraq]]. The town is on the main road that connects [[Kurdistan Region]] to its neighbour [[Turkey]]. It is {{cvt|14|km}} west of the [[Dahuk, Iraq|city of Dohuk]].\n\n== History ==\nHistorically, the region in which Simele was a part of [[Assyria]] during its existence as a nation and then province from the 24th century BCE until the 7th century AD. The town was converted to Christianity in the 2nd century and was later famous for its [[Syriac language|Syriac]] manuscripts. Its [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] inhabitants belonged to both the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and the [[Assyrian Church of the East]].<ref name=ankawa>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e] Ankawa.com</ref> Its Assyrians inhabitants were joined by [[Yazidis]] who settled the town in 1800. Both were in turn massacred by Mir Muhammad of [[Rowanduz]]. Later on, [[Arabs|Arab]] tribes also started settling the area.<ref name=ankawa/>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Simele massacre===\n{{Main|Simele massacre}}\nThe [[Assyrian people]], who resided in Simele and its neighbouring area, were subjected to [[Simele massacre|a massacre]] on August 7, 1933, implemented by the Iraqi government. The massacre was the first state-sponsored massacre in Iraq's young history after the establishment of Iraq in 1921. An estimated 3,000 [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] died during the 1933 massacre,<ref>http://www.fidh.org/IMG/pdf/iq350a.pdf &mdash; [[FIDH]] report on ethnic cleansing in Iraq, which describes the Simele massacre in the second paragraph of page 17.</ref> most of them in the village of Simele. Thousands were forced to flee to [[Syria]] where the Assyrians went on to establish 33 villages in the [[Khabur (Euphrates)|Khabur]] plains of the [[Al-Jazira, Mesopotamia|Al Jazeera]] region, which still exist today.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Simele massacre]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n[[Category:District capitals of Iraq]]\n{{Districts of Iraq}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|pushpin_map = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location in Iraq\n|official_name          = Simele\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            =\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = <!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto                  =\n|image          =\n|image_caption          = \n|population        = 71,600\n|population_as_of  = 2018\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Autonomous region\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Kurdistan Region}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krg.org/articles/detail.asp?lngnr=12&smap=03010300&rnr=140&anr=23911 |title=Kurdistan Regional Government |publisher=KRG |date= |accessdate=2012-05-21}}</ref>\n|subdivision_type2      = Governorate\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|coordinates            = {{coord|36|51|30|N|42|51|0.35|E|region:IQ|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Simele''' ({{lang-ku|S\u00eam\u00eal ,\u0633\u06ce\u0645\u06ce\u0644}})<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal asiatique |date=1910 |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 asiatique |location=Paris, France |page=131}}</ref> is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simele Massacre & the Unsung Hero of the Genocide Convention |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/07/simele-massacre-1933-assyrian-victims-still-seek-justice/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |agency=[[National Review]] |date=27 July 2018}}</ref> and [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ronald Sempill Stafford |title=The Tragedy of the Assyrian Minority in Iraq |date=1935 |page=187}}</ref> town located in the [[Dohuk Governorate|Dohuk province]] of [[Kurdistan Region]] in northern [[Iraq]]. The town is on the main road that connects [[Kurdistan Region]] to its neighbour [[Turkey]]. It is {{cvt|14|km}} west of the [[Dahuk, Iraq|city of Dohuk]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe town was mentioned by [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]] as \"Simwel\" which is thought to be a corruption of the Syriac ''Simm\u0101l\u0101'' ({{lang|syr|\u0723\u0721\u0720\u0710}}) meaning \"left\". Another possible origin could be the Syriac ''Shem\u02bb\u0113l'' ({{lang|syc|\u072b\u0721\u0725 \u0710\u071d\u0720}}), which means \"the name of God\".<ref>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e], Ankawa.com {{in lang|ar}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\nHistorically, the region in which Simele was a part of [[Assyria]] during its existence as a nation and then province from the 24th century BCE until the 7th century AD. The town was converted to Christianity in the 2nd century and was later famous for its [[Syriac language|Syriac]] manuscripts. Its [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] inhabitants belonged to both the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and the [[Assyrian Church of the East]].<ref name=ankawa>[http://www.ankawa.com/forum/index.php?topic=105353.0 \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e] Ankawa.com</ref> Its Assyrians inhabitants were joined by [[Yazidis]] who settled the town in 1800. Both were in turn massacred by Mir Muhammad of [[Rowanduz]]. Later on, [[Arabs|Arab]] tribes also started settling the area.<ref name=ankawa/>{{better source needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Simele massacre===\n{{Main|Simele massacre}}\nThe [[Assyrian people]], who resided in Simele and its neighbouring area, were subjected to [[Simele massacre|a massacre]] on August 7, 1933, implemented by the Iraqi government. The massacre was the first state-sponsored massacre in Iraq's young history after the establishment of Iraq in 1921. An estimated 3,000 [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] died during the 1933 massacre,<ref>http://www.fidh.org/IMG/pdf/iq350a.pdf &mdash; [[FIDH]] report on ethnic cleansing in Iraq, which describes the Simele massacre in the second paragraph of page 17.</ref> most of them in the village of Simele. Thousands were forced to flee to [[Syria]] where the Assyrians went on to establish 33 villages in the [[Khabur (Euphrates)|Khabur]] plains of the [[Al-Jazira, Mesopotamia|Al Jazeera]] region, which still exist today.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Simele massacre]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n[[Category:District capitals of Iraq]]\n{{Districts of Iraq}}\n", "name_user": "Sems\u00fbr\u00ee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtymology:based on a forum source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simele"}
{"title_page": "Changi Airport MRT station", "text_new": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox station\n| background = \n| name = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Changi Airport\n  | zhname = \u6a1f\u5b9c\u673a\u573a\n  | taname = \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\n  | msname = Changi Airport \n  | line = EAST WEST\n  | line2 = Silom\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n  | terminicode = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 3.png|25px]] \n}}\n| type = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit (MRT)]] station\n| image = File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Platform A.jpg\n| image_caption = Changi Airport station platform level\n| address = 70 Airport Boulevard<br />Singapore 819661\n| coordinates = {{Coord|1|21|26.54|N|103|59|19.81|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}\n| other = [[Changi Airport Bus Terminal]], Taxi\n| structure = Underground\n| platform = 2 ([[1 island platform]])\n| depth = \n| levels = 1\n| tracks = 2\n| parking = Yes ([[Changi Airport]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]])\n| bicycle = Yes ([[Changi Airport]])\n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = {{start date and age|df=yes|2002|02|08}}\n| opening = {{start date and age|df=yes|2040}} ([[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]])\n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = Yes\n| ADA = Yes\n| code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n| owned = \n| operator = [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (East West and Thomson\u2013East Coast lines)\n| zone = \n| former = \n| services = {{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|branch=Changi|previous=Expo|''Terminus''}}\n| mpassengers = \n| map_locator = {{Superimpose| base = MRT map EW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = East West line\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Changi Airport MRT station\n | x = 224\n | y = 69\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Changi Airport MRT station (CG2)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station and the eastern terminus of the [[East West MRT line|East West line]]'s Changi Airport Branch. The station is located in [[Changi]], [[Singapore]], within [[Singapore Changi Airport]], and is built in an East-West direction with the two ends of the station connecting directly to Changi Airport Terminals 2 and 3. It is also one of the few stations, where faregates are on the same level as the platforms. As the only MRT Station to serve the Changi planning area, it is currently the easternmost MRT station in Singapore until the opening of the [[Aviation Park MRT station]] in 2029.\n\nDuring the construction of Terminal 3, ideas have been put forth to build a new branch line connecting to and around the airport. The current two-station branch line was finalised in 1996 and construction started on 1999. The station opened on 8 February 2002, with passenger demand lower than expected. Nevertheless, it has provided a new transport option to the airport. On 25 May 2019, it was announced that the station will be incorporated as part of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]], connecting to Changi Airport Terminal 5 by 2040.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-stations-tel-extension-and-possible-new-rail-line-lta-2040-blueprint|title=New MRT stations, line extensions and a possible new rail line: LTA's 2040 blueprint|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Changi MRT.JPG|left|thumb|Changi Airport MRT station, featuring flight information box in addition to train route information]]\n[[File:CG1 changi airport faregates.jpg|left|thumb|Changi Airport is one of the few stations where faregates are on the same level as the platforms.]]\nBefore the MRT line, Changi Airport had been operating with no [[Airport rail link|rail link]] and with full reliance on [[Taxicabs of Singapore|taxi]] and [[Bus transport in Singapore|bus connections]] since the airport began operations in 1981. This has proven effective given the short 20 kilometre distance to the city via the [[East Coast Parkway]] and affordability of taxis and buses. Public buses instead link commuters to nearby MRT stations at [[Bedok MRT station|Bedok]], [[Tampines MRT station|Tampines]] and [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]]. Therefore, there were previously unsuccessful attempts to propose an extension to Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT Link to Airport: Not in next 10 years|date=17 May 1991|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=No MRT Line to Changi yet|date=20 March 1992|work=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of extending the Mass Rapid Transit system to Changi Airport was reconsidered when Terminal 3 was being built.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT extension to airport reconsidered.|date=2 August 1994|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The earlier plans had long been made for a new line branching off from the existing [[East West MRT line|East West line]] at [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Next Stop:Changi Airport?|date=2 August 1994|work=The New Paper}}</ref> with some conceptual plans showing a tentative route alignment up to the airport along Airport Boulevard, continuing beyond the airport to Changi Point, before turning southwest back towards the city along the east coast of the island. The plans were finally announced by then [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] on 15 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore Mass Rapid Transit Employees' Union (SMRTEU)'s annual Dinner and Dance  |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1996111503/lhl19961115s.pdf |website=NAS |accessdate=10 July 2019 |date=15 November 1996}}</ref> However, the route alignment showed a deviation from previous plans. The final plan involved building only the first two stations, namely [[Expo MRT station|Expo]], and the Changi Airport station, the underground station built between Terminal 2 and [[Changi Airport Terminal 3|Terminal 3]]. The alignment of the station at the airport has been switched perpendicularly to an east\u2013west direction, such that the station leads to two of the terminals directly from either end of the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19961212-1.2.51.7 |title=MRT Line will not go beyond passenger terminals |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=12 December 1996}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=changi+airport+mrt&KA=changi+airport+mrt&DF=02%2F01%2F1990&DT=01%2F09%2F2010&Display=0&NPT=&L=English&CTA=Article|title=Changi Airport MRT line details|date=12 December 1996|work=The Business Times|access-date=}}</ref> As part of the President's Challenge 2001, a part of a charity walk goes through the tunnel between Expo and Changi Airport stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Lim|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Chairty walk to talk place underground|date=12 August 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Perfectly legal, and for a good cause!|date=9 September 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Terence|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Tunnel walk a hit|date=9 September 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nThe Contract 504 for the construction of Changi Airport MRT station and its associated tunnels was awarded to Kumagai-Sembawang Joint Venture in October 1998. This project was a joint effort which combines Japanese technology and experience with local knowledge of subcontractor availability, supplier availability, due to the challanges of the construction of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.jsce.or.jp/jsce/open/00035/2001/56-cs/56-cs-0266.pdf|title=Underpinning Works in Construction of MRT Changi Airport Station in Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A groundbreaking ceremony was held on 29 January 1999. In the speech by then-communications minister [[Mah Bow Tan]] at the ceremony, he highlighted the challenges of the construction of the station, which requires close cooperation between various parties such as the [[Land Transport Authority]] (LTA), the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore]] (CAAS) and the contractors. For the construction of Changi Airport station, different methods of deep excavations using various ground support systems were adopted. The construction work involved the challenge of deep excavation works right next to nearby developments such as the existing Terminal 2 structures.<ref name=\"Excavations\">{{Cite book|last=Murugamoorthy|first=C.|title=Behaviour of Various Support Systems for Deep Excavations, Changi Airport Underground MRT Station|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In addition, closing monitoring is needed for the construction of the {{convert|1|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} tunnel leading to the station, which goes directly underneath the runway and airport terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1999012901.htm|title=Speech By Mr Mah Bow Tan, At The Changi Airport Line Ground Breaking Ceremony, 29 Jan 99, 10 am, Singapore Changi Airport|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During the construction, [[CPG Corporation|CPG Consultants]], which was designing Terminal 3 at the time, provided 20 staff to complement the LTA team on the Changi Airport line extension.<ref name=\"CPG consultants\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpgcorp.com.sg/cpgc/Project/Project_Details?ProjectID=1312|title=CPG Consultants - Changi Airport Mass Rapid Transit Station (MRT)|website=www.cpgcorp.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nThe station opened on 8 February 2002,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Completion%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension/|title=Completion Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Airport MRT stop to open tomorrow|date=7 February 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with the official opening ceremony of the Changi Airport MRT extension conducted on 27 February 2002.<ref name=\"Speech 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension%20on%2027%20February%202002/|title=Speech By Mr Yeo Cheow Tong At The Opening Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension on 27 February 2002|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since the station's opening, passenger traffic has been moderate, as most bus routes were maintained and continue to be a popular means of cheap, direct transport for local airport/airline employees, as well as travellers not living along the East West line. Many air travellers also prefer to continue taking taxis or private transport as not all of the MRT services have luggage racks in the trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Chew|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Taxi still the way to go for Changi air travellers|date=26 August 2002|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> However, taxi drivers claimed that the station have actually put them at a disadvantage, reporting a loss of 20 percent in earnings. By then, there are about 20,500 commuters travelling the station daily.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phei Phei|first=Leong|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20020311-2.2.4.11?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article&QT=changi,airport,station&oref=article|title=Airport woes for cabbies|date=11 March 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial numbering of the station was EW29, but was changed on 20 June 2003 to CG2.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=What SMRT said earlier|date=8 August 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Incorporation into the TEL===\nOn 25 May 2019, the [[Land Transport Authority]] announced an extension of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]] (TEL) to Changi Airport.  Set to be completed by 2040, The TEL will be extended from its current terminus at [[Sungei Bedok MRT station]] to serve the future Changi Airport Terminal 5, and the stretch between Tanah Merah and Changi Airport, which is currently part of the East-West line, will be transferred over to the Thomson\u2013East Coast line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents===\n*On 24 July 2002, a glass panel of the atria wall shattered. The area was quickly closed off, but train services were not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 July 2002 |publisher=[[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]] |access-date=16 January 2018 |quote=At 12.05pm, a piece of tempered glass at the atria wall in the Changi Airport MRT Station shattered into small fragments. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135244/https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |archive-date=16 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Joint%20Press%20Release%20By%20Land%20Transport%20Authority%20And%20Singapore%20MRT%20Ltd%20Atria%20Wall%20In%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station/|title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n*On 24 September that year, a man died at the station, apparently having fallen five stories from the departure hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20030925-2.2.11.1|title=Man Dies at Changi Airport|date=25 September 2003|work=TODAY}}</ref>\n\n*On 17 January 2020, the rail operator SMRT said that it had found a crack in the crossing at Changi Airport MRT Station, found during inspection works in the morning. Trains have to be diverted to only one platform and have to travel at a slower speed as they approach the affected crossing.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/slower-train-service-changi-airport-mrt-station-until-jan-21-after-crack-spotted-track|title=Slower train service to Changi Airport MRT Station until Jan 21, after crack spotted on track|date=17 January 2020|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Station details and design==\n[[File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Exit A.jpg|thumb|The panes of the glass Astria seen from Exit A to the station.]]\nVarious features have been incorporated into the design to make the station aesthetically pleasing to travellers.<ref name=\"Speech 1\"/> The station is designed by American architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]], featuring a large interior space and a {{convert|150|metre|ft}} linkbridge spanning over the platform, connecting Terminals 2 and 3 with travellators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgtrains.com/network-ewl.html|title=East-West Line|website=SGTrains|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Meinhardt also provided structural design engineering of the glazing system and the tensioned cable structure of the two atria (approximately 60m long by 20m wide by 36m high each) located at both end of the station box adjacent to Terminal 2 and 3 of Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meinhardt.com.sg/projects/changi-airport-glass-atria/|title=Changi Airport Glass Atria {{!}} Meinhardt \u2013 Transforming Cities, Shaping the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nChangi Airport station is currently served by the [[East West MRT line|East West line]], which connects to the airport from [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah station]] as a shuttle service. Initially, after the station was first opened, there were through services from [[Boon Lay MRT station|Boon Lay station]] to this station.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boon Lay to Expo: MRT now running|date=20 December 2001|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> However, due to low ridership, the route reverted to being operated as a shuttle service from 22 July that year, with trains from Changi Airport station terminating at Tanah Merah station instead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Board MRT to airport from Tanah Merah.|date=18 July 2003|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The first train from Changi Airport station departs at 5.31 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.59 am on Sundays instead, with the last train from the airport departing at 12.06 am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Changi Airport)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> From Tanah Merah station, the first train towards the station departs at 5.20 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.47 am on Sundays instead, with the last train towards the airport from Tanah Merah station departing at 11.50 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/tanah-merah/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Tanah Merah)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Headway]] between trains varies from 7 \u2013 9 mins during peak hours, and 12 mins during off-peak hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/|title=Changi Airport MRT Station {{!}} Land Transport Guru|date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the future, the station will be served by the TEL as part of the TEL extension to the airport.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Changi Airport MRT Station}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/ChangiAirport.aspx}}\n* [http://blog.smrt.com.sg/?p=159 Official blogsite]\n* [http://www.mynetbizz.com/MRT/To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/HarbourFront-To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station.cfm HarbourFront to Changi Airport MRT station route]\n* [http://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/ Changi Airport MRT Station,Land Transport Guru]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Changi Airport MRT station}}\n[[Category:Changi]]\n[[Category:Airport railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2002]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Singapore]]\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 350268 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 61111 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 403 us -->\n\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 6083007 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73546 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 925 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 338330 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 60129 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 416 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 410717 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73630 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 861 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 321675 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 56806 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 409 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n", "text_old": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox station\n| background = \n| name = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Changi Airport\n  | zhname = \u6a1f\u5b9c\u673a\u573a\n  | taname = \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\n  | msname = Changi Airport \n  | line = EAST WEST\n  | line2 = Silom\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n  | terminicode = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 3.png|25px]] \n}}\n| type = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit (MRT)]] station\n| image = File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Platform A.jpg\n| image_caption = Changi Airport station platform level\n| address = 70 Airport Boulevard<br />Singapore 819661\n| coordinates = {{Coord|1|21|26.54|N|103|59|19.81|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}\n| other = [[Changi Airport Bus Terminal]], Taxi\n| structure = Underground\n| platform = 2 ([[1 island platform]])\n| depth = \n| levels = 1\n| tracks = 2\n| parking = Yes ([[Changi Airport]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]])\n| bicycle = Yes ([[Changi Airport]])\n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = {{start date and age|df=yes|2002|02|08}}\n| opening = {{start date and age|df=yes|2040}} ([[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]])\n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = Yes\n| ADA = Yes\n| code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n| owned = \n| operator = [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (East West and Thomson\u2013East Coast lines)\n| zone = \n| former = \n| services = {{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|branch=Changi|previous=Expo|''Terminus''}}\n| mpassengers = \n| map_locator = {{Superimpose| base = MRT map EW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = East West line\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Changi Airport MRT station\n | x = 224\n | y = 69\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Changi Airport MRT station (CG2)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station and the eastern terminus of the [[East West MRT line|East West line]]'s Changi Airport Branch. The station is located in [[Changi]], [[Singapore]], within [[Singapore Changi Airport]], and is built in an East-West direction with the two ends of the station connecting directly to Changi Airport Terminals 2 and 3. It is also one of the few stations, where faregates are on the same level as the platforms. As the only MRT Station to serve the Changi planning area, it is currently the easternmost MRT station in Singapore until the opening of the [[Aviation Park MRT station]] in 2029.\n\nDuring the construction of Terminal 3, ideas have been put forth to build a new branch line connecting to and around the airport. The current two-station branch line was finalised in 1996 and construction started on 1999. The station opened on 8 February 2002, with passenger demand lower than expected. Nevertheless, it has provided a new transport option to the airport. On 25 May 2019, it was announced that the station will be incorporated as part of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]], connecting to Changi Airport Terminal 5 by 2040.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-stations-tel-extension-and-possible-new-rail-line-lta-2040-blueprint|title=New MRT stations, line extensions and a possible new rail line: LTA's 2040 blueprint|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Changi MRT.JPG|left|thumb|Changi Airport MRT station, featuring flight information box in addition to train route information]]\n[[File:CG1 changi airport faregates.jpg|left|thumb|Changi Airport is one of the few stations where faregates are on the same level as the platforms.]]\nBefore the MRT line, Changi Airport had been operating with no [[Airport rail link|rail link]] and with full reliance on [[Taxicabs of Singapore|taxi]] and [[Bus transport in Singapore|bus connections]] since the airport began operations in 1981. This has proven effective given the short 20 kilometre distance to the city via the [[East Coast Parkway]] and affordability of taxis and buses. Public buses instead link commuters to nearby MRT stations at [[Bedok MRT station|Bedok]], [[Tampines MRT station|Tampines]] and [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]]. Therefore, there were previously unsuccessful attempts to propose an extension to Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT Link to Airport: Not in next 10 years|date=17 May 1991|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=No MRT Line to Changi yet|date=20 March 1992|work=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of extending the Mass Rapid Transit system to Changi Airport was reconsidered when Terminal 3 was being built.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT extension to airport reconsidered.|date=2 August 1994|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The earlier plans had long been made for a new line branching off from the existing [[East West MRT line|East West line]] at [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Next Stop:Changi Airport?|date=2 August 1994|work=The New Paper}}</ref> with some conceptual plans showing a tentative route alignment up to the airport along Airport Boulevard, continuing beyond the airport to Changi Point, before turning southwest back towards the city along the east coast of the island. The plans were finally announced by then [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] on 15 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore Mass Rapid Transit Employees' Union (SMRTEU)'s annual Dinner and Dance  |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1996111503/lhl19961115s.pdf |website=NAS |accessdate=10 July 2019 |date=15 November 1996}}</ref> However, the route alignment showed a deviation from previous plans. The final plan involved building only the first two stations, namely [[Expo MRT station|Expo]], and the Changi Airport station, the underground station built between Terminal 2 and [[Changi Airport Terminal 3|Terminal 3]]. The alignment of the station at the airport has been switched perpendicularly to an east\u2013west direction, such that the station leads to two of the terminals directly from either end of the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19961212-1.2.51.7 |title=MRT Line will not go beyond passenger terminals |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=12 December 1996}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=changi+airport+mrt&KA=changi+airport+mrt&DF=02%2F01%2F1990&DT=01%2F09%2F2010&Display=0&NPT=&L=English&CTA=Article|title=Changi Airport MRT line details|date=12 December 1996|work=The Business Times|access-date=}}</ref> As part of the President's Challenge 2001, a part of a charity walk goes through the tunnel between Expo and Changi Airport stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Lim|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Chairty walk to talk place underground|date=12 August 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Perfectly legal, and for a good cause!|date=9 September 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Terence|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Tunnel walk a hit|date=9 September 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nThe Contract 504 for the construction of Changi Airport MRT station and its associated tunnels was awarded to Kumagai-Sembawang Joint Venture in October 1998. This project was a joint effort which combines Japanese technology and experience with local knowledge of subcontractor availability, supplier availability, due to the challanges of the construction of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.jsce.or.jp/jsce/open/00035/2001/56-cs/56-cs-0266.pdf|title=Underpinning Works in Construction of MRT Changi Airport Station in Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A groundbreaking ceremony was held on 29 January 1999. In the speech by then-communications minister [[Mah Bow Tan]] at the ceremony, he highlighted the challenges of the construction of the station, which requires close cooperation between various parties such as the [[Land Transport Authority]] (LTA), the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore]] (CAAS) and the contractors. For the construction of Changi Airport station, different methods of deep excavations using various ground support systems were adopted. The construction work involved the challenge of deep excavation works right next to nearby developments such as the the existing Terminal 2 structures.<ref name=\"Excavations\">{{Cite book|last=Murugamoorthy|first=C.|title=Behaviour of Various Support Systems for Deep Excavations, Changi Airport Underground MRT Station|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In addition, closing monitoring is needed for the construction of the {{convert|1|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} tunnel leading to the station, which goes directly underneath the runway and airport terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1999012901.htm|title=Speech By Mr Mah Bow Tan, At The Changi Airport Line Ground Breaking Ceremony, 29 Jan 99, 10 am, Singapore Changi Airport|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During the construction, [[CPG Corporation|CPG Consultants]], which was designing Terminal 3 at the time, provided 20 staff to complement the LTA team on the Changi Airport line extension.<ref name=\"CPG consultants\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpgcorp.com.sg/cpgc/Project/Project_Details?ProjectID=1312|title=CPG Consultants - Changi Airport Mass Rapid Transit Station (MRT)|website=www.cpgcorp.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nThe station opened on 8 February 2002,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Completion%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension/|title=Completion Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Airport MRT stop to open tomorrow|date=7 February 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with the official opening ceremony of the Changi Airport MRT extension conducted on 27 February 2002.<ref name=\"Speech 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension%20on%2027%20February%202002/|title=Speech By Mr Yeo Cheow Tong At The Opening Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension on 27 February 2002|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since the station's opening, passenger traffic has been moderate, as most bus routes were maintained and continue to be a popular means of cheap, direct transport for local airport/airline employees, as well as travellers not living along the East West line. Many air travellers also prefer to continue taking taxis or private transport as not all of the MRT services have luggage racks in the trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Chew|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Taxi still the way to go for Changi air travellers|date=26 August 2002|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> However, taxi drivers claimed that the station have actually put them at a disadvantage, reporting a loss of 20 percent in earnings. By then, there are about 20,500 commuters travelling the station daily.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phei Phei|first=Leong|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20020311-2.2.4.11?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article&QT=changi,airport,station&oref=article|title=Airport woes for cabbies|date=11 March 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial numbering of the station was EW29, but was changed on 20 June 2003 to CG2.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=What SMRT said earlier|date=8 August 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Incorporation into the TEL===\nOn 25 May 2019, the [[Land Transport Authority]] announced an extension of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]] (TEL) to Changi Airport.  Set to be completed by 2040, The TEL will be extended from its current terminus at [[Sungei Bedok MRT station]] to serve the future Changi Airport Terminal 5, and the stretch between Tanah Merah and Changi Airport, which is currently part of the East-West line, will be transferred over to the Thomson\u2013East Coast line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents===\n*On 24 July 2002, a glass panel of the atria wall shattered. The area was quickly closed off, but train services were not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 July 2002 |publisher=[[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]] |access-date=16 January 2018 |quote=At 12.05pm, a piece of tempered glass at the atria wall in the Changi Airport MRT Station shattered into small fragments. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135244/https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |archive-date=16 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Joint%20Press%20Release%20By%20Land%20Transport%20Authority%20And%20Singapore%20MRT%20Ltd%20Atria%20Wall%20In%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station/|title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n*On 24 September that year, a man died at the station, apparently having fallen five stories from the departure hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20030925-2.2.11.1|title=Man Dies at Changi Airport|date=25 September 2003|work=TODAY}}</ref>\n\n*On 17 January 2020, the rail operator SMRT said that it had found a crack in the crossing at Changi Airport MRT Station, found during inspection works in the morning. Trains have to be diverted to only one platform and have to travel at a slower speed as they approach the affected crossing.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/slower-train-service-changi-airport-mrt-station-until-jan-21-after-crack-spotted-track|title=Slower train service to Changi Airport MRT Station until Jan 21, after crack spotted on track|date=17 January 2020|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Station details and design==\n[[File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Exit A.jpg|thumb|The panes of the glass Astria seen from Exit A to the station.]]\nVarious features have been incorporated into the design to make the station aesthetically pleasing to travellers.<ref name=\"Speech 1\"/> The station is designed by American architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]], featuring a large interior space and a {{convert|150|metre|ft}} linkbridge spanning over the platform, connecting Terminals 2 and 3 with travellators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgtrains.com/network-ewl.html|title=East-West Line|website=SGTrains|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Meinhardt also provided structural design engineering of the glazing system and the tensioned cable structure of the two atria (approximately 60m long by 20m wide by 36m high each) located at both end of the station box adjacent to Terminal 2 and 3 of Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meinhardt.com.sg/projects/changi-airport-glass-atria/|title=Changi Airport Glass Atria {{!}} Meinhardt \u2013 Transforming Cities, Shaping the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nChangi Airport station is currently served by the [[East West MRT line|East West line]], which connects to the airport from [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah station]] as a shuttle service. Initially, after the station was first opened, there were through services from [[Boon Lay MRT station|Boon Lay station]] to this station.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boon Lay to Expo: MRT now running|date=20 December 2001|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> However, due to low ridership, the route reverted to being operated as a shuttle service from 22 July that year, with trains from Changi Airport station terminating at Tanah Merah station instead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Board MRT to airport from Tanah Merah.|date=18 July 2003|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The first train from Changi Airport station departs at 5.31 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.59 am on Sundays instead, with the last train from the airport departing at 12.06 am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Changi Airport)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> From Tanah Merah station, the first train towards the station departs at 5.20 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.47 am on Sundays instead, with the last train towards the airport from Tanah Merah station departing at 11.50 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/tanah-merah/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Tanah Merah)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Headway]] between trains varies from 7 \u2013 9 mins during peak hours, and 12 mins during off-peak hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/|title=Changi Airport MRT Station {{!}} Land Transport Guru|date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the future, the station will be served by the TEL as part of the TEL extension to the airport.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Changi Airport MRT Station}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/ChangiAirport.aspx}}\n* [http://blog.smrt.com.sg/?p=159 Official blogsite]\n* [http://www.mynetbizz.com/MRT/To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/HarbourFront-To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station.cfm HarbourFront to Changi Airport MRT station route]\n* [http://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/ Changi Airport MRT Station,Land Transport Guru]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Changi Airport MRT station}}\n[[Category:Changi]]\n[[Category:Airport railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2002]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Singapore]]\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 350268 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 61111 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 403 us -->\n\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 6083007 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73546 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 925 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: